{"title_page": "Personal area network", "text_new": "{{short description|Computer network centered on an individual person's workspace}}\n\n{{Area networks}}\n\nA '''personal area network''' ('''PAN''') is a [[computer network]] for interconnecting [[electronic devices]]  centered on an individual person's workspace.<ref name=\"Gratton2013\">{{cite book |last1=Gratton |first1=Dean A. |title=The Handbook of Personal Area Networking Technologies and Protocols |date=2013 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=9780521197267 |pages=15\u201318 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1aE0AAAAQBAJ&dq=personal+area+network&source=gbs_navlinks_s |accessdate=12 December 2018 |language=en}}</ref> A PAN provides [[data transmission]] among devices such as [[computer]]s, [[smartphone]]s, [[Tablet computer|tablets]] and [[personal digital assistant]]s. PANs can be used for communication among the personal devices themselves, or for connecting to a higher level network and the Internet where one master device takes up the role as [[Gateway (telecommunications)|gateway]]. A PAN may be wireless or carried over wired interfaces such as [[USB]].\n\nA '''wireless personal area network''' ('''WPAN''') is a PAN carried over a low-powered, short-distance [[wireless network]] technology such as [[Infrared Data Association|IrDA]], [[Wireless USB]], [[Bluetooth]] or [[ZigBee]]. The reach of a WPAN varies from a few centimeters to a few meters.\n\n==Wired==\nWired personal area networks provide short connections between peripherals. Example technologies include:\n*\n*\n*\n\n==Wireless==\nA wireless personal area network (WPAN) is a personal area network in which the connections are wireless. [[IEEE 802.15]] has produced standards for several types of PANs operating in the [[ISM band]] including [[Bluetooth]]. The [[Infrared Data Association]] has produced standards for WPANs which operate using [[infrared communication]]s.\n\n===Bluetooth===\n[[Bluetooth]] uses short-range radio waves. Uses in a WPAN include, for example, Bluetooth devices such as keyboards, pointing devices, audio head sets, printers may connect to [[smartwatch]]es, [[cell phone]]s, or computers. A Bluetooth WPAN is also called a ''[[piconet]]'', and is composed of up to 8 active devices in a master-slave relationship (a very large number of additional devices can be connected in \"parked\" mode). The first Bluetooth device in the piconet is the master, and all other devices are slaves that communicate with the master. A piconet typically has a range of {{convert|10|m}}, although ranges of up to {{convert|100|m}} can be reached under ideal circumstances. Long-range Bluetooth routers with augmented antenna arrays connect Bluetooth devices up to 1,000 feet.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iotworldtoday.com/2017/09/11/cassia-networks-secures-patent-long-range-bluetooth/|title=Long-range Bluetooth: Cassia Networks secures patent|website=www.iotworldtoday.com}}</ref>\n\nWith [[Bluetooth mesh networking]] the range and number of devices is extended by using [[mesh networking]] techniques to relay information from one to another. Such a network doesn't have a master device and may or may not be treated as a WPAN.<ref>{{cite web|last=Boxall |first=Andy |url=https://www.digitaltrends.com/mobile/bluetooth-5-release-news/ |title=Faster, Longer, And More Capacious: Bluetooth 5 Is Here |publisher=Digital Trends |date=2016-12-08 |accessdate=2019-12-18}}</ref>\n\n===IrDA===\n[[Infrared Data Association]] (IrDA) uses [[infrared]] light, which has a frequency below the human eye's sensitivity. Infrared is used in other wireless communications applications, for instance, in [[remote control]]s. Typical WPAN devices that use IrDA include printers, keyboards, and other [[serial communication]] interfaces.<ref>Charles D. Knutson with Jeffrey M. Brown, IrDA Principles and Protocols, 2004, {{ISBN|0-9753892-0-3}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Telecommunication}}\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n* [[6LoWPAN]]\n* [[Ambient network]]s\n* [[DASH7]]\n* [[IEEE 802.15]]\n* [[Internalnet]]\n* [[Microchip implant (human)]]\n* [[RuBee]]\n* [[Ultra-wideband]] and [[FM-UWB]] networks\n* [[Wireless ad hoc network]] (WANET)\n* [[Z-Wave]]\n* [[ZigBee]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.ieee802.org/15/ IEEE 802.15 Working Group for WPAN]\n\n{{Internet access}}\n{{Telecommunications}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Personal Area Network}}\n[[Category:Wireless networking]]\n[[Category:Personal area networks]]\n[[Category:Bluetooth]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Computer network centered on an individual person's workspace}}\n\n{{Area networks}}\n\nA '''personal area network''' ('''PAN''') is a [[computer network]] for interconnecting [[electronic devices]]  centered on an individual person's workspace.<ref name=\"Gratton2013\">{{cite book |last1=Gratton |first1=Dean A. |title=The Handbook of Personal Area Networking Technologies and Protocols |date=2013 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=9780521197267 |pages=15\u201318 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1aE0AAAAQBAJ&dq=personal+area+network&source=gbs_navlinks_s |accessdate=12 December 2018 |language=en}}</ref> A PAN provides [[data transmission]] among devices such as [[computer]]s, [[smartphone]]s, [[Tablet computer|tablets]] and [[personal digital assistant]]s. PANs can be used for communication among the personal devices themselves, or for connecting to a higher level network and the Internet where one master device takes up the role as [[Gateway (telecommunications)|gateway]]. A PAN may be wireless or carried over wired interfaces such as [[USB]].\n\nA '''wireless personal area network''' ('''WPAN''') is a PAN carried over a low-powered, short-distance [[wireless network]] technology such as [[Infrared Data Association|IrDA]], [[Wireless USB]], [[Bluetooth]] or [[ZigBee]]. The reach of a WPAN varies from a few centimeters to a few meters.\n\n==Wired==\nWired personal area networks provide short connections between peripherals. Example technologies include:\n*[[USB]]\n*[[IEEE-1394]]\n*[[Thunderbolt (interface)]]\n\n==Wireless==\nA wireless personal area network (WPAN) is a personal area network in which the connections are wireless. [[IEEE 802.15]] has produced standards for several types of PANs operating in the [[ISM band]] including [[Bluetooth]]. The [[Infrared Data Association]] has produced standards for WPANs which operate using [[infrared communication]]s.\n\n===Bluetooth===\n[[Bluetooth]] uses short-range radio waves. Uses in a WPAN include, for example, Bluetooth devices such as keyboards, pointing devices, audio head sets, printers may connect to [[smartwatch]]es, [[cell phone]]s, or computers. A Bluetooth WPAN is also called a ''[[piconet]]'', and is composed of up to 8 active devices in a master-slave relationship (a very large number of additional devices can be connected in \"parked\" mode). The first Bluetooth device in the piconet is the master, and all other devices are slaves that communicate with the master. A piconet typically has a range of {{convert|10|m}}, although ranges of up to {{convert|100|m}} can be reached under ideal circumstances. Long-range Bluetooth routers with augmented antenna arrays connect Bluetooth devices up to 1,000 feet.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iotworldtoday.com/2017/09/11/cassia-networks-secures-patent-long-range-bluetooth/|title=Long-range Bluetooth: Cassia Networks secures patent|website=www.iotworldtoday.com}}</ref>\n\nWith [[Bluetooth mesh networking]] the range and number of devices is extended by using [[mesh networking]] techniques to relay information from one to another. Such a network doesn't have a master device and may or may not be treated as a WPAN.<ref>{{cite web|last=Boxall |first=Andy |url=https://www.digitaltrends.com/mobile/bluetooth-5-release-news/ |title=Faster, Longer, And More Capacious: Bluetooth 5 Is Here |publisher=Digital Trends |date=2016-12-08 |accessdate=2019-12-18}}</ref>\n\n===IrDA===\n[[Infrared Data Association]] (IrDA) uses [[infrared]] light, which has a frequency below the human eye's sensitivity. Infrared is used in other wireless communications applications, for instance, in [[remote control]]s. Typical WPAN devices that use IrDA include printers, keyboards, and other [[serial communication]] interfaces.<ref>Charles D. Knutson with Jeffrey M. Brown, IrDA Principles and Protocols, 2004, {{ISBN|0-9753892-0-3}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Telecommunication}}\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n* [[6LoWPAN]]\n* [[Ambient network]]s\n* [[DASH7]]\n* [[IEEE 802.15]]\n* [[Internalnet]]\n* [[Microchip implant (human)]]\n* [[RuBee]]\n* [[Ultra-wideband]] and [[FM-UWB]] networks\n* [[Wireless ad hoc network]] (WANET)\n* [[Z-Wave]]\n* [[ZigBee]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.ieee802.org/15/ IEEE 802.15 Working Group for WPAN]\n\n{{Internet access}}\n{{Telecommunications}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Personal Area Network}}\n[[Category:Wireless networking]]\n[[Category:Personal area networks]]\n[[Category:Bluetooth]]\n", "name_user": "2001:d08:1a01:2c26:1:0:ca19:5966", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Personal_area_network"}
{"title_page": "Geoff Baker", "text_new": "{{About||the British field marshal|Geoffrey Baker|the New Zealand cricketer|Geoffrey Baker (cricketer)}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Geoff Baker\n| image         = <!-- just the filename, without the File: or Image: prefix or enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date    = \n| birth_place   = [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]]\n| death_date    = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} or {{Death-date and age|death date\u2020|birth date\u2020}} -->\n| death_place   = \n| nationality   =\n| residence     = [[Seattle, Washington]]\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = [[Journalist]]\n| years_active  = 1987&ndash;present\n| known_for     = \n| notable_works =\n}}\n'''Geoff Baker''' is an award-winning Canadian-born journalist currently working as an NHL writer and columnist while also doubling as a sports enterprise and investigative reporter.<ref>https://www.seattletimes.com/author/geoff-baker/</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBaker currently resides in [[Seattle, Washington]], with his wife, Amy.\n\n==Early life and education==\nBaker was born in [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]], and raised in the suburb of [[Laval, Quebec]]. A graduate of Chomedey High School, Baker played football for the Vanier College Cheetahs<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vaniercollege.qc.ca/athletics/footballfactory/gaz_story.html|title=Vanier Lauded in Gazette as Prime Football Talent Breeding Ground|work=Vaniercollege.qc.ca|accessdate=18 February 2015}}</ref> (CEGEP) 1987 provincial championship football team<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vaniercollege.qc.ca/athletics/images/football-alumni/all-time-list-football-cheetahs.pdf |format=PDF |title=All-Time Roster Cheetahs (1971-2014) : Football Collegial AA-AAA |publisher=Vaniercollege.qc.ca |accessdate=18 February 2015}}</ref> and attended training camp with the Concordia University Stingers as a slot receiver in 1989.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://neatesager.blogspot.com/2009/03/batter-up-seattle-mariners.html|title=Out Of Left Field|author=Rob Pettapiece|work=neatesager.blogspot.com}}</ref>\n\n==Journalism career==\nAfter summer internships at the Toronto Star and The Gazette in Montreal, Baker was hired full-time by The Gazette as a night police reporter in 1991.\n\n==Awards and recognition==\nIn Canada, Baker won the country's National Newspaper Award three times in 1994 (spot news), 1997 (sports) and 2005 (sports) and was a top-three finalist in 1992 (spot news).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nna-ccj.ca/award-archives/list-of-winners-since-1949/|title=Winners since 1949|work=National Newspaper Awards}}</ref> The final award, in 2005, was for a series on steroids use by young baseball players in the Dominican Republic. Those stories also helped Baker become the first Canadian to win an Associated Press Sports Editors (APSE) award in the highest-newspaper-circulation category.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://seattletimes.com/html/localnews/2003241567_fancher03.html |title=The Seattle Times: Local News: Times sports department recruits 3 top reporters |work=seattletimes.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150210042339/http://seattletimes.com/html/localnews/2003241567_fancher03.html |archivedate=2015-02-10 }}</ref>\n\nBaker won a second APSE award,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://apsportseditors.org/newsletter/geoff-baker-of-the-seattle-times-wins-apse-over-175k-explanatory-contest/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2015-04-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151205091628/http://apsportseditors.org/newsletter/geoff-baker-of-the-seattle-times-wins-apse-over-175k-explanatory-contest/ |archive-date=2015-12-05 |url-status=dead }}</ref> with the Seattle Times, in 2014 for a story about troubled indoor soccer owner Dion Earl. He has been a finalist for seven other APSE prizes with the Times, in 2006,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.apsportseditors.org/contest/2006/writing/writing.100-250.html|title=APSE - Associated Press Sports Editors|author=The Dallas Morning News|work=apsportseditors.org|access-date=2014-12-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150210041403/http://archive.apsportseditors.org/contest/2006/writing/writing.100-250.html|archive-date=2015-02-10|url-status=dead}}</ref> 2009,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://apsportseditors.org/newsletter/final-results-for-writing-categories-of-the-apse-contest/ |title=APSE |author=Indiana University School of Journalism |work=apsportseditors.org |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150210041404/http://apsportseditors.org/newsletter/final-results-for-writing-categories-of-the-apse-contest/ |archivedate=2015-02-10 }}</ref> 2010,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://seattletimes.com/html/othersports/2014714741_apse08.html |title=Other Sports - Times reporters Geoff Baker, Larry Stone earn APSE writing awards - Seattle Times Newspaper |work=The Seattle Times |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150210042432/http://seattletimes.com/html/othersports/2014714741_apse08.html |archivedate=2015-02-10 }}</ref> 2013,.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://seattletimes.com/html/othersports/2023134195_apseawards16xml.html |title=Geoff Baker, Seattle Times Sports sections earn honors from APSE |work=The Seattle Times |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150210044917/http://seattletimes.com/html/othersports/2023134195_apseawards16xml.html |archivedate=2015-02-10 }}</ref> and 2015.<ref>http://www.seattletimes.com/sports/seattle-times-earns-apse-grand-slam-among-11-top-10-awards/</ref>\n\n==1998 Tim Johnson controversy and firing==\nUpon joining the Toronto Star in June 1998, Baker became aware that manager [[Tim Johnson (baseball)|Tim Johnson]] had talked to players about serving in the U.S. Marine Corps and fighting overseas during the Vietnam War. But Baker knew Johnson had not served overseas and the manager quickly claimed he'd never told such stories to players or coaches. On Sept. 23, 1998, Baker wrote an initial story describing a rift amongst team coaches and a heated bar argument between them over Johnson's fake Vietnam stories. A much-larger, feature-length follow-up story on Oct. 18, 1998 quoted players on and off the record about having been told Vietnam stories by Johnson. The most damaging quotes came from former Cy Young Award winner Pat Hentgen, who described Johnson telling him about his Vietnam hardships while on the field at Fenway Park before a series with the Red Sox. Johnson had just told Hentgen he would not be starting in what was then a crucial series for the Blue Jays.\n\nJohnson continued to deny he'd told such stories until a Boston Globe column by Will McDonough in November 1998 mentioned that Johnson had told such war stories while serving as a Red Sox bench coach a few years earlier.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0evrQMx81r4C&pg=PA45-IA1&lpg=PA45-IA1&dq=geoff+baker+tim+johnson&source=bl&ots=fu3797lrDN&sig=y6tJIFE4iu5yWm5A7ux9dfQJU7g&hl=en&sa=X&ei=U6KQVKH7CoPloASUpoGQBQ&ved=0CE8Q6AEwCA#v=onepage&q=geoff%20baker%20tim%20johnson&f=false|title=100 Things Blue Jays Fans Should Know & Do Before They Die|work=google.com}}</ref> A few weeks later, at the 1998 baseball winter meetings in Nashville, Johnson held a press conference admitting he'd lied about serving in the war. The Blue Jays allowed Johnson to stay on as manager (he'd won 88 games his only season in 1998) but fired him in spring training when it became clear players no longer respected him.\n\n==2003 White Jays controversy==\nOn June 28, 2003, the Toronto Star ran a Baker story and accompanying sidebar under an A-1 front-page banner titled \"The White Jays?\" along with accompanying headshots of the 25 players on the Toronto Blue Jays baseball team. The stories themselves were about how the team had taken a decisive turn away from Latin American players and towards U.S.-born products after international scouting cutbacks under the regime of GM J.P. Ricciardi.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.majorwager.com/forums/mess-hall/122525-article-toronto-blue-jays-whitest-team-majors.html|title=ARTICLE...TORONTO BLUE JAYS: Whitest team in the majors - MajorWager Forums|work=majorwager.com}}</ref>\n\nThe front-page treatment of the stories sparked a widespread outcry in Toronto and more than 2,000 letters to the editor, to this day a record for Canada's largest newspaper.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rrj.ca/big-push-big-error/|title=Big Push, Big Error|work=Ryerson Review of Journalism :: The Ryerson School of Journalism}}</ref> Moneyball author Michael Lewis wrote about the series as part of a Sports Illustrated feature<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.si.com/vault/2004/03/01/363830/out-of-their-tree-the-author-wrote-a-book-moneyball-that-drove-baseballs-clubby-traditionalists-crazy-they-fought-back-now-he-does-too|title=Out Of Their Tree The author wrote a book, Moneyball, that drove baseball's clubby traditionalists crazy. They fought back. Now he does too|work=SI.com}}</ref> that was later re-published as an afterward in the paperback version of his best-selling book.\n\nThe Toronto Star's ombudsman investigated and found no issue with the content of Baker's stories,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsombudsmen.org/columns/pitch-at-jays-high-and-wide |title=Pitch at Jays: High and wide\u2026 |work=newsombudsmen.org |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150210041629/http://newsombudsmen.org/columns/pitch-at-jays-high-and-wide |archivedate=2015-02-10 }}</ref> but did criticize the paper's editors for their packaging of the story and front page treatment. Baker later wrote a follow up feature on the Blue Jays and their Latin American cutbacks in October 2005. This time, without the racially charged front-page treatment of the 2003 \"White Jays\" stories, the work by Baker was well-received, despite containing much the same subject matter.\n\n==2004 Carlos Delgado controversy==\nOn July 4, 2004, the Toronto Star published \"Citizen Carlos\":<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.puertorico-herald.org/issues/2004/vol8n28/CitizenCarlos.html |title=Citizen Carlos; Jays' Delgado Fights For Justice For The People Of A Small Puerto Rican Island Vieques Ravaged By Six Decades Of U.S. Weapons Testing, Writes Geoff Baker |publisher=Puerto Rico Herald |accessdate=2015-02-18 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080706044740/http://www.puertorico-herald.org/issues/2004/vol8n28/CitizenCarlos.html |archivedate=2008-07-06 }}</ref> a Baker-penned feature from Puerto Rico about how Blue Jays slugger Carlos Delgado was no longer standing on the field during the playing of God Bless America. Delgado had shared with Baker that he was silently protesting the U.S. invasion of Iraq. The Baker feature described Delgado's work with activists on the Puerto Rican island of Vieques and the fact that it had been the testing ground for uranium depleted shells dropped by the U.S. military on Iraq.\n\nThe story was later picked up by the New York Times<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/07/21/sports/baseball/21rhoden.html|title=Delgado Makes a Stand by Taking a Seat|date=21 July 2004|work=nytimes.com}}</ref> and other U.S. news outlets,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politicalaffairs.net/blue-jays-slugger-carlos-delgado-stands-up-to-war/|title=Blue Jays Slugger Carlos Delgado Stands Up to War|work=politicalaffairs.net}}</ref> causing Delgado to be booed on subsequent trips to New York<ref>{{cite web|url=https://articles.latimes.com/2004/jul/25/sports/sp-dogwilstein25|title=Patriotism, Protest at Yankee Stadium|work=Los Angeles Times}}</ref> to play the Yankees or Mets. Upon joining the Mets in 2006, Delgado addressed the situation and agreed to stand on the field with teammates when God Bless America was played, saying he'd made his point and did not wish to cause distractions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenation.com/article/silencing-carlos-delgado|title=The Silencing of Carlos Delgado|work=thenation.com}}</ref>\n\n==2005 Dominican steroids stories==\nIn April 2005, Baker and Toronto Star photographer Peter Power traveled to the Dominican Republic, where they spent a week touring the country's needle-ridden baseball fields to do a pair of feature stories on PED use by teenage prospects from that country.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metro.us/news/baker-s-insight-will-be-missed-by-fans/tmWfhq---66epp9chfaxVk/|title=Baker\u2019s insight will be missed by fans|author=Marty York|date=17 October 2014|work=Metro}}</ref> The groundbreaking series described the use of cheaper farm animal supplements as steroids alternatives and also produced an expos\u00e9 of the country's \"buscones\"\u2014street-level hustlers grooming prospects for bigger paydays in the U.S.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zreportage.com/zrep_text.html?storypath=2010/zrep063|title=zReportage ~ Story 063 - Complete Text|work=zreportage.com}}</ref>\n\nBaker won his third National Newspaper Award in Canada for the stories.<ref>{{cite web|last=Citizen |first=Ottawa |url=http://www.canada.com/story_print.html?id=30d5a3a0-ba68-4b7c-bb95-49b6088c493c&sponsor= |title=Citizen wins National Newspaper Awards |publisher=Canada.com |date=2006-05-26 |accessdate=2015-02-18 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160322220955/http://www.canada.com/story_print.html?id=30d5a3a0-ba68-4b7c-bb95-49b6088c493c&sponsor= |archivedate=2016-03-22 }}</ref> He also became the first Canadian to win an APSE Award in the United States, in the highest newspaper circulation category.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.apsportseditors.org/2006/oct2006/101406moves.html|title=APSE - Associated Press Sports Editors|author=The Dallas Morning News|work=apsportseditors.org|access-date=2014-12-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150210041317/http://archive.apsportseditors.org/2006/oct2006/101406moves.html|archive-date=2015-02-10|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe aftermath of the series led to Baker being hired by the Seattle Times. He has since traveled to Venezuela to write about steroids testing there<ref>{{cite web|url=http://seattletimes.com/html/mariners/2003404352_steroids12.html |title=The Seattle Times: Mariners: Growing pains: Venezuela deals with steroid testing |work=seattletimes.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150210045501/http://seattletimes.com/html/mariners/2003404352_steroids12.html |archivedate=2015-02-10 }}</ref> and was invited to speak at an October 2006 sports conference in Caracas<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.seattletimes.com/mariners/2011/11/10/only_surprise_in_wilson_ramos/|title=Only surprise in Wilson Ramos kidnapping is that it doesn't happen more often|work=The Seattle Times}}</ref> about the exploitation faced by Latin American ballplayers.\n\nA photograph by Power from the Toronto Star series, of a young Dominican throwing a baseball in a sugar cane field,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gettyimages.com/search/2/image?phrase=165322118&family=editorial|title=165322118 Pictures & News Photos - Getty Images|work=gettyimages.com}}</ref> his bicycle perched against a tree in the foreground, was used by filmmaker Ken Burns to illustrate the opening of the Dominican portion of his 2010 baseball documentary, The Tenth Inning.\n\n==2010 Josh Lueke controversy==\nThe Mariners made a blockbuster July 2010 trade of ace pitcher Cliff Lee to the Texas Rangers for Justin Smoak and three prospects, one of them a relief pitcher named Josh Lueke. There were reports all over Google about how Lueke had pleaded no contest to a charge of false imprisonment with violence after being arrested for rape and sodomy in 2008. At first, the Mariners, known for their \"family friendly\" image and support of a \"Refuse to Abuse\" campaign pertaining to violence against women, denied knowing about Lueke's background and added it was too late to reverse the trade or do anything further other than let Lueke play.\n\nBut on September 1, 2010, Baker published an A-1 story<ref>{{cite web|url=http://seattletimes.com/html/mariners/2012784518_lueke02.html |title=Mariners - Coach says Mariners were told of Josh Lueke's criminal past - Seattle Times Newspaper |work=The Seattle Times |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140810090900/http://seattletimes.com/html/mariners/2012784518_lueke02.html |archivedate=2014-08-10 }}</ref> disputing that version of events. Baker quoted Rick Adair, a former Mariners pitching coach\u2014who'd also been in charge of minor league pitchers in Texas in 2008\u2014saying he'd warned GM Jack Zduriencik all about Lueke's troubled past before the trade was made. The story also quoted Rangers GM Jon Daniels saying he'd offered Zduriencik a chance to give Lueke back and take another player, but that he refused to do so.\n\nThe Mariners have never commented on the discrepancy between their initial statements and the version presented by the sources named in Baker's story. In September 2010, they fired Carmen Fusco, their head of professional scouting.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.seattletimes.com/mariners/2010/09/13/mariners_confirm_firing_of_pro/|title=Mariners|work=The Seattle Times}}</ref> Fusco has since said he was made a scapegoat in the affair.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sportspressnw.com/2171994/2013/thiel-is-there-a-bottom-to-mariners-free-fall|title=Thiel: Is there a bottom to Mariners\u2019 free-fall?|work=Sportspress Northwest}}</ref>\n\nThe story finished in 4th place in voting for an APSE award for Explanatory Reporting. It won a regional SPJ award for Sports Reporting in the Pacific Northwest.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://seattletimes.com/html/localnews/2015117317_apspjawards3rdld2ndad.html |title=Local News - SPJ Awards      - Seattle Times Newspaper |work=The Seattle Times |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150210043608/http://seattletimes.com/html/localnews/2015117317_apspjawards3rdld2ndad.html |archivedate=2015-02-10 }}</ref>\n\n==2013 Eric Wedge/Mariners controversy==\nAfter a 16-year career as an MLB beat writer, Baker launched his new career as a sports investigative reporter with a Dec. 8, 2013 feature story about the dysfunction permeating the upper levels of the Seattle Mariners hierarchy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://seattletimes.com/html/mariners/2022420240_mariners08xml.html |title=Dysfunction at the top:  Eric Wedge, others point to trouble in Mariners\u2019 front office |work=The Seattle Times |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141216132907/http://seattletimes.com/html/mariners/2022420240_mariners08xml.html |archivedate=2014-12-16 }}</ref> Baker specifically addressed the reasons why manager Eric Wedge had walked out on the team in September, leaving a $2 million contract extension on the table. Using on-the-record quotes from Wedge, Baker painted a dysfunctional situation brought about by Mariners CEO Howard Lincoln, resident Chuck Armstrong and GM Jack Zduriencik. The story also quoted former Mariners GM assistant Tony Blengino saying he'd drawn up Zduriencik's entire resume and had helped falsely portray him as an expert in advanced statistics in order to get the job.\n\nThe story was nominated for an APSE award for Explanatory Reporting.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://apsportseditors.org/newsletter/apse-2013-contest-explanatory-over-175/|title=APSE|author=Indiana University School of Journalism|work=apsportseditors.org|access-date=2014-12-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150210041318/http://apsportseditors.org/newsletter/apse-2013-contest-explanatory-over-175/|archive-date=2015-02-10|url-status=dead}}</ref> It won a regional SPJ Award for Sports Reporting in the Pacific Northwest.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://health-city.com/2013-spj-northwest-awards/|title=2013 SPJ Northwest awards|work=health-city.com}}</ref>\n\n==2016 Controversy Over NBA Arena Reporting ==\nBaker's reporting on the proposed SoDo arena in the Stadium District of Seattle drew criticism from the SB Nation website Sonics Rising, a group of Seattle area fans lobbying for the return of NBA basketball. The site has campaigned openly for the city to support hedge fund operator Chris Hansen in efforts to build a public-subsidized arena and private sports and entertainment development in SoDo.<ref>{{Cite web\n| url = http://seattle.curbed.com/2016/2/23/11096656/the-seattle-times-really-does-not-like-chris-hansens-sodo-arena-plan\n| title = The Seattle Times Really Does Not Like Chris Hansen's SoDo Arena Plan\n| website = Curbed Seattle\n| access-date = 2016-02-24\n}}</ref> On February 22, 2016, Baker and the Editorial Board of The Seattle Times were accused by Seattle city councilman Tim Burgess of misreporting facts to suit personal bias against the arena. The allegation came via a memo introduced by Burgess in council after a front-page story by Baker suggesting council members delayed publicizing a report by architectural firm AECOM in 2015 that concluded KeyArena could be remodeled for NBA and NHL use.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Seattle councilmembers rip Times' reporting on arena studies|url = http://www.king5.com/story/news/local/seattle/2016/02/22/seattle-councilmembers-rip-times-reporting-arena-studies/80778798/|website = KING5|access-date = 2016-02-23}}</ref> Sonics Rising and two local bloggers used the occasion to again accuse Baker of biased reporting. They referenced a story of Baker's from the previous November about M.T. Phoenix, a company that offered to help finance a KeyArena renovation. The city never responded to or investigated the legitimacy of M.T. Phoenix and claimed that it legally could not entertain offers pertaining to KeyArena. The city later rebuffed a separate offer from businessman Victor Coleman, who was interested in a KeyArena renovation. Follow up stories on M.T. Phoenix, including one by Baker, found the M.T. Phoenix website contained inconsistencies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sonicsrising.com/2015/11/16/9746820/seattle-times-mt-phoenix-keyarena|title=Seattle Times Introduced us to M.T. Phoenix|work=SB Nation}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sonicsrising.com/2015/11/18/9754636/seattle-times-credibility-story-discredited-arena|title=Seattle Times Reporter Scrambling for Credibility|work=SB Nation}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Paper's Petty Personal Vendetta Impeding SoDo Arena|url = http://seattlesportsnet.com/2016/02/22/papers-petty-personal-vendetta-impeding-sodo-arena/|website = Seattle Sportsnet|access-date = 2016-02-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Thiel: Stop with the KeyArena remodel talk {{!}} Sportspress Northwest|url = http://sportspressnw.com/2215368/2016/thiel-stop-with-the-keyarena-remodel-talk|website = Sportspress Northwest|access-date = 2016-02-23}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the Burgess memo claiming inaccuracies in Baker's ensuing story in February, the newspaper met with Burgess. Seattle Times editor Kathy Best afterwards issued a statement <ref>http://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/about-the-seattle-times-arena-coverage/</ref> that he'd provided no example of factual errors in Baker's reporting and that no corrections would be made. Subsequent stories by Seattle Weekly <ref>http://archive.seattleweekly.com/home/963218-129/whos-winning-the-great-city-hall-seattle</ref> and the national Field of Schemes <ref>http://www.fieldofschemes.com/2016/03/02/10697/seattle-council-did-too-ignore-possibility-of-renovating-keyarena-says-seattle-weekly-report/</ref> website concluded that Baker's story had been correct in finding discrepancies between the AECOM report and the city's claim that KeyArena could not be remodeled for NBA and NHL. Both also found no merit to the Burgess claim of factual inaccuracies in Baker's story. Baker, in a follow-up report in April 2016, showed city hall officials had worried ahead of time that the AECOM report on KeyArena contradicted a city-issued environmental study on Hansen's Sodo arena.<ref>http://www.seattletimes.com/sports/city-worried-about-clashing-keyarena-reports-then-delayed-one/</ref> On May 2, 2016, the city voted against selling a public street so Hansen could build the arena, effectively stopping the project. Baker's arena stories earned him a finalist nod for a 2016 APSE award in investigative reporting.\n\nOn September 12, 2017, the City of Seattle and [[Oak View Group]] agreed on a $600 million deal to renovate KeyArena for NBA and NHL teams.<ref>http://www.seattletimes.com/sports/nba/oak-view-group-plans-to-renovate-keyarena-by-october-2020-spend-40-million-on-transportation-fund/</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Baker, Geoff}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Anglophone Quebec people]]\n[[Category:Canadian male journalists]]\n[[Category:Journalists from Quebec]]\n[[Category:People from Montreal]]\n", "text_old": "{{About||the British field marshal|Geoffrey Baker|the New Zealand cricketer|Geoffrey Baker (cricketer)}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Geoff Baker\n| image         = <!-- just the filename, without the File: or Image: prefix or enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date    = \n| birth_place   = [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]]\n| death_date    = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} or {{Death-date and age|death date\u2020|birth date\u2020}} -->\n| death_place   = \n| nationality   =\n| residence     = [[Seattle, Washington]]\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = [[Journalist]]\n| years_active  = 1987&ndash;present\n| known_for     = \n| notable_works =\n}}\n'''Geoff Baker''' is an award-winning Canadian-born journalist currently working as an NHL writer and columnist while also doubling as a sports enterprise and investigative reporter.<ref>https://www.seattletimes.com/author/geoff-baker/</ref>.\n\n==Personal life==\nBaker currently resides in [[Seattle, Washington]], with his wife, Amy.\n\n==Early life and education==\nBaker was born in [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]], and raised in the suburb of [[Laval, Quebec]]. A graduate of Chomedey High School, Baker played football for the Vanier College Cheetahs<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vaniercollege.qc.ca/athletics/footballfactory/gaz_story.html|title=Vanier Lauded in Gazette as Prime Football Talent Breeding Ground|work=Vaniercollege.qc.ca|accessdate=18 February 2015}}</ref> (CEGEP) 1987 provincial championship football team<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vaniercollege.qc.ca/athletics/images/football-alumni/all-time-list-football-cheetahs.pdf |format=PDF |title=All-Time Roster Cheetahs (1971-2014) : Football Collegial AA-AAA |publisher=Vaniercollege.qc.ca |accessdate=18 February 2015}}</ref> and attended training camp with the Concordia University Stingers as a slot receiver in 1989.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://neatesager.blogspot.com/2009/03/batter-up-seattle-mariners.html|title=Out Of Left Field|author=Rob Pettapiece|work=neatesager.blogspot.com}}</ref>\n\n==Journalism career==\nAfter summer internships at the Toronto Star and The Gazette in Montreal, Baker was hired full-time by The Gazette as a night police reporter in 1991.\n\n==Awards and recognition==\nIn Canada, Baker won the country's National Newspaper Award three times in 1994 (spot news), 1997 (sports) and 2005 (sports) and was a top-three finalist in 1992 (spot news).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nna-ccj.ca/award-archives/list-of-winners-since-1949/|title=Winners since 1949|work=National Newspaper Awards}}</ref> The final award, in 2005, was for a series on steroids use by young baseball players in the Dominican Republic. Those stories also helped Baker become the first Canadian to win an Associated Press Sports Editors (APSE) award in the highest-newspaper-circulation category.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://seattletimes.com/html/localnews/2003241567_fancher03.html |title=The Seattle Times: Local News: Times sports department recruits 3 top reporters |work=seattletimes.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150210042339/http://seattletimes.com/html/localnews/2003241567_fancher03.html |archivedate=2015-02-10 }}</ref>\n\nBaker won a second APSE award,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://apsportseditors.org/newsletter/geoff-baker-of-the-seattle-times-wins-apse-over-175k-explanatory-contest/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2015-04-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151205091628/http://apsportseditors.org/newsletter/geoff-baker-of-the-seattle-times-wins-apse-over-175k-explanatory-contest/ |archive-date=2015-12-05 |url-status=dead }}</ref> with the Seattle Times, in 2014 for a story about troubled indoor soccer owner Dion Earl. He has been a finalist for seven other APSE prizes with the Times, in 2006,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.apsportseditors.org/contest/2006/writing/writing.100-250.html|title=APSE - Associated Press Sports Editors|author=The Dallas Morning News|work=apsportseditors.org|access-date=2014-12-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150210041403/http://archive.apsportseditors.org/contest/2006/writing/writing.100-250.html|archive-date=2015-02-10|url-status=dead}}</ref> 2009,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://apsportseditors.org/newsletter/final-results-for-writing-categories-of-the-apse-contest/ |title=APSE |author=Indiana University School of Journalism |work=apsportseditors.org |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150210041404/http://apsportseditors.org/newsletter/final-results-for-writing-categories-of-the-apse-contest/ |archivedate=2015-02-10 }}</ref> 2010,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://seattletimes.com/html/othersports/2014714741_apse08.html |title=Other Sports - Times reporters Geoff Baker, Larry Stone earn APSE writing awards - Seattle Times Newspaper |work=The Seattle Times |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150210042432/http://seattletimes.com/html/othersports/2014714741_apse08.html |archivedate=2015-02-10 }}</ref> 2013,.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://seattletimes.com/html/othersports/2023134195_apseawards16xml.html |title=Geoff Baker, Seattle Times Sports sections earn honors from APSE |work=The Seattle Times |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150210044917/http://seattletimes.com/html/othersports/2023134195_apseawards16xml.html |archivedate=2015-02-10 }}</ref> and 2015. <ref>http://www.seattletimes.com/sports/seattle-times-earns-apse-grand-slam-among-11-top-10-awards/</ref>\n\n==1998 Tim Johnson controversy and firing==\nUpon joining the Toronto Star in June 1998, Baker became aware that manager [[Tim Johnson (baseball)|Tim Johnson]] had talked to players about serving in the U.S. Marine Corps and fighting overseas during the Vietnam War. But Baker knew Johnson had not served overseas and the manager quickly claimed he'd never told such stories to players or coaches. On Sept. 23, 1998, Baker wrote an initial story describing a rift amongst team coaches and a heated bar argument between them over Johnson's fake Vietnam stories. A much-larger, feature-length follow-up story on Oct. 18, 1998 quoted players on and off the record about having been told Vietnam stories by Johnson. The most damaging quotes came from former Cy Young Award winner Pat Hentgen, who described Johnson telling him about his Vietnam hardships while on the field at Fenway Park before a series with the Red Sox. Johnson had just told Hentgen he would not be starting in what was then a crucial series for the Blue Jays.\n\nJohnson continued to deny he'd told such stories until a Boston Globe column by Will McDonough in November 1998 mentioned that Johnson had told such war stories while serving as a Red Sox bench coach a few years earlier.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0evrQMx81r4C&pg=PA45-IA1&lpg=PA45-IA1&dq=geoff+baker+tim+johnson&source=bl&ots=fu3797lrDN&sig=y6tJIFE4iu5yWm5A7ux9dfQJU7g&hl=en&sa=X&ei=U6KQVKH7CoPloASUpoGQBQ&ved=0CE8Q6AEwCA#v=onepage&q=geoff%20baker%20tim%20johnson&f=false|title=100 Things Blue Jays Fans Should Know & Do Before They Die|work=google.com}}</ref> A few weeks later, at the 1998 baseball winter meetings in Nashville, Johnson held a press conference admitting he'd lied about serving in the war. The Blue Jays allowed Johnson to stay on as manager (he'd won 88 games his only season in 1998) but fired him in spring training when it became clear players no longer respected him.\n\n==2003 White Jays controversy==\nOn June 28, 2003, the Toronto Star ran a Baker story and accompanying sidebar under an A-1 front-page banner titled \"The White Jays?\" along with accompanying headshots of the 25 players on the Toronto Blue Jays baseball team. The stories themselves were about how the team had taken a decisive turn away from Latin American players and towards U.S.-born products after international scouting cutbacks under the regime of GM J.P. Ricciardi.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.majorwager.com/forums/mess-hall/122525-article-toronto-blue-jays-whitest-team-majors.html|title=ARTICLE...TORONTO BLUE JAYS: Whitest team in the majors - MajorWager Forums|work=majorwager.com}}</ref>\n\nThe front-page treatment of the stories sparked a widespread outcry in Toronto and more than 2,000 letters to the editor, to this day a record for Canada's largest newspaper.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rrj.ca/big-push-big-error/|title=Big Push, Big Error|work=Ryerson Review of Journalism :: The Ryerson School of Journalism}}</ref> Moneyball author Michael Lewis wrote about the series as part of a Sports Illustrated feature<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.si.com/vault/2004/03/01/363830/out-of-their-tree-the-author-wrote-a-book-moneyball-that-drove-baseballs-clubby-traditionalists-crazy-they-fought-back-now-he-does-too|title=Out Of Their Tree The author wrote a book, Moneyball, that drove baseball's clubby traditionalists crazy. They fought back. Now he does too|work=SI.com}}</ref> that was later re-published as an afterward in the paperback version of his best-selling book.\n\nThe Toronto Star's ombudsman investigated and found no issue with the content of Baker's stories,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsombudsmen.org/columns/pitch-at-jays-high-and-wide |title=Pitch at Jays: High and wide\u2026 |work=newsombudsmen.org |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150210041629/http://newsombudsmen.org/columns/pitch-at-jays-high-and-wide |archivedate=2015-02-10 }}</ref> but did criticize the paper's editors for their packaging of the story and front page treatment. Baker later wrote a follow up feature on the Blue Jays and their Latin American cutbacks in October 2005. This time, without the racially charged front-page treatment of the 2003 \"White Jays\" stories, the work by Baker was well-received, despite containing much the same subject matter.\n\n==2004 Carlos Delgado controversy==\nOn July 4, 2004, the Toronto Star published \"Citizen Carlos\":<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.puertorico-herald.org/issues/2004/vol8n28/CitizenCarlos.html |title=Citizen Carlos; Jays' Delgado Fights For Justice For The People Of A Small Puerto Rican Island Vieques Ravaged By Six Decades Of U.S. Weapons Testing, Writes Geoff Baker |publisher=Puerto Rico Herald |accessdate=2015-02-18 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080706044740/http://www.puertorico-herald.org/issues/2004/vol8n28/CitizenCarlos.html |archivedate=2008-07-06 }}</ref> a Baker-penned feature from Puerto Rico about how Blue Jays slugger Carlos Delgado was no longer standing on the field during the playing of God Bless America. Delgado had shared with Baker that he was silently protesting the U.S. invasion of Iraq. The Baker feature described Delgado's work with activists on the Puerto Rican island of Vieques and the fact that it had been the testing ground for uranium depleted shells dropped by the U.S. military on Iraq.\n\nThe story was later picked up by the New York Times<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/07/21/sports/baseball/21rhoden.html|title=Delgado Makes a Stand by Taking a Seat|date=21 July 2004|work=nytimes.com}}</ref> and other U.S. news outlets,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politicalaffairs.net/blue-jays-slugger-carlos-delgado-stands-up-to-war/|title=Blue Jays Slugger Carlos Delgado Stands Up to War|work=politicalaffairs.net}}</ref> causing Delgado to be booed on subsequent trips to New York<ref>{{cite web|url=https://articles.latimes.com/2004/jul/25/sports/sp-dogwilstein25|title=Patriotism, Protest at Yankee Stadium|work=Los Angeles Times}}</ref> to play the Yankees or Mets. Upon joining the Mets in 2006, Delgado addressed the situation and agreed to stand on the field with teammates when God Bless America was played, saying he'd made his point and did not wish to cause distractions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenation.com/article/silencing-carlos-delgado|title=The Silencing of Carlos Delgado|work=thenation.com}}</ref>\n\n==2005 Dominican steroids stories==\nIn April 2005, Baker and Toronto Star photographer Peter Power traveled to the Dominican Republic, where they spent a week touring the country's needle-ridden baseball fields to do a pair of feature stories on PED use by teenage prospects from that country.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metro.us/news/baker-s-insight-will-be-missed-by-fans/tmWfhq---66epp9chfaxVk/|title=Baker\u2019s insight will be missed by fans|author=Marty York|date=17 October 2014|work=Metro}}</ref> The groundbreaking series described the use of cheaper farm animal supplements as steroids alternatives and also produced an expos\u00e9 of the country's \"buscones\"\u2014street-level hustlers grooming prospects for bigger paydays in the U.S.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zreportage.com/zrep_text.html?storypath=2010/zrep063|title=zReportage ~ Story 063 - Complete Text|work=zreportage.com}}</ref>\n\nBaker won his third National Newspaper Award in Canada for the stories.<ref>{{cite web|last=Citizen |first=Ottawa |url=http://www.canada.com/story_print.html?id=30d5a3a0-ba68-4b7c-bb95-49b6088c493c&sponsor= |title=Citizen wins National Newspaper Awards |publisher=Canada.com |date=2006-05-26 |accessdate=2015-02-18 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160322220955/http://www.canada.com/story_print.html?id=30d5a3a0-ba68-4b7c-bb95-49b6088c493c&sponsor= |archivedate=2016-03-22 }}</ref> He also became the first Canadian to win an APSE Award in the United States, in the highest newspaper circulation category.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.apsportseditors.org/2006/oct2006/101406moves.html|title=APSE - Associated Press Sports Editors|author=The Dallas Morning News|work=apsportseditors.org|access-date=2014-12-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150210041317/http://archive.apsportseditors.org/2006/oct2006/101406moves.html|archive-date=2015-02-10|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe aftermath of the series led to Baker being hired by the Seattle Times. He has since traveled to Venezuela to write about steroids testing there<ref>{{cite web|url=http://seattletimes.com/html/mariners/2003404352_steroids12.html |title=The Seattle Times: Mariners: Growing pains: Venezuela deals with steroid testing |work=seattletimes.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150210045501/http://seattletimes.com/html/mariners/2003404352_steroids12.html |archivedate=2015-02-10 }}</ref> and was invited to speak at an October 2006 sports conference in Caracas<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.seattletimes.com/mariners/2011/11/10/only_surprise_in_wilson_ramos/|title=Only surprise in Wilson Ramos kidnapping is that it doesn't happen more often|work=The Seattle Times}}</ref> about the exploitation faced by Latin American ballplayers.\n\nA photograph by Power from the Toronto Star series, of a young Dominican throwing a baseball in a sugar cane field,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gettyimages.com/search/2/image?phrase=165322118&family=editorial|title=165322118 Pictures & News Photos - Getty Images|work=gettyimages.com}}</ref> his bicycle perched against a tree in the foreground, was used by filmmaker Ken Burns to illustrate the opening of the Dominican portion of his 2010 baseball documentary, The Tenth Inning.\n\n==2010 Josh Lueke controversy==\nThe Mariners made a blockbuster July 2010 trade of ace pitcher Cliff Lee to the Texas Rangers for Justin Smoak and three prospects, one of them a relief pitcher named Josh Lueke. There were reports all over Google about how Lueke had pleaded no contest to a charge of false imprisonment with violence after being arrested for rape and sodomy in 2008. At first, the Mariners, known for their \"family friendly\" image and support of a \"Refuse to Abuse\" campaign pertaining to violence against women, denied knowing about Lueke's background and added it was too late to reverse the trade or do anything further other than let Lueke play.\n\nBut on September 1, 2010, Baker published an A-1 story<ref>{{cite web|url=http://seattletimes.com/html/mariners/2012784518_lueke02.html |title=Mariners - Coach says Mariners were told of Josh Lueke's criminal past - Seattle Times Newspaper |work=The Seattle Times |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140810090900/http://seattletimes.com/html/mariners/2012784518_lueke02.html |archivedate=2014-08-10 }}</ref> disputing that version of events. Baker quoted Rick Adair, a former Mariners pitching coach\u2014who'd also been in charge of minor league pitchers in Texas in 2008\u2014saying he'd warned GM Jack Zduriencik all about Lueke's troubled past before the trade was made. The story also quoted Rangers GM Jon Daniels saying he'd offered Zduriencik a chance to give Lueke back and take another player, but that he refused to do so.\n\nThe Mariners have never commented on the discrepancy between their initial statements and the version presented by the sources named in Baker's story. In September 2010, they fired Carmen Fusco, their head of professional scouting.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.seattletimes.com/mariners/2010/09/13/mariners_confirm_firing_of_pro/|title=Mariners|work=The Seattle Times}}</ref> Fusco has since said he was made a scapegoat in the affair.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sportspressnw.com/2171994/2013/thiel-is-there-a-bottom-to-mariners-free-fall|title=Thiel: Is there a bottom to Mariners\u2019 free-fall?|work=Sportspress Northwest}}</ref>\n\nThe story finished in 4th place in voting for an APSE award for Explanatory Reporting. It won a regional SPJ award for Sports Reporting in the Pacific Northwest.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://seattletimes.com/html/localnews/2015117317_apspjawards3rdld2ndad.html |title=Local News - SPJ Awards      - Seattle Times Newspaper |work=The Seattle Times |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150210043608/http://seattletimes.com/html/localnews/2015117317_apspjawards3rdld2ndad.html |archivedate=2015-02-10 }}</ref>\n\n==2013 Eric Wedge/Mariners controversy==\nAfter a 16-year career as an MLB beat writer, Baker launched his new career as a sports investigative reporter with a Dec. 8, 2013 feature story about the dysfunction permeating the upper levels of the Seattle Mariners hierarchy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://seattletimes.com/html/mariners/2022420240_mariners08xml.html |title=Dysfunction at the top:  Eric Wedge, others point to trouble in Mariners\u2019 front office |work=The Seattle Times |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141216132907/http://seattletimes.com/html/mariners/2022420240_mariners08xml.html |archivedate=2014-12-16 }}</ref> Baker specifically addressed the reasons why manager Eric Wedge had walked out on the team in September, leaving a $2 million contract extension on the table. Using on-the-record quotes from Wedge, Baker painted a dysfunctional situation brought about by Mariners CEO Howard Lincoln, resident Chuck Armstrong and GM Jack Zduriencik. The story also quoted former Mariners GM assistant Tony Blengino saying he'd drawn up Zduriencik's entire resume and had helped falsely portray him as an expert in advanced statistics in order to get the job.\n\nThe story was nominated for an APSE award for Explanatory Reporting.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://apsportseditors.org/newsletter/apse-2013-contest-explanatory-over-175/|title=APSE|author=Indiana University School of Journalism|work=apsportseditors.org|access-date=2014-12-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150210041318/http://apsportseditors.org/newsletter/apse-2013-contest-explanatory-over-175/|archive-date=2015-02-10|url-status=dead}}</ref> It won a regional SPJ Award for Sports Reporting in the Pacific Northwest.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://health-city.com/2013-spj-northwest-awards/|title=2013 SPJ Northwest awards|work=health-city.com}}</ref>\n\n==2016 Controversy Over NBA Arena Reporting ==\nBaker's reporting on the proposed SoDo arena in the Stadium District of Seattle drew criticism from the SB Nation website Sonics Rising, a group of Seattle area fans lobbying for the return of NBA basketball. The site has campaigned openly for the city to support hedge fund operator Chris Hansen in efforts to build a public-subsidized arena and private sports and entertainment development in SoDo.<ref>{{Cite web\n| url = http://seattle.curbed.com/2016/2/23/11096656/the-seattle-times-really-does-not-like-chris-hansens-sodo-arena-plan\n| title = The Seattle Times Really Does Not Like Chris Hansen's SoDo Arena Plan\n| website = Curbed Seattle\n| access-date = 2016-02-24\n}}</ref> On February 22, 2016, Baker and the Editorial Board of The Seattle Times were accused by Seattle city councilman Tim Burgess of misreporting facts to suit personal bias against the arena. The allegation came via a memo introduced by Burgess in council after a front-page story by Baker suggesting council members delayed publicizing a report by architectural firm AECOM in 2015 that concluded KeyArena could be remodeled for NBA and NHL use.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Seattle councilmembers rip Times' reporting on arena studies|url = http://www.king5.com/story/news/local/seattle/2016/02/22/seattle-councilmembers-rip-times-reporting-arena-studies/80778798/|website = KING5|access-date = 2016-02-23}}</ref> Sonics Rising and two local bloggers used the occasion to again accuse Baker of biased reporting. They referenced a story of Baker's from the previous November about M.T. Phoenix, a company that offered to help finance a KeyArena renovation. The city never responded to or investigated the legitimacy of M.T. Phoenix and claimed that it legally could not entertain offers pertaining to KeyArena. The city later rebuffed a separate offer from businessman Victor Coleman, who was interested in a KeyArena renovation. Follow up stories on M.T. Phoenix, including one by Baker, found the M.T. Phoenix website contained inconsistencies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sonicsrising.com/2015/11/16/9746820/seattle-times-mt-phoenix-keyarena|title=Seattle Times Introduced us to M.T. Phoenix|work=SB Nation}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sonicsrising.com/2015/11/18/9754636/seattle-times-credibility-story-discredited-arena|title=Seattle Times Reporter Scrambling for Credibility|work=SB Nation}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Paper's Petty Personal Vendetta Impeding SoDo Arena|url = http://seattlesportsnet.com/2016/02/22/papers-petty-personal-vendetta-impeding-sodo-arena/|website = Seattle Sportsnet|access-date = 2016-02-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Thiel: Stop with the KeyArena remodel talk {{!}} Sportspress Northwest|url = http://sportspressnw.com/2215368/2016/thiel-stop-with-the-keyarena-remodel-talk|website = Sportspress Northwest|access-date = 2016-02-23}}</ref> \n\nFollowing the Burgess memo claiming inaccuracies in Baker's ensuing story in February, the newspaper met with Burgess. Seattle Times editor Kathy Best afterwards issued a statement <ref>http://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/about-the-seattle-times-arena-coverage/</ref> that he'd provided no example of factual errors in Baker's reporting and that no corrections would be made. Subsequent stories by Seattle Weekly <ref>http://archive.seattleweekly.com/home/963218-129/whos-winning-the-great-city-hall-seattle </ref> and the national Field of Schemes <ref>http://www.fieldofschemes.com/2016/03/02/10697/seattle-council-did-too-ignore-possibility-of-renovating-keyarena-says-seattle-weekly-report/</ref>website concluded that Baker's story had been correct in finding discrepancies between the AECOM report and the city's claim that KeyArena could not be remodeled for NBA and NHL. Both also found no merit to the Burgess claim of factual inaccuracies in Baker's story. Baker, in a follow-up report in April 2016, showed city hall officials had worried ahead of time that the AECOM report on KeyArena contradicted a city-issued environmental study on Hansen's Sodo arena. <ref>http://www.seattletimes.com/sports/city-worried-about-clashing-keyarena-reports-then-delayed-one/</ref> On May 2, 2016, the city voted against selling a public street so Hansen could build the arena, effectively stopping the project. Baker's arena stories earned him a finalist nod for a 2016 APSE award in investigative reporting. \n\nOn September 12, 2017, the City of Seattle and [[Oak View Group]] agreed on a $600 million deal to renovate KeyArena for NBA and NHL teams. <ref>http://www.seattletimes.com/sports/nba/oak-view-group-plans-to-renovate-keyarena-by-october-2020-spend-40-million-on-transportation-fund/</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Baker, Geoff}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Anglophone Quebec people]]\n[[Category:Canadian male journalists]]\n[[Category:Journalists from Quebec]]\n[[Category:People from Montreal]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geoff_Baker"}
{"title_page": "Dani Shapiro", "text_new": "{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name = Dani Shapiro\n| image = Dani Shapiro 2018.jpg\n| caption = Shapiro at the 2018 Texas Book Festival\n| birth_name = Daneile Shapiro\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1962|04|10}}\n| birth_place = [[New York City]], United States\n| occupation = [[Author]]\n| spouse = [[Michael Maren]]\n| children = 1\n}}\n\n'''Dani Shapiro''' is an American writer, the [[author]] of five [[novel]]s including ''Black & White'' (2007) and ''Family History'' (2003) and the [[best-selling]] [[memoirs]] ''Inheritance'' (2019)'', Hourglass'' (2017), ''Devotion'' (2010), and ''Slow Motion'' (1998)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://danishapiro.com/contact-bio/|title=Contact & Bio|date=2013-08-26|website=Dani Shapiro|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>. She has also written for magazines such as ''[[The New Yorker]]'', ''[[O, The Oprah Magazine|The Oprah Magazine]]'', ''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]'', and ''[[Elle (magazine)|Elle]]''.<ref name = B&N2019>{{Cite web|url=http://www.barnesandnoble.com/writers/writerdetails.asp?cid=1145006|title=Barnes & Noble Interview & Writer Details|accessdate=Feb 28, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080319094346/http://www.barnesandnoble.com/writers/writerdetails.asp?cid=1145006|archive-date=March 19, 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref> In February 2019, she premiered an original podcast on [[IHeartRadio|iHeart Radio]] called ''Family Secrets.''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.iheart.com/Pages/podcast-spotlight-nothing-stays-hidden-for-long-on-%E2%80%9Cfamily-secrets%E2%80%9D.aspx|title=Podcast Spotlight: Nothing Stays Hidden For Long on \u201cFamily Secrets\u201d {{!}} iHeartRadio Blog|website=blog.iheart.com|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> In April 2020, she launched her second original podcast in collaboration with iHeart Radio called ''The Way We Live Now.''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://podcasts.apple.com/us/podcast/introducing-the-way-we-live-now/id1506782444?i=1000470765129|title=\u200eThe Way We Live Now: Introducing: The Way We Live Now on Apple Podcasts|website=Apple Podcasts|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> \n\n==Early life and education==\nShapiro was born Daneile Shapiro<ref>{{Cite book|last=Shapiro|first=Dani|title=Inheritance|publisher=Knopf|year=1019|isbn=1524732710|location=|pages=228}}</ref> on April 10, 1962 In [[New York City]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Maran|first=Meredith|title=Why We Write About Ourselves: Twenty Memoirists on Why They Expose Themselves (and Others) in the Name of Literature|publisher=Plume|year=2016|isbn=0142181978|location=|pages=}}</ref> She is the daughter of Paul Shapiro, from an [[Orthodox Judaism|Orthodox Jewish]] family (who, she later learned through a recreational DNA test, was not her biological father<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/author-dani-shapiro-discovers-her-dad-isnt-her-biological-father-after-ancestry-com-dna-test/|title=Author Dani Shapiro discovers her dad isn't her biological father after DNA test|last=April 6|first=CBS News|last2=2019|website=www.cbsnews.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31|last3=Pm|first3=1:51}}</ref>), and Irene Shapiro, from [[South Jersey]]. Shapiro attended a [[Solomon Schechter Day School Association|Solomon Schechter Jewish day school]] through 6th grade, after which she attended the [[Pingry School]] in [[New Jersey]].<ref name = MindellJLedger20110211>Mindell, Cindy. [http://www.jewishledger.com/2011/01/q-a-author-dani-shapiro/ \"Q & A: Author Dani Shapiro\"], ''[[Jewish Ledger]]'', January 12, 2011. Accessed February 11, 2011.</ref> She attended [[Sarah Lawrence College]], where she was taught by [[Grace Paley]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.danaroc.com/inspiring_092506danishapiro.html|title=Dani Shapiro &#124; Inspiring People &#124; Living Louder &#124; DanaRoc.com|website=www.danaroc.com|accessdate=Feb 28, 2019}}</ref>\n==Career==\n=== Writing ===\nShapiro's [[novel]]s include ''Playing with Fire, Fugitive Blue, Picturing the Wreck, Black & White,'' and ''Family History.'' Her [[best-selling]] [[memoirs]] include ''Slow Motion'', ''Devotion, Still Writing: The Perils and Pleasures of a Creative Life, Hourglass: Time, Memory, Marriage,'' and most recently, ''Inheritance: A Memoir of Genealogy, Paternity, and Love''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goodreads.com/author/list/13932.Dani_Shapiro|title=Books by Dani Shapiro (Author of Inheritance)|website=www.goodreads.com|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> \n\nIn ''Inheritance,'' Shapiro writes about her experience of learning through a recreational DNA test that her biological father was not Paul Shapiro; rather, she had been conceived by the primitive practice of mixing Paul's sperm with that of an anonymous donor, whom she later was able to identify.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2019/01/12/im-the-result-of-a-secret-sperm-concoction/|title=I\u2019m the result of a secret sperm concoction|last=Ridley|first=Jane|date=Jan 12, 2019|accessdate=Feb 28, 2019}}</ref> ''Inheritance'' debuted at #11 on the [[The New York Times Best Seller list|''New York Times'' Best Seller list]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/best-sellers/2019/02/03/hardcover-nonfiction/|title=Hardcover Nonfiction Books - Best Sellers - Feb. 3, 2019 - The New York Times|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-02|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> and Ruth Franklin called it \"beautifully written and deeply moving.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Franklin|first=Ruth|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/01/15/books/review/dani-shapiro-inheritance.html|title=March\u2019s Book Club Pick: Dani Shapiro\u2019s New Memoir Uncovers a Life-Changing Family Secret|date=2019-01-15|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-02|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The [[San Francisco Chronicle]] described ''Inheritance'' as \"compulsively readable as a mystery novel, while exploring the deeper mysteries of identity and family and truth itself\u2026 a story told with great insight and honesty and heart.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://datebook.sfchronicle.com/books/true-blood-a-review-of-inheritance-a-memoir-by-dani-shapiro|title=True blood: A review of \u2018Inheritance,\u2019 a memoir by Dani Shapiro|last=Br|first=Gayle|last2=eisFebruary 5|website=Datebook {{!}} San Francisco Arts & Entertainment Guide|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-02|last3=February 18|first3=2019Updated:|last4=2019|last5=Pm|first5=4:55}}</ref> And [[Pulitzer Prize for Fiction|Pulitzer Prize]] winning author [[Jennifer Egan]] wrote that \u201c''Inheritance'' is Dani Shapiro at her best: a gripping genetic detective story, and a meditation on the meaning of parenthood and family.\u201d The memoir was included on several best-of-the-year lists, including that of ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/style/photos/2019/07/the-best-books-of-2019-so-far|title=The Best Books of 2019, So Far|last=Fair|first=Vanity|website=Vanity Fair|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>, ''[[O, The Oprah Magazine|Oprah Magazine]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oprahmag.com/entertainment/books/a25725613/best-book-releases-january-2019/|title=Calling It Now: Everyone Will Talk About These 4 Books All Year Long|date=2019-01-07|website=Oprah Magazine|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>, [[Literary Hub|Lit Hub]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2019/|title=Lit Hub\u2019s Most Anticipated Books of 2019|date=2018-12-28|website=Literary  Hub|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> and ''[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wired.com/story/12-top-science-books-2019/|title=12 Science Books You Should Read Right Now|work=Wired|access-date=2020-04-02|language=en|issn=1059-1028}}</ref>. \n\nIn addition to ''[[The New Yorker]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/contributors/dani-shapiro|title=Dani Shapiro|website=The New Yorker|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>, ''[[O, The Oprah Magazine|The Oprah Magazine]]''<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.oprah.com/inspiration/dani-shapiro-what-noone-tells-you-about-painful-regrets|title=What Nobody Tells You About Painful Regrets|work=Oprah.com|access-date=2020-04-02|language=en-us}}</ref>, ''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vogue.com/contributor/dani-shapiro|title=Dani Shapiro|website=Vogue|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>, and ''[[Elle (magazine)|Elle]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elle.com/author/5401/dani-shapiro/|title=Dani Shapiro|website=ELLE|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>'','' Shapiro's writing has also appeared in ''[[Salon (website)|Salon]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.salon.com/writer/dani_shapiro|title=Dani Shapiro {{!}} Salon.com|website=www.salon.com|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>, and ''[[n+1]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nplusonemag.com/authors/shapirodani/|title=Shapiro/Dani|website=n+1|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>, among others. Shapiro has also written for the screen; in 1999, she adapted [[Oscar Wilde]]'s ''[[The Happy Prince and Other Tales|The Happy Prince]]'' for [[HBO]] and in 2000, she co-wrote a screenplay based on her memoir, ''Slow Motion'', with her husband, journalist and screenwriter [[Michael Maren]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm0788484/bio|title=Dani Shapiro|website=IMDb|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\n=== Teaching ===\nDani has taught writing classes and workshops at [[New York University|NYU]], [[Wesleyan University]] and [[Columbia University]]<ref>{{cite news|last=Shapiro|first=Dani|title=#amwriting|url=http://nplusonemag.com/amwriting|accessdate=June 16, 2011|newspaper=NPlusOne|date=June 15, 2011}}</ref> as well [[Kripalu Center|Kripalu Center for Yoga and Health]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kripalu.org/presenters-programs/stories-we-carry-meditation-and-writing|title=The Stories We Carry Meditation and Writing|website=Kripalu|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>, [https://www.1440.org 1440 Multiversity]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.1440.org/programs/faculty-led-programs/personal-growth/creative-expression/the-stories-we-carry-writing-and-meditation|title=The Stories We Carry - 1440 Multiversity.|website=www.1440.org|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>, and [[Fine Arts Work Center]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.fawc.org/summer-program/transforming-chaos-art-workshop-fiction-memoir-2|title=Transforming Chaos into Art: A Workshop in Fiction & Memoir|last=FAWC-Admin|date=2020-01-09|website=FINE ARTS WORK CENTER in Provincetown|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>. On March 31, 2020, she launched her first digital course, \"Writing for Inner Calm: Methods & Exercises\", on the [[Skillshare]] online learning platform.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.skillshare.com/classes/Writing-for-Inner-Calm-A-Mindset-Methods-and-Daily-Exercises-for-All/1727076748|title=Writing for Inner Calm: A Mindset, Methods, and Daily Exercises for All {{!}} Dani Shapiro|website=Skillshare|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> \n\nShe also co-founded [https://sirenland.net Sirenland Writers Conference]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.refinery29.com/en-us/dani-shapiro-memoir-writing-advice|title=Dani Shapiro On How Writing Saved Her Life \u2014 & How It Can Save Yours|last=Barberich|first=Christene|website=www.refinery29.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> which takes place annually in [[Positano]], Italy.\n\n=== Podcasting ===\nIn collaboration with [[IHeartRadio|iHeart Radio]], Shapiro launched the original podcast ''Family Secrets'' in 2019. Each episode of this [[iTunes]] Top 10 podcast features a conversation between Dani and a guest who's experienced a family secret and its effects.<ref>[https://severancemag.com/the-family-secrets-podcast/ \"The Family Secrets Podcast\"], ''Severance Magazine'', September 2, 2019</ref> The podcast\u2019s third season premiered on February 6, 2020.<ref>[https://www.iheart.com/podcast/105-family-secrets-30131253/episode/family-secrets-season-3-is-coming-56665966/ \u201cFamily Secrets Podcast Season 3\u201d], ''iHeartRadio.com'', February 2020</ref>\n\nHer second podcast with iHeart Radio, ''The Way We Live Now'', launched in April 2020; the podcast examines the way in which individuals are experiencing isolation during the [[COVID-19]] pandemic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.iheart.com/Pages/dani-shapiros-new-daily-podcast-the-way-we-live-now-will-keep-you-company-while-practicing-social-distancing.aspx|title=Dani Shapiro\u2019s New Daily Podcast \u201cThe Way We Live Now\u201d Will Keep You Company While Practicing Social Distancing {{!}} iHeartRadio Blog|website=blog.iheart.com|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nShapiro has been married since 1997 to screenwriter [[Michael Maren]],<ref>Weddings: [https://www.nytimes.com/1997/06/08/style/dani-shapiro-michael-p-maren.html \"Dani Shapiro, Michael P Maren\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', June 8, 1997.</ref> and they have a teenage son, Jacob<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ruralintelligence.com/arts/dani_shapiros_hourglass_explores_a_marriage_over_time|title=Dani Shapiro\u2019s \u2018Hourglass\u2019 Explores A Marriage Over TimeLitchfield County resident and bestselling memoirist Dani Shapiro discusses her latest book, Hourglass.|last=May 9|last2=2017|website=www.ruralintelligence.com|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>. In the early 2000s, Dani and her family moved from [[Brooklyn]], NY to [[Litchfield, Connecticut]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Shaw|first=Dan|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/10/27/realestate/dani-shapiros-provident-move-to-the-country.html|title=Dani Shapiro\u2019s Provident Move to the Country|date=2013-10-24|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-03|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n==Books==\n\n*''Playing with Fire'' Doubleday Publishing Group, 1990, {{ISBN|9780385267229}} \n*''Fugitive Blue'' Nan A. Talese, 1992, {{ISBN|978-0385421072}} \n*''Picturing the Wreck'' Doubleday, 1995, {{ISBN|978-0385472630}} \n*''Slow Motion: A True Story'' Random House, 1998 {{ISBN|978-0-307-82800-2}}\n*''Family History: A Novel'' Knopf, 2004 {{ISBN|978-0-307-42585-0}}\n*''Black & White'' Knopf, 2007 {{ISBN|978-1-4000-3212-9}}\n*''Devotion: A Memoir'' Harper, 2010 {{ISBN|978-0-06-162834-4}}\n*''Still Writing: The Perils and Pleasures of a Creative Life'' Atlantic Monthly Press, 2013 {{ISBN|978-0-8021-9343-8}}\n*''Hourglass: Time, Memory, Marriage'' Knopf, 2017 {{ISBN|978-0-4514-9448-1}}\n*''Inheritance: A Memoir of Genealogy, Paternity, and Love'' Knopf, 2019 {{ISBN|978-1524732714}}\n\n==Appearances (selected)==\n\n* [[Oprah Winfrey]]'s ''[[Super Soul Sunday]]'', on the [[Oprah Winfrey Network (U.S. TV channel)|Oprah Winfrey Network]], to discuss ''Devotion'' on October 20, 2013 <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.supersoul.tv/tag/dani-shapiro|title=Dani Shapiro Archives|website=SuperSoul.tv|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n* [[Today (American TV program)|Today Show]] on [[NBC]] to discuss ''Inheritance'' on January 15, 2019 <ref>{{Citation|title=Dani Shapiro Opens Up About DNA Shocker That Changed Her Life {{!}} TODAY|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iRDZB-3PB8A|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n* [[CBS This Morning]] to discuss ''Inheritance'' on April 6, 2019 <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/author-dani-shapiro-discovers-her-dad-isnt-her-biological-father-after-ancestry-com-dna-test/|title=Author Dani Shapiro discovers her dad isn't her biological father after DNA test|last=April 6|first=CBS News|last2=2019|website=www.cbsnews.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06|last3=Pm|first3=1:51}}</ref>\n* [[PBS NewsHour|PBS News Hour]] to discuss ''Inheritance'' on March 31, 2020 <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/show/inheritance-author-dani-shapiro-answers-your-questions|title='Inheritance' author Dani Shapiro answers your questions|date=2020-03-31|website=PBS NewsHour|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n== Awards ==\n* 2019: [[National Jewish Book Award]] in the Autobiography and Memoir category for ''Inheritance: A Memoir of Genealogy, Paternity, and Love''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jewishbookcouncil.org/awards/national-jewish-book-awards/past-winners?category=30732|title=Past Winners|last=|first=|date=|website=Jewish Book Council|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-29}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.danishapiro.com/ Official Website]\n*[https://us.imdb.com/name/nm0788484/ Internet Movie Database Bio]\n*[http://lcwp.org/display_guest.php?id=12/ Litchfield County Writers Project]\n*[http://sirenland.net/ Sirenland Writers Conference]\n*[http://www.oprah.com/own-super-soul-sunday/Oprah-and-Dani-Shapiro-Finding-Devotion Super Soul Sunday]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shapiro, Dani}}\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:American women novelists]]\n[[Category:Jewish American writers]]\n[[Category:Pingry School alumni]]\n[[Category:Wesleyan University faculty]]\n[[Category:American women screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Writers from New York City]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:Novelists from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Novelists from Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from Connecticut]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name = Dani Shapiro\n| image = Dani Shapiro 2018.jpg\n| caption = Shapiro at the 2018 Texas Book Festival\n| birth_name = Daneile Shapiro\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1962|04|10}}\n| birth_place = [[New York City]], United States\n| occupation = [[Author]]\n| spouse = [[Michael Maren]]\n| children = 1\n}}\n\n'''Dani Shapiro''' is an American writer, the [[author]] of five [[novel]]s including ''Black & White'' (2007) and ''Family History'' (2003) and the [[best-selling]] [[memoirs]] ''Inheritance'' (2019)'', Hourglass'' (2017), ''Devotion'' (2010), and ''Slow Motion'' (1998)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://danishapiro.com/contact-bio/|title=Contact & Bio|date=2013-08-26|website=Dani Shapiro|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>. She has also written for magazines such as ''[[The New Yorker]]'', ''[[O, The Oprah Magazine|The Oprah Magazine]]'', ''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]'', and ''[[Elle (magazine)|Elle]]''.<ref name = B&N2019>{{Cite web|url=http://www.barnesandnoble.com/writers/writerdetails.asp?cid=1145006|title=Barnes & Noble Interview & Writer Details|accessdate=Feb 28, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080319094346/http://www.barnesandnoble.com/writers/writerdetails.asp?cid=1145006|archive-date=March 19, 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref> In February 2019, she premiered an original podcast on [[IHeartRadio|iHeart Radio]] called ''Family Secrets.''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.iheart.com/Pages/podcast-spotlight-nothing-stays-hidden-for-long-on-%E2%80%9Cfamily-secrets%E2%80%9D.aspx|title=Podcast Spotlight: Nothing Stays Hidden For Long on \u201cFamily Secrets\u201d {{!}} iHeartRadio Blog|website=blog.iheart.com|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nShapiro was born Daneile Shapiro<ref>{{Cite book|last=Shapiro|first=Dani|title=Inheritance|publisher=Knopf|year=1019|isbn=1524732710|location=|pages=228}}</ref> on April 10, 1962 In [[New York City]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Maran|first=Meredith|title=Why We Write About Ourselves: Twenty Memoirists on Why They Expose Themselves (and Others) in the Name of Literature|publisher=Plume|year=2016|isbn=0142181978|location=|pages=}}</ref> She is the daughter of Paul Shapiro, from an [[Orthodox Judaism|Orthodox Jewish]] family (who, she later learned through a recreational DNA test, was not her biological father<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/author-dani-shapiro-discovers-her-dad-isnt-her-biological-father-after-ancestry-com-dna-test/|title=Author Dani Shapiro discovers her dad isn't her biological father after DNA test|last=April 6|first=CBS News|last2=2019|website=www.cbsnews.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31|last3=Pm|first3=1:51}}</ref>), and Irene Shapiro, from [[South Jersey]]. Shapiro attended a [[Solomon Schechter Day School Association|Solomon Schechter Jewish day school]] through 6th grade, after which she attended the [[Pingry School]] in [[New Jersey]].<ref name = MindellJLedger20110211>Mindell, Cindy. [http://www.jewishledger.com/2011/01/q-a-author-dani-shapiro/ \"Q & A: Author Dani Shapiro\"], ''[[Jewish Ledger]]'', January 12, 2011. Accessed February 11, 2011.</ref> She attended [[Sarah Lawrence College]], where she was taught by [[Grace Paley]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.danaroc.com/inspiring_092506danishapiro.html|title=Dani Shapiro &#124; Inspiring People &#124; Living Louder &#124; DanaRoc.com|website=www.danaroc.com|accessdate=Feb 28, 2019}}</ref>\n==Career==\n=== Writing ===\nShapiro's [[novel]]s include ''Playing with Fire, Fugitive Blue, Picturing the Wreck, Black & White,'' and ''Family History.'' Her [[best-selling]] [[memoirs]] include ''Slow Motion'', ''Devotion, Still Writing: The Perils and Pleasures of a Creative Life, Hourglass: Time, Memory, Marriage,'' and most recently, ''Inheritance: A Memoir of Genealogy, Paternity, and Love''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goodreads.com/author/list/13932.Dani_Shapiro|title=Books by Dani Shapiro (Author of Inheritance)|website=www.goodreads.com|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> \n\nIn ''Inheritance,'' Shapiro writes about her experience of learning through a recreational DNA test that her biological father was not Paul Shapiro; rather, she had been conceived by the primitive practice of mixing Paul's sperm with that of an anonymous donor, whom she later was able to identify.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2019/01/12/im-the-result-of-a-secret-sperm-concoction/|title=I\u2019m the result of a secret sperm concoction|last=Ridley|first=Jane|date=Jan 12, 2019|accessdate=Feb 28, 2019}}</ref> ''Inheritance'' debuted at #11 on the [[The New York Times Best Seller list|''New York Times'' Best Seller list]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/best-sellers/2019/02/03/hardcover-nonfiction/|title=Hardcover Nonfiction Books - Best Sellers - Feb. 3, 2019 - The New York Times|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-02|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> and Ruth Franklin called it \"beautifully written and deeply moving.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Franklin|first=Ruth|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/01/15/books/review/dani-shapiro-inheritance.html|title=March\u2019s Book Club Pick: Dani Shapiro\u2019s New Memoir Uncovers a Life-Changing Family Secret|date=2019-01-15|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-02|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The [[San Francisco Chronicle]] described ''Inheritance'' as \"compulsively readable as a mystery novel, while exploring the deeper mysteries of identity and family and truth itself\u2026 a story told with great insight and honesty and heart.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://datebook.sfchronicle.com/books/true-blood-a-review-of-inheritance-a-memoir-by-dani-shapiro|title=True blood: A review of \u2018Inheritance,\u2019 a memoir by Dani Shapiro|last=Br|first=Gayle|last2=eisFebruary 5|website=Datebook {{!}} San Francisco Arts & Entertainment Guide|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-02|last3=February 18|first3=2019Updated:|last4=2019|last5=Pm|first5=4:55}}</ref> And [[Pulitzer Prize for Fiction|Pulitzer Prize]] winning author [[Jennifer Egan]] wrote that \u201c''Inheritance'' is Dani Shapiro at her best: a gripping genetic detective story, and a meditation on the meaning of parenthood and family.\u201d The memoir was included on several best-of-the-year lists, including that of ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/style/photos/2019/07/the-best-books-of-2019-so-far|title=The Best Books of 2019, So Far|last=Fair|first=Vanity|website=Vanity Fair|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>, ''[[O, The Oprah Magazine|Oprah Magazine]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oprahmag.com/entertainment/books/a25725613/best-book-releases-january-2019/|title=Calling It Now: Everyone Will Talk About These 4 Books All Year Long|date=2019-01-07|website=Oprah Magazine|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>, [[Literary Hub|Lit Hub]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2019/|title=Lit Hub\u2019s Most Anticipated Books of 2019|date=2018-12-28|website=Literary  Hub|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> and ''[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wired.com/story/12-top-science-books-2019/|title=12 Science Books You Should Read Right Now|work=Wired|access-date=2020-04-02|language=en|issn=1059-1028}}</ref>. \n\nIn addition to ''[[The New Yorker]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/contributors/dani-shapiro|title=Dani Shapiro|website=The New Yorker|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>, ''[[O, The Oprah Magazine|The Oprah Magazine]]''<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.oprah.com/inspiration/dani-shapiro-what-noone-tells-you-about-painful-regrets|title=What Nobody Tells You About Painful Regrets|work=Oprah.com|access-date=2020-04-02|language=en-us}}</ref>, ''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vogue.com/contributor/dani-shapiro|title=Dani Shapiro|website=Vogue|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>, and ''[[Elle (magazine)|Elle]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elle.com/author/5401/dani-shapiro/|title=Dani Shapiro|website=ELLE|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>'','' Shapiro's writing has also appeared in ''[[Salon (website)|Salon]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.salon.com/writer/dani_shapiro|title=Dani Shapiro {{!}} Salon.com|website=www.salon.com|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>, and ''[[n+1]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nplusonemag.com/authors/shapirodani/|title=Shapiro/Dani|website=n+1|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>, among others. Shapiro has also written for the screen; in 1999, she adapted [[Oscar Wilde]]'s ''[[The Happy Prince and Other Tales|The Happy Prince]]'' for [[HBO]] and in 2000, she co-wrote a screenplay based on her memoir, ''Slow Motion'', with her husband, journalist and screenwriter [[Michael Maren]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm0788484/bio|title=Dani Shapiro|website=IMDb|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\n=== Teaching ===\nDani has taught writing classes and workshops at [[New York University|NYU]], [[Wesleyan University]] and [[Columbia University]]<ref>{{cite news|last=Shapiro|first=Dani|title=#amwriting|url=http://nplusonemag.com/amwriting|accessdate=June 16, 2011|newspaper=NPlusOne|date=June 15, 2011}}</ref> as well [[Kripalu Center|Kripalu Center for Yoga and Health]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kripalu.org/presenters-programs/stories-we-carry-meditation-and-writing|title=The Stories We Carry Meditation and Writing|website=Kripalu|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>, [https://www.1440.org 1440 Multiversity]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.1440.org/programs/faculty-led-programs/personal-growth/creative-expression/the-stories-we-carry-writing-and-meditation|title=The Stories We Carry - 1440 Multiversity.|website=www.1440.org|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>, and [[Fine Arts Work Center]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.fawc.org/summer-program/transforming-chaos-art-workshop-fiction-memoir-2|title=Transforming Chaos into Art: A Workshop in Fiction & Memoir|last=FAWC-Admin|date=2020-01-09|website=FINE ARTS WORK CENTER in Provincetown|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>. On March 31, 2020, she launched her first digital course, \"Writing for Inner Calm: Methods & Exercises\", on the [[Skillshare]] online learning platform.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.skillshare.com/classes/Writing-for-Inner-Calm-A-Mindset-Methods-and-Daily-Exercises-for-All/1727076748|title=Writing for Inner Calm: A Mindset, Methods, and Daily Exercises for All {{!}} Dani Shapiro|website=Skillshare|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> \n\nShe also co-founded [https://sirenland.net Sirenland Writers Conference]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.refinery29.com/en-us/dani-shapiro-memoir-writing-advice|title=Dani Shapiro On How Writing Saved Her Life \u2014 & How It Can Save Yours|last=Barberich|first=Christene|website=www.refinery29.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> which takes place annually in [[Positano]], Italy.\n\n=== Podcast ===\nIn collaboration with [[IHeartRadio|iHeart Radio]], Shapiro launched the original podcast ''Family Secrets'' in 2019. Each episode of this [[iTunes]] Top 10 podcast features a conversation between Dani and a guest who's experienced a family secret and its effects.<ref>[https://severancemag.com/the-family-secrets-podcast/ \"The Family Secrets Podcast\"], ''Severance Magazine'', September 2, 2019</ref> The podcast\u2019s third season premiered on February 6, 2020.<ref>[https://www.iheart.com/podcast/105-family-secrets-30131253/episode/family-secrets-season-3-is-coming-56665966/ \u201cFamily Secrets Podcast Season 3\u201d], ''iHeartRadio.com'', February 2020</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nShapiro has been married since 1997 to screenwriter [[Michael Maren]],<ref>Weddings: [https://www.nytimes.com/1997/06/08/style/dani-shapiro-michael-p-maren.html \"Dani Shapiro, Michael P Maren\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', June 8, 1997.</ref> and they have a teenage son, Jacob<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ruralintelligence.com/arts/dani_shapiros_hourglass_explores_a_marriage_over_time|title=Dani Shapiro\u2019s \u2018Hourglass\u2019 Explores A Marriage Over TimeLitchfield County resident and bestselling memoirist Dani Shapiro discusses her latest book, Hourglass.|last=May 9|last2=2017|website=www.ruralintelligence.com|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>. In the early 2000s, Dani and her family moved from [[Brooklyn]], NY to [[Litchfield, Connecticut]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Shaw|first=Dan|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/10/27/realestate/dani-shapiros-provident-move-to-the-country.html|title=Dani Shapiro\u2019s Provident Move to the Country|date=2013-10-24|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-03|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n==Books==\n\n*''Playing with Fire'' Doubleday Publishing Group, 1990, {{ISBN|9780385267229}} \n*''Fugitive Blue'' Nan A. Talese, 1992, {{ISBN|978-0385421072}} \n*''Picturing the Wreck'' Doubleday, 1995, {{ISBN|978-0385472630}} \n*''Slow Motion: A True Story'' Random House, 1998 {{ISBN|978-0-307-82800-2}}\n*''Family History: A Novel'' Knopf, 2004 {{ISBN|978-0-307-42585-0}}\n*''Black & White'' Knopf, 2007 {{ISBN|978-1-4000-3212-9}}\n*''Devotion: A Memoir'' Harper, 2010 {{ISBN|978-0-06-162834-4}}\n*''Still Writing: The Perils and Pleasures of a Creative Life'' Atlantic Monthly Press, 2013 {{ISBN|978-0-8021-9343-8}}\n*''Hourglass: Time, Memory, Marriage'' Knopf, 2017 {{ISBN|978-0-4514-9448-1}}\n*''Inheritance: A Memoir of Genealogy, Paternity, and Love'' Knopf, 2019 {{ISBN|978-1524732714}}\n\n==Appearances (selected)==\n\n* [[Oprah Winfrey]]'s ''[[Super Soul Sunday]]'', on the [[Oprah Winfrey Network (U.S. TV channel)|Oprah Winfrey Network]], to discuss ''Devotion'' on October 20, 2013 <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.supersoul.tv/tag/dani-shapiro|title=Dani Shapiro Archives|website=SuperSoul.tv|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n* [[Today (American TV program)|Today Show]] on [[NBC]] to discuss ''Inheritance'' on January 15, 2019 <ref>{{Citation|title=Dani Shapiro Opens Up About DNA Shocker That Changed Her Life {{!}} TODAY|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iRDZB-3PB8A|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n* [[CBS This Morning]] to discuss ''Inheritance'' on April 6, 2019 <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/author-dani-shapiro-discovers-her-dad-isnt-her-biological-father-after-ancestry-com-dna-test/|title=Author Dani Shapiro discovers her dad isn't her biological father after DNA test|last=April 6|first=CBS News|last2=2019|website=www.cbsnews.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06|last3=Pm|first3=1:51}}</ref>\n* [[PBS NewsHour|PBS News Hour]] to discuss ''Inheritance'' on March 31, 2020 <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/show/inheritance-author-dani-shapiro-answers-your-questions|title='Inheritance' author Dani Shapiro answers your questions|date=2020-03-31|website=PBS NewsHour|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n== Awards ==\n* 2019: [[National Jewish Book Award]] in the Autobiography and Memoir category for ''Inheritance: A Memoir of Genealogy, Paternity, and Love''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jewishbookcouncil.org/awards/national-jewish-book-awards/past-winners?category=30732|title=Past Winners|last=|first=|date=|website=Jewish Book Council|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-29}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.danishapiro.com/ Official Website]\n*[https://us.imdb.com/name/nm0788484/ Internet Movie Database Bio]\n*[http://lcwp.org/display_guest.php?id=12/ Litchfield County Writers Project]\n*[http://sirenland.net/ Sirenland Writers Conference]\n*[http://www.oprah.com/own-super-soul-sunday/Oprah-and-Dani-Shapiro-Finding-Devotion Super Soul Sunday]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shapiro, Dani}}\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:American women novelists]]\n[[Category:Jewish American writers]]\n[[Category:Pingry School alumni]]\n[[Category:Wesleyan University faculty]]\n[[Category:American women screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Writers from New York City]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:Novelists from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Novelists from Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from Connecticut]]\n", "name_user": "PennyReader 0705", "label": "safe", "comment": "Updates to podcast info", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dani_Shapiro"}
{"title_page": "January 1975", "text_new": "{{Events by month|1975}}\n{{calendar|year=1975|month=January}}\n\nThe following events occurred in '''January 1975''':\n\n[[File:DengXiaoping.jpg|200px|left|thumb|January 17, 1975: Deng Xiaoping returns to power]]\n[[File:SpaceMountainMK.jpg|300px|right|thumb|January 15, 1975: Space Mountain roller coaster opens]]\n[[File:Landsat-1.jpg|200px|left|thumb|January 22, 1975: Landsat 2 launched into space]]\n\n==[[January 1]], 1975 (Wednesday)==\n*Former U.S. Attorney General [[John N. Mitchell]], former presidential Chief of Staff [[H. R. Haldeman]] and [[John Ehrlichman]] were found guilty by a jury or 9 women and 3 men, on charges of conspiracy, obstruction of justice, and perjury in the cover-up of the [[Watergate scandal]].  Robert C. Mardian, a fourth defendant, was found guilty on one count of conspiracy.<ref>\"4 EX-NIXON AIDES CONVICTED, FACE LONG COVERUP TERMS\", ''Pittsburgh Press'', January 2, 1975, p1</ref><ref>\"Tapes Tipped the Scales\", ''Milwaukee Journal'', January 2, 1975, p1</ref>\n*In college football, the previously-undefeated Alabama Crimson Tide, ranked #1 in the UPI poll and #2 by the AP, lost to #9 Notre Dame, 13-11, in the Orange Bowl, giving Irish coach [[Ara Parseghian]] a victory in his final game.<ref>\"End Of Ara Era: Irish Stem Tide\", ''Pittsburgh Press'', January 2, 1975, p41</ref>  The #5 USC Trojans, going for a 2-point conversion rather than kicking an extra point, defeated #3 Ohio State (#2 in UPI), 18-17, to win the Rose Bowl before a crowd of 106,000.<ref>\"Trojans Disdain Tie in 18-17 Victory\", ''Milwaukee Journal'', January 2, 1975, p2-1</ref> Oklahoma University, ranked #1 by the AP, and was ineligible for a bowl and for a ranking in the UPI Coaches' Poll, while #4 Michigan was not invited to a bowl.\n*The [[Khmer Rouge]] began the campaign that would put it in control of [[Cambodia]], cutting off the supply lines to [[Phnom Penh]].<ref name=Kissinger>Henry Kissinger, ''Years of Renewal'' (Simon and Schuster, 2000) p502</ref>\n*Knighthood was conferred by [[Queen Elizabeth II]] on comedian [[Charlie Chaplin]], author [[P. G. Wodehouse]], athlete [[Roger Bannister]], and cricket legend [[Gary Sobers]].<ref>\"Charlie Chaplin, P.G. Wodehouse Knighted\", ''St. Petersburg Times'', January 2, 1975, p2-A</ref>\n*In fiction, the 2000 novel ''[[White Teeth]]'', by [[Zadie Smith]], opens with  Archie Jones making an attempt at suicide on January 1, 1975.<ref>Zadie Smith, ''White Teeth: A Novel'' (Random House, 2000) p3</ref>\n*The new Constitution of Sweden came into effect.<ref>Heather Knowles, ''Passport Series: Western Europe'' (Lorenz Educational Press, 2010) p149</ref>\n\n==[[January 2]], 1975 (Thursday)==\n*[[Lalit Narayan Mishra]], the Railway Minister of India, was assassinated as he attended a ceremony to dedicate a new railway line at [[Samastipur]] in the [[Bihar]] State.  Mishra was fatally injured by a bomb that had been placed under the speaker's [[dais]], in a blast that killed another person and injured 23 other people, and died the next day.<ref>\"Blast Kills Rail Chief in India\", ''Milwaukee Journal'', January 3, 1975, p1-2</ref>  Members of the terrorist group [[Ananda Marg]] claimed responsibility for the blast, aiming to retaliate for the imprisonment of their leader, [[Prabhat Ranjan Sarkar]].<ref>Sean Anderson and Stephen Sloan, ''Historical Dictionary of Terrorism (Scarecrow Press, 2009) p20</ref>\n*Bangladesh Marxist leader [[Siraj Sikder]] was arrested, then shot and killed on orders by that nation's president, [[Sheikh Mujibur Rahman]].  Mujibur himself would be assassinated seven months later.<ref>S. Mahmud Ali, ''Understanding Bangladesh'' (Columbia University Press, 2010) p305</ref>\n*The bill approving the [[Federal Rules of Evidence]] was signed into law by U.S. President Ford.<ref>\"Who's Making the Rules Around Here Anyway?\", by Cary H. Copeland, ''ABA Journal'' (May 1976) p665</ref>\n*The [[World Tourism Organization]] (WTO) was established by the [[United Nations]], replacing the International Union of Official Travel Organizations (IUOTO).<ref>Edmund Jan Osma\u0144czyk and Anthony Mango, ''Encyclopedia of the United Nations and Agreements'', Volume 4 (Taylor & Francis, 2003) p2757</ref>\n*The [[1974 USC Trojans football team|USC Trojans]] were ranked #1 in the final UPI [[college football]] poll, taken of college coaches, giving them a share of the mythical national championship.<ref>\"Southern Cal Ranked No. 1\", ''Milwaukee Journal'', January 2, 1975, p2-10</ref>\n*'''Died:''' [[Chilaiditi syndrome|Dimitrios Chiladiti]], 91, Greek radiologist\n\n==[[January 3]], 1975 (Friday)==\n*The [[1974 Oklahoma Sooners football team|University of Oklahoma Sooners]] were given the number 1 ranking in the final AP sportswriters poll of the [[1974 college football season]], and a share of the unofficial national college football championship.  The Sooners had been the only undefeated and untied team, but had been ineligible for postseason play, and were not included in the UPI coaches' poll. The USC Trojans, #1 in UPI, were 2nd in the AP poll.<ref>\"Oklahoma Picked No. 1\", ''Milwaukee Sentinel'', January 4, 1975, p2-3</ref>\n*In the largest return in history of U.S. government land to an American Indian tribe, 250 square miles of the [[Grand Canyon National Monument]] were deeded back to the [[Havasupai people]] with the signing of a bill by President Ford.  The 400 members of the tribe had been limited to a reservation of only 518 acres, less than one square mile, at the bottom of Havasu Canyon, since 1882.  The legislation also enlarged the National Park by adding 687,000 acres to bring its total size to 1,875 square miles.<ref>Todd R. Berger, ''It Happened at Grand Canyon'' (Globe Pequot, 2007) p126</ref>\n*'''Died:''' [[Milton Cross]], 77, announcer since 1931 for the weekly radio broadcasts of the [[Metropolitan Opera]].  Cross, known to his fans as \"Mr. Opera\", was preparing for the next day's show when he collapsed at his home.\n\n==[[January 4]], 1975 (Saturday)==\n*[[Henry Boucha]] of the [[Minnesota North Stars]], who had been the NHL's Rookie of the Year two years earlier, suffered a career ending eye injury after being high-sticked by [[Dave Forbes]] of the [[Boston Bruins]] during Boston's 8-0 win.  Forbes would become the first American professional athlete to be criminally indicted for a crime committed in the course of a game, although the trial ended in a hung jury.  In 1980, Boucha settled a lawsuit against Forbes, the Bruins and the NHL for $1,500,000.<ref>\nStanley H. Teitelbaum, ''Sports Heroes, Fallen Idols'' (University of Nebraska Press, 2008) p204</ref>\n*U.S. President [[Gerald R. Ford]] signed legislation making 55 miles per hour the maximum speed limit across the United States, making permanent what had been a temporary order in 1973 by President Nixon.<ref>\"Ford Makes 55 mph Permanent, Signs Bill To Aid Jobless\", ''Pittsburgh Press'', January 5, 1975, p1</ref>\n*Executive Order 11828 created the Commission on CIA Activities within the United States, chaired by U.S. Vice-President [[Nelson Rockefeller]].<ref>W. Thomas Smith, ''[[Encyclopedia of the Central Intelligence Agency]]'' (Infobase Publishing, 2003) p90</ref>\n*[[Wimbledon F.C.|Wimbledon]] become the first non league club to win at a [[Football League First Division|First Division]] club in the [[1974\u201375 FA Cup|F A cup]] third round since the creation of the [[Football League Third Division|Third Division]] in [[1920\u201321 in English football|1920]]. [[Altrincham F.C.|Altrincham]] almost achieve the same objective when holding [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] to a draw. Thirty-one of the Thirty-two ties take place with cup holders, [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] defeating [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke]] while [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham]] win at [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] at the start of their ultimately victorious cup run.<ref>http://www.statto.com/football/stats/results/1975-01-04</ref>\n*'''Died:''' \n**[[Bob Montana]], 54, American comic strip artist who created the characters in [[Archie Comics]]\n**[[Carlo Levi]], 71, Italian novelist and legislator\n\n==[[January 5]], 1975 (Sunday)==\n*''[[The Wiz]]'', a musical adaptation of ''[[The Wonderful Wizard of Oz]]'' with an African-American cast, opened on Broadway.  It would go on to win two Tony Awards and run for 1,672 performances.<ref>Michael Patrick Hearn, ed., ''The Annotated Wizard of Oz'' (W. W. Norton & Company, 2000)</ref>\n*The [[Tasman Bridge]] in [[Tasmania]], [[Australia]], [[Tasman Bridge disaster|was struck]] by the bulk ore carrier ''Lake Illawarra'', killing 12 people.   The ship struck a support on the mile-long bridge at about 9:00 pm, bringing down a {{convert|240|ft|m|adj=mid|-long}} section on top of it, and sank.  Three vehicles on the bridge plunged into the [[River Derwent (Tasmania)|River Derwent]] below.<ref>\"5 Die As Ship Hits Aussie Span, Sinks\", ''Pittsburgh Post-Gazette'', January 6, 1975, p1</ref>\n*The leaders of the three military groups fighting for the independence of Angola- Jonas Savimbi of UNITA, Agostinho Neto of MPLA, and Holden Roberto of FNLA- signed the Mombasa Agreement in Kenya's capital, under the sponsorship of President Jomo Kenyatta, pledging to work together to negotiate with Portugal.  The united front lasted only a few months, after the United States allied with UNITA and the Soviet Union assisted the MPLA.<ref>W. Martin James III, ''A Political History of the Civil War in Angola, 1974-1990'' (Transaction Publishers, 2011) p55</ref><ref name=Angola>W. Martin James, ''Historical Dictionary of Angola'' (Scarecrow Press, 2011) p169</ref>\n*'''Born:''' \n**[[Mike Grier]], the first African-American NHL player (1996\u20132011) to be born and trained in the United States; in [[Detroit]]; \n**[[Warrick Dunn]], American NFL running back, in [[Baton Rouge]], [[Louisiana]]\n**[[Bradley Cooper]], American TV actor (''Alias''), in [[Philadelphia]]\n*'''Died:''' \n**[[Don Wilson (baseball)|Don Wilson]], 29, American MLB pitcher for the Houston Astros (1966\u20131974), by carbon monoxide poisoning\n**[[Gottlob Berger]], 79, convicted German SS General and Nazi war criminal who spent six years at Spandau prison\n**[[Rudolf Demme]], 80, German Panzer division general who spent ten years in a Soviet prison\n\n==[[January 6]], 1975 (Monday)==\n*The game show ''[[Wheel of Fortune (US daytime game show)|Wheel of Fortune]]'', created by [[Merv Griffin]] and inspired by the children's game [[Hangman (game)|\"Hangman\"]], premiered on [[NBC]] at 10:30 am Eastern time.  The original hosts were [[Chuck Woolery]] and [[Susan Stafford]], who would be replaced in 1982 by [[Pat Sajak]] and [[Vanna White]], respectively.<ref>Horace Newcomb, ''Encyclopedia of Television'' (CRC Press, 2004) p2527</ref>\n*After the sale of gold was legalized in the United States, for the first time since 1933, on December 31, the U.S. Treasury conducted its first auction of a part of its gold reserves, setting aside an unprecedented 2,000,000 ounces for sale, in individual 400 ounce gold bricks, valued at $70,000 apiece based on the European market price of $175 an ounce.  The first sealed bid that was opened was for $156 an ounce by the investment firm of Austern and Paul.<ref>\"Big gold auction opens to 200 bids\", ''Miami News'', January 6, 1975, p1</ref>\n*''[[AM America]]'', which would later be replaced by ''[[Good Morning America]]'', made its television debut on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] at 7:00 am Eastern time.  Intended to compete against the ''Today'' show and ''The CBS Morning News'', the news series was hosted by [[Bill Beutel]], with co-hosts [[Stephanie Edwards (TV personality)|Stephanie Edwards]] and [[Peter Jennings]].\n*''[[Another World (TV series)|Another World]]'', an afternoon soap opera airing on NBC since 1964 as a 30-minute show, expanded to 60 minutes.  It was the first ongoing attempt of a U.S. serial to air in a time slot of that length, and would be the beginning of a wave of other soaps expanding to 60-minute lengths.  The last long-running 30-minute serial to expand to 60 minutes would be ''[[The Young and the Restless]]'' in 1980.\n*An attempt by [[Malcolm Forbes]] to become the first person to fly a balloon across the Atlantic Ocean, ended before it started.  Multimillionaire publisher Forbes and aerospace scientist Thomas Heinsheimer were preparing to lift off from [[Santa Ana, California]] in the ''Windborne'' for a 7,000 mile trip.<ref>\"2 Safe As Balloons Burst\", ''Pittsburgh Press'', January 6, 1975, p1</ref>\n*'''Born:''' [[Ricardo Santos (beach volleyball)|Ricardo Santos]], Brazilian beach volleyball player, and 2004 Olympic gold medalist; in [[Salvador, Bahia]], [[Brazil]]\n*'''Died:''' [[Burton K. Wheeler]], 92, isolationist U.S. Senator for Montana from 1923 to 1947\n\n==[[January 7]], 1975 (Tuesday)==\n*The South Vietnamese province of [[Phuoc Binh]] became the first to be captured by Viet Cong invaders, who led an assault with tanks and three infantry divisions.<ref>\"Viet Reds Capture An Entire Province\", ''Pittsburgh Press'', January 4, 1975, p1</ref>  Out of 5,400 South Vietnamese Army defenders, only 850 survived, and twenty Vietnam Air Force planes were shot down; local officials were summarily executed.<ref>Spencer Tucker, ''Vietnam'' (UCL Press, 1999)</ref>   U.S. Secretary of State [[Henry Kissinger]] would later write, \"Phuoc Binh was the test case\" for the North Vietnamese government to decide whether to proceed with trying to conquer South Vietnam, and \"If the United States reacted, there was still a chance for Hanoi to withdraw from the brink.\" <ref name=Kissinger/>\n*The [[Louisiana Tech Lady Techsters basketball|women's basketball team of Louisiana Tech]], which would go on to win three national championships and more than 80% of its games, played its very first game, and lost, 59-55, to visiting [[Southeastern Louisiana University]].<ref>''Louisiana Tech Lady Techsters Basketball 2010-11 Media Guide'', p122</ref> The crowd for the first was about 45 people.<ref>Kim Mulkey, ''Won't Back Down: Teams, Dreams, and Family'' (Da Capo Press, 2008) p20</ref>\n\n==[[January 8]], 1975 (Wednesday)==\n*''[[The Boston Globe]]'' broke an exclusive story that Soviet leader [[Leonid Brezhnev]] was going to arrive in Boston's [[Dana\u2013Farber Cancer Institute|Sidney Farber Cancer Center]] to receive treatment for [[leukemia]].<ref>\"Brezhnev reportedly coming to Boston cancer center today\", ''Boston Globe'', January 8, 1975, p1</ref>  The hospital, the Kremlin and the White House quickly denied the story <ref>\"Brezhnev Boston trip denied\", ''Miami News'', January 8, 1975, p1; \"Cancer story 'false'\", ''Ottawa Citizen'', January 7, 1975, p4</ref> and the ''Globe'' soon admitted that it had been the victim of a hoax.<ref>\"Boston Fooled by Hoax on Brezhnev Visit\", ''Milwaukee Journal'', January 30, 1975, p4</ref>  Brezhnev, who did not have leukemia and who was not coming to the United States, would live on until 1982.\n*After [[South Vietnam]]'s Phuoc Long province had been conquered without any intervention by the United States, the Politburo of North Vietnam's Communist Party approved \"Campaign 275\", to \"liberate\" the rest of South Vietnam, starting with a full-scale attack on the Central Highlands.  Party First Secretary [[L\u00ea Du\u1ea9n]]  ordered strikes on [[Bu\u00f4n Ma Thu\u1ed9t]], [[Tuy H\u00f2a]], [[Qui Nh\u01a1n]], [[Hu\u1ebf]] and [[Da Nang]].<ref>J. Edward Lee and Toby Haynsworth, ''Nixon, Ford, and the Abandonment of South Vietnam'' (McFarland, 2002) p83</ref>\n*[[Ella Grasso]] became [[Governor of Connecticut]], the first female U.S. governor who did not succeed her husband.<ref>\"Mrs. Grasso Sees Hard Times Ahead\", ''Milwaukee Journal'', January 9, 1975, p3</ref>\n*Convicted Watergate conspirators [[John W. Dean III]], [[Jeb Stuart Magruder]] and [[Herbert W. Kalmbach]] were released from prison after serving sentences ranging from four months to seven months.<ref>\"Sirica Frees Dean, 2 Others in Scandal\", ''Milwaukee Journal'', January 8, 1975, p1</ref>\n*'''Died:''' \n**[[Richard Tucker]], 61, American operatic tenor, while on tour with the Metropolitan Opera\n**[[David Marshall Williams|David \"Carbine\" Williams]], 74, inventor of M-1 carbine rifle, portrayed by Jimmy Stewart in the 1952 film ''[[Carbine Williams]]''\n\n==[[January 9]], 1975 (Thursday)==\n*Denmark's Liberal Party, led by Prime Minister [[Poul Hartling]], gained seats in the election for the Parliament, the 179 seat Folketing, to increase its share to 42 members.  The Social Democrats gained as well, winning 53 seats.<ref>\"Danes Vote; Coalition May Result\", ''Milwaukee Journal'', January 10, 1975, p4</ref>\n*A mountain in Mexico called the Mountain of Butterflies where many monarch butterflies go at wintertime is discovered.\n*\"The Beatles & Co., Ltd.\", the corporation created by [[John Lennon]], [[Paul McCartney]], [[George Harrison]] and [[Ringo Starr]] to pay them as employees in order to effect a savings on taxes, was formally dissolved by a court in London, four years after McCartney had filed suit in the year after the band's breakup.<ref>Peter Doggett, ''You Never Give Me Your Money: The Beatles After the Breakup'' (HarperCollins, 2010) p28</ref>\n*'''Died:''' \n**[[Li Fuchun]], 74, Communist Chinese economic planner\n**[[Virginia Ellis Jenckes]], 77, U.S. Representative, 1933\u201339 and first woman to represent Indiana in Congress\n**[[Pierre Fresnay]], 77, French actor\n\n==[[January 10]], 1975 (Friday)==\n*[[Pope Paul VI]] broke a 900-year-old policy by accepting a woman as an envoy from to the Vatican.  [[Bernadette Olowo]] was appointed by [[Uganda]], which had 3.5 million Roman Catholics, more than any other nation in Africa, and was also that nation's ambassador to [[West Germany]].  A spokesman for the Vatican said, \"The acceptance of a woman ambassador will be subject to the same rules as men,\" including good moral behavior and compliance with for Roman Catholic doctrine.  The year before, the Pope had rejected an Australian nomination of a woman ambassador because she was a divorcee.  Forty years earlier, [[Pope Pius XI]] had declared that women should not work at any occupation outside of the home.<ref>\"First female envoy gets Pope's approval\", ''St. Petersburg Times'', January 11, 1975, p5-B</ref>\n*The [[Queen Elizabeth 2]] began its first round-the-world cruise, departing New York City under tight security with 1,200 passengers.<ref>\"Security Tight as Luxury Ship Starts Journey\", ''Milwaukee Journal'', January 11, 1975, p2</ref>\n*'''Born:''' [[Jake Delhomme]], American NFL quarterback, in [[Breaux Bridge, Louisiana]]\n\n==[[January 11]], 1975 (Saturday)==\n*[[Soyuz 17]], with Soviet cosmonauts [[Aleksei Gubarev]] and [[Georgi Grechko]], both 43 and making their first flights, lifted off from the Baikonur space center and docked successfully with the [[Salyut 4]] space station, becoming the first men to occupy it.<ref>\"2 Cosmonauts Settle Into Salyut 4 'Home'\", ''Pittsburgh Post-Gazette'', January 13, 1975, p3</ref>  They would return to Earth on February 7 after setting a new record for most days (28) spent in outer space.<ref>Philip Baker, ''The Story of Manned Space Stations: An Introduction'' (Springer, 2007) p53</ref>\n*The last remains of the rocket that had launched [[Skylab]] into orbit in 1973, re-entered the atmosphere and burned up at about 3:00 pm EST.<ref>\"Remains of Rocket End Journey\", ''Milwaukee Journal'', January 11, 1975, p3</ref>\n*[[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]] defeat [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]] 2-0 to maintain a one-point lead in the English Soccer First Division with sixteen games remaining. [[Roger Osborne]] and [[David Johnson (footballer born 1951)|David Johnson]] are the goal scorers. \n*'''Died:''' [[Paul Peter Meouchi]], 80, Lebanese Maronite priest and first Maronite to serve in the Vatican's college of cardinals\n\n==[[January 12]], 1975 (Sunday)==\n*The [[Pittsburgh Steelers]] defeated the [[Minnesota Vikings]] 16\u20136 at [[Tulane Stadium]] in [[New Orleans, Louisiana]], to win [[Super Bowl IX]] and their first NFL championship in their 42-year history.  The Steelers led 2-0 at halftime after Dwight White sacked Vikings' quarterback [[Fran Tarkenton]] in the end zone, and only 9-6 in the last quarter until Pittsburgh drove to another touchdown late in the game.<ref>\"SUPER STEELERS WIN, 16-6\", ''Pittsburgh Post-Gazette'', January 13, 1975, p1</ref>\n*Caryn Campbell vanished while walking from the lobby to her room at the Wildwood Inn at [[Snowmass, Colorado]].  She was the 15th victim of serial killer [[Ted Bundy]], but the first for whose murder he ever stood trial.<ref>\nKevin M. Sullivan, ''The Bundy Murders: A Comprehensive History'' (McFarland, 2009) pp119-124</ref>\n*[[Maharishi Mahesh Yogi]], guru of the [[Transcendental Meditation]] movement, declared to a gathering of thousands of his followers, at [[Hertenstein, Lucerne|Hertenstein]], on [[Lake Lucerne]] in Switzerland, that the dawn of the new Age of Enlightenment had arrived.<ref>Bob Oates, ''Celebrating the Dawn: Maharishi Mahesh Yogi and the TM Technique'' (Putnam, 1976) p57</ref>\n\n==[[January 13]], 1975 (Monday)==\n*The Chrysler Corporation began offering rebates of up to $400 on specific models of new cars and light trucks in what was described as \"an unprecedented five week campaign\".  The move was driven by an inventory of 340,000 unsold 1975 models, with the incentive of paying customers rather than reducing the sticker price.<ref>\"Chrysler Rebates May Set Trend\", ''Milwaukee Journal'', January 8, 1975, p1</ref>\n*Terrorists attempted to shoot down an El Al airliner that was preparing to take off from Orly airport in Paris on a flight to New York with 136 passengers.  The missile failed to hit due to the pilot's evasive action, and struck a Yugoslavian DC-9 that had not yet boarded, but failed to explode.  A second attempt was made six days later, and the two tries were traced to the Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine, to Muamar Gadhafi, and to the international terrorist [[Ilich Ramirez Sanchez]] (Carlos).<ref>\nRuwantissa Abeyratne, ''Aviation Security Law'' (Springer, 2010) p30</ref>\n*The coldest [[wind chill]] ever recorded in North America was measured at [[Kugaaruk]],  in the [[Nunavut]] territory of [[Canada]] (formerly Pelly Bay, Northwest Territories).  An air temperature of -60&nbsp;\u00b0F and a wind speed of 35&nbsp;mph combined for a wind chill factor of -135&nbsp;\u00b0F (-78&nbsp;\u00b0C) <ref>Christopher C. Burt and Mark Stroud, ''Extreme Weather: A Guide & Record Book'' (W. W. Norton & Company, 2007) p58</ref>\n*In a crime that shocked all of [[India]], terrorists from the [[Mizo National Front]] (MNF) charged into the police headquarters at [[Aizawl]], capital of the [[Mizoram]] state, and murdered the three top officials- Inspector General G.S. Arya, Deputy Inspector Sewa and Police Superintendent Panchapakesan.<ref>\nSuhas Chatterjee, ''Making of Mizoram: Role of Laldenga'' (M.D. Publications Pvt. Ltd., 1994) p244</ref>\n\n==[[January 14]], 1975 (Tuesday)==\n*The [[House Un-American Activities Committee]], most notable for its investigations and accusations of Communist infiltration of Hollywood, was disbanded by the U.S. House of Representatives after 37 years.  In 1969, it had been renamed the \"Committee on Internal Security\".<ref>Richard Gid Powers, ''Not without Honor: The History of American Anticommunism'' (Yale University Press, 1998) p353; \"Democrats Vote to Abolish Security Committee\", ''Sarasota Herald-Tribune'', January 14, 1975, p5-A</ref>\n*U.S. Secretary of State [[Henry Kissinger]] announced that the Soviet Union was rescinding its agreement to a trade deal with the United States, eleven days after the [[Jackson\u2013Vanik amendment]] to the [[Trade Act of 1974]] had been signed into law.  The amendment, sponsored by U.S. Senator and Democratic presidential candidate [[Henry M. Jackson]] (as well as U.S. Representative [[Charles Vanik]]) provided that nations with \"non-market economies\" that restricted emigration were to be denied [[most favored nation]] status, and had been aimed at putting pressure on the Soviet Union to drop its opposition to allowing its Jewish citizens to emigrate.  Soviet First Secretary [[Leonid Brezhnev]] had sent a letter to U.S. President Ford on December 25, warning that the amendment was unacceptable.  The amendment had the opposite effect, with Jewish emigration decreasing by 35% between 1974 and 1975.<ref>Robert G. Kaufman, ''Henry M. Jackson: A Life in Politics'' (University of Washington Press, 2000) p280-281; \"Trade Pact Repudiated By Russia\", ''Pittsburgh Press'', January 15, 1975, p1</ref>\n*The [[Registration Convention|Convention on Registration of Launched Objects into Outer Space]], an international treaty requiring the signatory nations to keep the United Nations informed of the orbital details of any object launched into outer space, was signed in New York, and went into effect on September 15, 1976.<ref>Francis Lyall and Paul B. Larsen, ''Space Law: A Treatise'' (Ashgate Publishing, 2009) p85</ref>\n*U.S. Vice-President [[Nelson Rockefeller]] was named by President Ford to chair a special commission to investigate domestic spying by the [[Central Intelligence Agency]].<ref>Bruce P. Montgomery, ''Richard B. Cheney and the Rise of the Imperial Vice Presidency'' (ABC-CLIO, 2009) p29</ref>\n\n==[[January 15]], 1975 (Wednesday)==\n*The [[Alvor Agreement]] was signed at the Penina Golfe Hotel in [[Alvor (Portim\u00e3o)|Alvor]], [[Portugal]], by the chiefs of the three groups fighting for the independence of [[Angola]] (Savimbi, Neto and Roberto) and President Costa Gomes of [[Portugal]], after which the Portuguese government announced a date of November 11, 1975, for the independence of the colony of Portuguese West Africa as Angola.<ref name=Angola/><ref>\"Angola to Become Independent Nov. 11\", ''Pittsburgh Post-Gazette'', January 16, 1975, p4</ref><ref>Witney W. Schneidman, ''Engaging Africa: Washington and the Fall of Portugal's Colonial Empire'' (University Press of America, 2004) p198</ref>\n*[[Space Mountain (Magic Kingdom)|Space Mountain]], an enclosed roller coaster, operated in near darkness, opened at [[Walt Disney World]] in Florida, and later was duplicated at the other Disney parks.<ref>Susan Veness, ''The Hidden Magic of Walt Disney World'' (Adams Media, 2009) p54; \"Disney World Opens Space Mountain\", ''Lakeland (FL) Ledger'', January 17, 1975, p1D</ref>\n*CIA Director [[William Colby]] confirmed the reports from ''New York Times'' reporter [[Seymour Hersh]] and revealed to a U.S. Senate subcommittee that the agency had violated its charter by spying on American citizens for activities within the United States.<ref>\"CIA ADMITS SPYING INSIDE U.S.\", ''Pittsburgh Press'', January 15, 1975, p1; Frank J. Smist, Jr., ''Congress Oversees the United States Intelligence Community, 1947-1994'' (University of Tennessee Press, 1994) p27</ref>\n*'''Born:''' [[Mary Pierce]], Canadian-born French professional tennis player; winner of Australian Open, 1995, and French Open, 2000; in [[Montreal]]\n*'''Died:''' [[Ernest Koliqi]], 78, Albanian poet\n\n==[[January 16]], 1975 (Thursday)==\n[[File:Raymond burr ironside.JPG|100px|right|thumb|Ironside]] \n*A U.S. District Court jury awarded $12,000,000 to 1,200 anti-war demonstrators who had been illegally arrested on May 5, 1971 while they listened to a speech by Congressman [[Ronald Dellums]] of California at the U.S. Capitol.  The amount was ordered payable by the District of Columbia government, following the suit by the ACLU.  Many of the group had been detained at makeshift compounds, including the RFK Stadium.  The ACLU had located 900 of the named plaintiffs <ref>\"D.C. Protesters Get $12 Million\",  ''Pittsburgh Press'', January 17, 1975, p1; \"Calls Pour In For Share Of D.C. Suit\", ''Pittsburgh Press'', January 18, 1975, p3</ref>\n*The NBC television show [[Ironside (TV series)|''Ironside'']], starring [[Raymond Burr]] as wheelchair-bound police detective Robert Ironside, showed its 199th and final episode after a run of eight seasons.<ref>\"'Ironside' Ending Tonight\", ''Ocala (FL) Star-Banner'', January 16, 1975, p12B</ref>\n\n==[[January 17]], 1975 (Friday)==\n*At the first meeting of China's National People's Congress in ten years, [[Zhou Enlai]] was re-elected as Prime Minister, and [[Deng Xiaoping]], who had been in disgrace with the Communist Party for eight years, was elected as a Vice-Premier and Vice-Chairman of the party.  Yeh Chin-ying was made Defense Minister, filling a spot left vacant by the death of the vilified [[Lin Biao]].<ref>\"China Re-elects Ailing Chou\" ''Pittsburgh Press'', January 18, 1975, p1</ref>  A new Constitution for the People's Republic was promulgated on the same day.<ref>Xing Lu, ''Rhetoric of the Chinese Cultural Revolution: the Impact on Chinese Thought, Culture, and Communication'' University of South Carolina Press, 2004 p76</ref>\n*After the French Chamber of Deputies voted 284-189 in favor of legalization of abortion, the law proposed by [[Simone Veil]] went into effect, allowing abortion on demand during the first ten weeks of pregnancy.<ref>Melanie Latham, ''Regulating Reproduction: A Century of Conflict in Britain and France'' (Manchester University Press, 2002) p123</ref>\n*'''Born:''' [[Tony Brown (rugby union)|Tony Brown]], New Zealand rugby union football player, in [[Balclutha, New Zealand|Balclutha]]\n*'''Died:''' General [[Gustavo Rojas Pinilla]], 74, [[President of Colombia]] from 1953 to 1957\n\n==[[January 18]], 1975 (Saturday)==\n*The first of 253 episodes of ''[[The Jeffersons]]'' was telecast, as [[Sherman Hemsley]], [[Isabel Sanford]] and [[Mike Evans (actor)|Mike Evans]] took their recurring characters on ''[[All in the Family]]'' (George, Louise and Lionel Jefferson) to a spinoff TV series that would run for eleven seasons, concluding in 1985.<ref>James S. Olson, ''Historical Dictionary of the 1970s'' (Greenwood Publishing Group, 1999) p210</ref>\n*The derailment of a train near [[Cairo]] killed 27 persons in Egypt and injured 52.<ref>\"Derailment Kills 27\", ''Pittsburgh Press'', January 19, 1975, p1</ref>\n*Everton became the new leaders of the English Soccer First Division with 16 games remaining after a brace from [[Bob Latchford]] and an own goal from [[Archie Styles]] that secured a 3-0 victory at [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]]. Previous leader Ipwsich was defeated, 1-2, at [[Carlisle United F.C.|Carlisle United]].<ref>http://www.statto.com/football/stats/results/1975-01-18</ref>\n\n==[[January 19]], 1975 (Sunday)==\n[[File:US Atomic Energy Commission logo.jpg|150px|left|thumb|AEC out]]\n[[File:US-NuclearRegulatoryCommission-Logo.svg|150px|right|thumb|NRC in]]\n[[File:Seal of the United States Energy Research and Development Administration.png|150px|right|thumb|ERDA]]\n*The [[United States Atomic Energy Commission]] was split up into the [[Nuclear Regulatory Commission]] (NRC) and the [[Energy Research and Development Administration]] (ERDA), under the terms of the [[Energy Reorganization Act of 1974]].  The NRC assumed the functions of regulating private nuclear power plants, while ERDA oversaw nuclear weapons.<ref>Barton C. Hacker, ''Elements of Controversy: the Atomic Energy Commission and Radiation Safety in Nuclear Weapons Testing, 1947-1974'' (University of California Press, 1994) p254</ref>\n*Three Arab gunmen went to the observation deck at the [[Orly Airport]] in [[Paris]] and tried to shoot down at [[El Al]] 747 jumbo jet as it was taking off from Paris to [[Tel Aviv]] with 220 people on board.    After police prevented them from succeeding, the gunmen fired machine guns into the crowd and threw grenades, wounding 78 people, then took ten hostages.  After 17 hours, the men were allowed to depart on a flight to Iraq after freeing all of their hostages.<ref>\"ARABS FREE 10, FLY TO MIDDLE EAST\", ''Pittsburgh Press'', January 20, 1975, p1</ref>\n*[[1975 Kinnaur earthquake|A 6.8 magnitude earthquake]] struck in the state of [[Himachal Pradesh]], [[India]], at 1:30 pm local time, killing 47 people, mostly in the township of Kaurik.<ref>\"Quake Kills 14\" ''Pittsburgh Press'', January 20, 1975, p1; S. S. Negi, ''Discovering the Himalaya'' (Indus Publishing, 2002) p500</ref>\n*A group of four surfers became the first to ride the 15 foot breaker at [[Kaena Point]] in [[Hawaii]], described in at least one source as \"the final big-wave frontier\".<ref>Matt Warshaw, ''The Encyclopedia of Surfing'' (Houghton Mifflin Harcourt, 2005) p265</ref>\n*Seven-year old Patrick Toner was killed by an [[Provisional Irish Republican Army|IRA]] booby trap bomb near his home in [[Forkhill]], [[Northern Ireland]] <ref name=\"cain.ulst.ac.uk\">http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/sutton/chron/1975.html</ref> \n*'''Died:''' [[Thomas Hart Benton (painter)|Thomas Hart Benton]], 85, known for his painting of [[mural]]s across the United States, died the day after completing his final work, entitled ''The Sources of Country Music''.<ref>Lawrence O. Christensen, ''Dictionary of Missouri Biography'' (University of Missouri Press, 1999) p64</ref>\n\n==[[January 20]], 1975 (Monday)==\n* Work was abandoned on the [[United Kingdom|British]] end of the [[Channel Tunnel]].  The House of Commons approved cancellation of the project, 294-218, after Environment Secretary [[Anthony Crosland]] said that the nation could no longer afford the cost, which had increased to $4.6 billion.<ref>\"Majority of 76 for decision to drop Chunnel project\", ''Glasgow Herald'', January 21, 1975, p3</ref>  Crosland, 56, said that he expected that the tunnel would be finished during his lifetime,<ref>\"Channel Tunnel Plan Shelved\", ''Milwaukee Journal'', January 21, 1975, p7</ref> but he died two years later.  Work was restarted in 1986 as a private venture, and the tunnel was completed in 1994.<ref>Graham Anderson and Ben Roskrow, ''The Channel Tunnel Story'' (Taylor & Francis, 1994) p1</ref>\n*The [[Passamaquoddy people|Passamaquoddy]] and the [[Penobscot people|Penobscot]] Indian tribes received a major victory in their  lawsuit against the [[U.S. Department of the Interior]] and their claims against the [[State of Maine]], when U.S. District Judge [[Edward T. Gignoux]] ruled in [[Portland, Maine|Portland]] that the Interior Department had to intervene on their side in the case, based on the [[Nonintercourse Act]] of 1790.<ref>\"Maine Indians upheld in landmark suit against U.S.\", ''Bangor Daily News'', January 22, 1975, p1</ref>  The two small tribes would go on to obtain an $81,500,000 settlement and build a huge gambling empire.<ref>Kim Isaac Eisler, ''Revenge of the Pequots: How a Small Native American Tribe Created the World's Most Profitable Casino'' (University of Nebraska Press, 2002) p75</ref>\n*[[Life University]], founded by [[Sid E. Williams]] and located in [[Marietta, Georgia]], held its first classes, as Life Chiropractic College, with 22 students enrolled.  By 1995, it had more than 4,000 students.<ref>Sid E. Williams, ''Lasting Purpose: A Mindset for Success'' (HCI, 1996) p147</ref>\n*[[Michael Ovitz]], [[Michael Rosenfeld]], Ron Meyer, Bill Haber, and Rowland Perkins founded the [[Creative Artists Agency]] after departing from the William Morris agency, and built CAA into one of the most powerful groups of sports agents and entertainment agents.<ref>Robert Slater, ''Ovitz: The Inside Story of Hollywood's Most Controversial Power Broker'' (McGraw Hill, 1997) p209</ref>\n*Provisional IRA member, Kevin Coen was killed by soldiers while attempting to hijack a bus in [[Kinawley]], Northern Ireland.<ref name=\"cain.ulst.ac.uk\"/>\n*'''Born:''' [[David Eckstein]], American MLB baseball player and 2006 World Series MVP; in [[Sanford, Florida]]\n*'''Died:''' [[Kay Summersby]], 66, wartime chauffeur for General Dwight Eisenhower who wrote about their extramarital relationship in her book, ''Past Forgetting''\n\n==[[January 21]], 1975 (Tuesday)==\n*In the English town of [[Todmorden]], Dr. [[Harold Shipman]], a young general practitioner, made a house call to 73-year-old widow Lily Crossley, who died half an hour after he left.  Later in the day, he visited Elizabeth Pearce, 84, who died a few minutes later of what he listed as a cerebral hemorrhage.  At the close of the day, he visited Robert Lingard, 63, who died minutes later of what Dr. Shipman described as a heart attack.<ref>Wensley Clarkson, ''The Good Doctor'' (Macmillan, 2002) pp60-61</ref> They were the first of hundreds of Dr. Shipman's patients to die after he treated them, until his arrest in 1998.  Officially, there were 215 confirmed victims, and he was suspected in the deaths of another 200.<ref>\"Shipman, Harold Frederick\", in ''The Encyclopedia of Serial Killers'' by Michael Newton (Infobase Publishing, 2006) pp239-241</ref>\n*The bodies of ten men and three women were found at Club Gargantua, a topless bar in [[Montreal]], victims of an apparent gangland slaying.  The club's manager was shot, and the entire group was herded into a storeroom, which was then padlocked and set afire.<ref>\"13 Slain Gang-Style At Bar In Montreal\",  ''Pittsburgh Press'', January 21, 1975, p1</ref>   The gangster suspected in the murders, Richard Blass, nicknamed \"The Cat\" for his ability to elude attempts on life and to escape jail three times, was killed three days later by Montreal police after going for his gun when he was cornered.<ref>\"Montreal Blaze Suspect Slain\",  ''Pittsburgh Press'', January 25, 1975, p3</ref>\n*The United States Supreme Court rendered its decision in ''[[Taylor v. Louisiana]]'', invalidating a Louisiana state law that exempted women from jury duty unless they specifically requested to be eligible.<ref>Sara Dubow, ''Ourselves Unborn: A History of the Fetus in Modern America'' (Oxford University Press, 2010) p211</ref>\n*The [[National Hockey League]] became the first American sports league to allow women journalists into the players' locker room for interviews, a privilege formerly reserved for men.  The NBA followed suit later in the year, with MLB and the NFL not admitting female reporters until later.<ref>Ray Gamache, ''A History of Sports Highlights: Replayed Plays from Edison to ESPN''  (McFarland, Jul 11, 2010) pp148-149</ref>  The two women included in the press at the game in Montreal (which the Wales Conference won 7-1 over the Campbell Conference), were Robin Herman of the ''[[New York Times]]'' and Marcelle St. Cyr of Montreal redio station CKLM.<ref>\"Everyone welcome\", ''Regina Leader-Post'', January 21, 1975, p23</ref>\n*Two would-be IRA bombers, John Kelly and John Stone, were killed when the bomb they are transporting detonates prematurely in Victoria Street, [[Belfast]], Northern Ireland. Only the bombers are killed in the explosion.<ref name=\"cain.ulst.ac.uk\"/>\n\n==[[January 22]], 1975 (Wednesday)==\n*Almost 50 years after it had been proposed, the United States ratified the Geneva Protocol of 1925, a treaty to ban use of poison gases in wartime as President Ford signed the measure.  The U.S. Senate had voted in favor of ratification, 93-0, on December 16, 1974.<ref>\"Started By Coolidge, Treaty Finally Law\",  ''Pittsburgh Press'', January 23, 1975, p1</ref>\n*[[Landsat 2]], the second in a series of American satellites designed to photograph images around the world, was launched from [[Vandenberg Air Force Base]] at 9:56 am.<ref>\"New Satellite Put Into Orbit To Film Earth\", ''Sarasota Herald-Tribune'',  January 23, 1975, p16-A</ref>  Nine days earlier, ERTS-1 (launched on [[July 1972|July 23, 1972]]) was renamed [[Landsat 1]] while in orbit above the Earth.  Landsat 2 was removed from service on February 25, 1982.<ref>Kali Charan Sahu, ''Textbook of Remote Sensing and Geographical Information Systems'' (Atlantic Publishers, 2007) p172</ref>\n*A crowd of 3,000 people, angry about the mishandling of flood relief by Governor Khlai Chitphithak of [[Nakhon Si Thammarat Province]] in [[Thailand]], attacked his official residence and burned it to the ground.  The Governor was able to escape the city and to flee to Bangkok.<ref>Benedict Anderson, ''The Spectre of Comparisons: Nationalism, Southeast Asia, and the World'' (Verso, 1998) p161</ref>\n* [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] will face [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]] in the English Soccer [[Football League Cup]] Final after the former defeat [[Chester City F.C.|Chester City]] 3-2 on the night and 5-4 on aggregate while the latter defeat [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] 1-0 on the night and 3-2 on aggregate in the second leg of their semi final ties. [[Brian Little (footballer)|Brian Little]], for Villa, and [[Colin Suggett]], for Norwich, are the winning goal scorers.<ref>http://www.statto.com/football/stats/results/1975-01-22</ref>\n\n==[[January 23]], 1975 (Thursday)==\n*Dr. [[Andreas Gruentzig]], a heart surgeon at the [[University of Zurich]], successfully inflated a double-lumen balloon [[catheter]] (which he had designed with his wife, assistant to her husband) to dilate the iliac artery of a dog without the side effects of creating an embolism.  Later in the year, on September 24, he would first test the method on a [[coronary artery]], and on September 16, 1976, he would use the technique for the first [[angioplasty]] on a human being.<ref>Adrian Thomas, et al., ''Classic Papers in Modern Diagnostic Radiology (Springer, 2005) p514</ref>\n*U.S. President Gerald Ford signed a proclamation for an eventual three-dollar per barrel fee on imported oil, with a one dollar fee effective on February 1, followed by similar increases on March 1 and April 1.  Ten northeastern States would receive rebates on the fees due to their heavier reliance on imported oil.  Congress voted to delay the increase for 90 days, and a federal court eventually ruled that the President did not have the power to implement fees independently of Congress.<ref>Yanek Mieczkowski, ''Gerald Ford and the Challenges of the 1970s'' (University Press of Kentucky, 2005) pp232-233; \"Ford Boosts Foreign Oil Tariff\", ''Pittsburgh Post-Gazette'', January 24, 1975, p1</ref>\n*The first measurement of astronomical data by an [[Occultation#Occultations by asteroids|asteroidal occultation]] took place as astronomers in North America gathered information from the passage of [[433 Eros]] between the Earth and the star [[Kappa Geminorum]].<ref>Stephen J. Edberg and David H. Levy, ''Observing Comets, Asteroids, Meteors, and the Zodiacal Light'' (Cambridge University Press, 1994) p103</ref>\n*'''Born:''' [[Tito Ortiz]], American martial artist; UFC light heavyweight champion, 2000 to 2003; in [[Santa Ana, California]]\n\n==[[January 24]], 1975 (Friday)==\n[[File:Keith Jarrett-commons.jpg|100px|right|thumb|Jarrett]]\n*[[Jazz]] [[pianist]] [[Keith Jarrett]] played the solo [[improvisation]] '[[The K\u00f6ln Concert]]' at the [[Cologne Opera]].  The live performance became the best-selling piano recording in history.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allaboutjazz.com/php/musician.php?id=7984 |title=Keith Jarrett - Biography |work=[[All About Jazz]] |accessdate=2011-04-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110318092416/http://www.allaboutjazz.com/php/musician.php?id=7984 |archivedate=2011-03-18 }}</ref><ref>David Davies, ''Philosophy of the Performing Arts'' (John Wiley & Sons, 2011) p135</ref>\n*Dr. [[Donald Coggan]] was made the new [[Archbishop of Canterbury]], the administrator of the Church of England.<ref>\"Anglicans Install 101st Archbishop\",  ''Pittsburgh Press'', January 24, 1975, p4</ref>\n*A bomb, planted by the Puerto Rican nationalist group FALN, killed 4 people and injured 58 at the Anglers Club in New York City.  The club was located in the dining room of the Frances Tavern, where George Washington had given his Farewell Address in 1783.  A note from the group said that the bombing was in retaliation for a blast on January 11 in [[Mayag\u00fcez]], which the FALN said had been placed by the CIA, and had killed 2 people and injured 11.<ref>\"N.Y. Bomb Kills 4, Injures 40\",  ''Pittsburgh Press'', January 25, 1975, p1; David N. Bossie, ''Hillary: The Politics of Personal Destruction'' (Thomas Nelson Inc, 2008)</ref>\n*Dr. [[Jeffrey MacDonald]] was arrested at his home in [[Huntington Beach, California]] after being indicted by a federal grand jury in North Carolina, for the February 17, 1970 murders of his wife and two daughters while he had been in the U.S. Army.  Murder charges had been brought against MacDonald but dropped that year for lack of evidence.  MacDonald maintained that the killings had been done by four hippies who chanted \"Acid is groovy, kill the pigs\" before beating him unconscious, and that he had woken to find his family dead.<ref>\"Ex-Army Doctor Arrested Again In Family Killing\", ''Pittsburgh Post-Gazette'', January 25, 1975, p2</ref>  MacDonald was freed on bail a week later.  His case came to trial in 1979, and he was found guilty of murder and sentenced to life imprisonment.  A federal court reversed the conviction in 1980 and MacDonald was freed on bail again, then re-arrested and imprisoned in 1982 after the verdict was upheld.<ref>Jerry Allen Potter and Fred Bost, ''Fatal Justice: Reinvestigating the MacDonald Murders'' (W. W. Norton & Company, 1997)</ref>\n*Only seven months after its launch, the [[Salyut 3]] space station was deorbited by the Soviet Union, a day after the secret test-firing of its defensive cannon.  It was later determined that the firing of the shells had not played a role in taking the station out of orbit.  Salyut 3 re-entered the atmosphere over the Pacific Ocean and burned up.<ref>Ben Evans, ''Foothold in the Heavens: The Seventies'' (Springer, 2010) p286; \"Salyut 3 Ends Mission, Burns in Space\", ''Milwaukee Sentinel'', January 25, 1975</ref>\n*British soldier Thomas Lea died eight months after being injured in an IRA bomb attack in Belfast, Northern Ireland.<ref name=\"cain.ulst.ac.uk\"/>\n*'''Died:''' [[Larry Fine]], 72, who had been one of [[The Three Stooges]] along with [[Moe Howard]] (who would die on May 4) and [[Curly Howard]]\n\n==[[January 25]], 1975 (Saturday)==\n*[[Sheikh Mujibur Rahman]], the first [[President of Bangladesh]], declared a state of emergency and was authorized to rule by decree.  Shortly afterward, the legislature, dominated by the [[Awami League]] party, banned all opposition political parties.<ref>Craig Baxter and Syedur Rahman, ''Historical Dictionary of Bangladesh''  (Scarecrow Press, 2003) p20</ref>\n*Liverpool's defence of the English Soccer F A cup ended in the fourth round when they were defeated 0-1 at Ipswich Town with a goal from [[Mick Mills]]. Eventual cup winners, West Ham were held to a 1-1 draw in their tie against [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]].<ref>http://www.statto.com/football/stats/results/1975-01-25</ref>\n*'''Born:''' \n**[[Ricky Rodriguez]], described by the [[Family International]] cult as the first product of \"[[flirty fishing]]\" and heir apparent to cult leader [[David Berg]] (d. 2005)\n**[[Tim Montgomery]], American track athlete, 2000 Olympic gold medalist; in [[Gaffney, South Carolina]]\n\n==[[January 26]], 1975 (Sunday)==\n*[[Immaculata University]] defeated the [[University of Maryland]] 80-48 in the first nationally televised [[women's basketball]] game in the [[United States]].<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=TYZPAAAAIBAJ&sjid=iQUEAAAAIBAJ&pg=3918,4742960&dq=immaculata&hl=en \"Women Cagers Make TV Debut\"], ''Ocala (FL) Star-Banner\", January 27, 1975, p2B</ref>\n*In what the ''New York Times'' described as [[1975 Thai general election|\"Thailand's freest and fairest national election in history]], the winners were divided among 22 political parties for the 269 seat House of Representatives.<ref>\"Thailand's Free Election\", ''New York Times'', February 3, 1975</ref>  The [[Democrat Party (Thailand)|Democrat Party]] won 72 of the available seats, or roughly 27%, and [[Seni Pramoj]] formed a coalition government that would last only two weeks, before he was replaced by his brother.<ref>Takashi Shiraishi and P. N. Abinales,''After the Crisis: Hegemony, Technocracy and Governance in Southeast Asia'' (Trans Pacific Press, 2005) p28</ref>\n*The [[Order of Australia]] was created.<ref>Christopher McCreery, ''The Order of Canada: its origins, history, and development'' (University of Toronto Press, 2005)</ref>\n*An IRA booby trap bomb, left at the Air Training Corps premises in Belfast, Northern Ireland killed sixteen-year-old cadet, Edward Wilson.<ref name=\"cain.ulst.ac.uk\"/>\n\n==[[January 27]], 1975 (Monday)==\n*The U.S. Senate voted 82-4 to establish its own special committee to investigate the CIA, with Frank Church of Idaho as the chairman.<ref>L. Britt Snider, ''Agency and the hill: the cia's relationship with congress'' (Government Printing Office, Aug 7, 2008) p34</ref>\n\n==[[January 28]], 1975 (Tuesday)==\n*[[Japan]] and the [[Soviet Union]] signed an agreement for a joint venture of drilling for oil on [[Sakhalin Island]], former Japanese territory that became part of the USSR.  In return for funding of the development, Japan would receive \"a significant discount on half of the pumped oil\" for ten years.<ref>Werner D. Lippert, ''The Economic Diplomacy of Ostpolitik: Origins of NATO's Energy Dilemma'' (Berghahn Books, 2010) p169</ref>\n*'''Died:''' \n**[[Anton\u00edn Novotn\u00fd]], 70, President of Czechoslovakia 1957-1968\n**[[Arthur Judson]], 93, artists' manager for New York Philharmonic and Philadelphia Orchestra and a co-founder of the Columbia Broadcasting System\n\n==[[January 29]], 1975 (Wednesday)==\n*The [[Weatherman (organization)|Weather Underground]] bombed the U.S. [[State Department]] main office in [[Washington, D.C.]].<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=_UE0AAAAIBAJ&sjid=x-sFAAAAIBAJ&pg=1310,3707494&dq=weather+underground&hl=en \"State Department Bombed\"], ''Miami News'', January 28, 1975, p1</ref>\n*Seventeen-year-old Robert McCullough, a Catholic, was killed by the [[Ulster Defence Association|UDA]] at his workplace in Belfast, Northern Ireland. The murder was thought to be a random sectarian retaliation for the murder of a teenage Protestant in an IRA bomb three days earlier.<ref name=\"cain.ulst.ac.uk\"/>\n*'''Born:''' [[Sara Gilbert]], American TV actress ([[Roseanne (TV series)|''Roseanne'']]) and panelist ([[The Talk (U.S. TV series)|''The Talk'']]); as Sara Rebecca Abeles in [[Santa Monica, California]]\n\n==[[January 30]], 1975 (Thursday)==\n*A professor of architecture in [[Budapest]] applied to the patent office in [[Hungary]] for his invention, which he called ''Terbeli logikai jatek'' (\"Spatial logic game\") [[Rubik's Cube|''B\u0171v\u00f6s Kocka'']] (\"Magic Cube\").  Patent #HU 170,062 was granted on March 28, 1977 to [[Ern\u0151 Rubik]].  <ref>[https://www.wired.com/2009/01/dayintech-0130/ \"Jan. 30, 1975: Rubik Applies for Patent on Magic Cube\", ''This Day in Tech'', ''Wired'' magazine, January 30, 2009</ref> <ref>[https://www.lens.org/lens/patent/040-568-871-927-77X HU 170062 B\"], Lens.org, Queensland University of Technology</ref> <ref>[https://www.hipo.gov.hu/en/node/2744 \"Rubik Ern\u0151: T\u00e9rbeli logikai j\u00e1t\u00e9k\"], Hungarian Intellectual Property Office (in Hungarian)</ref>\n*[[Turkish Airlines Flight 345]] fell into the Sea of Marmara while coming in for a landing in [[Istanbul]].  Electric power at the airport failed as the plane, arriving from [[Izmir]] was descending, and the pilot abandoned the landing, and was circling when the jet fell from the sky.  All 38 passengers and the crew of 4 were killed.<ref>\"Turkish Jet Crashes; 41 Aboard\", ''Milwaukee Sentinel'', January 31, 1975, p1; [http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19750130-0 Aviation Safety Network]</ref>\n*The area around the wreckage of the gunboat [[USS Monitor|USS ''Monitor'']], which had sunk in 1862 off of [[Cape Hatteras, North Carolina]], was designated at the first [[National Marine Sanctuary]] in the United States.  The ship, which had fought the CSS Merrimac in the most famous naval battle of the American Civil War, had become an artificial reef over 110 years prior to its location on August 27, 1973.<ref>Paul R. Clancy, ''Ironclad: The Epic Battle, Calamitous Loss, and Historic Recovery of the USS Monitor'' (McGraw-Hill Professional, 2005) p31; \"Monitor Safe From Modern Ocean Peril\", ''Toledo Blade'', January 30, 1975, p7</ref>\n*The January 31 deadline for [[Draft evasion#Vietnam War|amnesty for draft dodgers]] who fled from the United States during the Vietnam War was extended to March 1.  To that time, about 7,400 of 137,000 eligible had participated in the program, which required one year of volunteer service to avoid prosecution.<ref>\"Ford Extends Clemency Plan 1 Month, ''Milwaukee Sentinel'', January 31, 1975, p3</ref>\n\n==[[January 31]], 1975 (Friday)==\n*The last victim, of the [[serial killer]] known as the \"Skid Row Slasher\", was claimed after Clyde Hay, a 43-year-old cash register repairman, was found dead in his home in Hollywood, California.  Hay was the killer's ninth victim in two months.  The first seven had been transients in Los Angeles.  Two days later, the killer was forced to flee during his next murder attempt, but left a clue that would end his spree. [[Vaughn Greenwood]] would be convicted on nine counts of first degree murder almost two years later.<ref>\"Greenwood, Vaughn Orrin\", in ''The Encyclopedia of Serial Killers'', by Michael Newton (Infobase Publishing, 2006) pp101-102</ref>\n*Twenty-seven people on board the Greek oil tanker SS ''Corinthos'' were killed after their ship was struck by the American freighter ''Edgar M. Queeny''.  The ''Corinthos'' had been docked at [[Marcus Hook, Pennsylvania]], and was  unloading its cargo of crude oil at a dockside refinery operated by [[British Petroleum]], when it was struck by the freighter, which was making a course change.<ref>\"Two Dead, 25 Missing As Ship Rams Tanker\", ''Sarasota (FL) Herald-Tribune'', February 1, 1975, p1</ref>\n*[[Royal Ulster Constabulary|RUC]] Constable George Coulter was shot dead by the IRA while at a mobile Police patrol near [[Dungannon]], Northern Ireland. He is the ninth and last official Northern Ireland troubles related fatality during the month and the only Police Officer killed<ref name=\"cain.ulst.ac.uk\"/>\n*'''Born:''' [[Preity Zinta]], Indian film actress, in [[Shimla]], [[Himachal Pradesh]] state.\n*'''Died:''' \n**[[Bernard Fitzalan-Howard, 16th Duke of Norfolk]], 66, the [[Earl Marshal]] of the United Kingdom who choreographed coronations, funerals and other state occasions\n**[[Ida May Fuller]], 100, former legal secretary and first American to ever receive social security benefits\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Events by month links}}\n\n[[Category:January|1975]]\n[[Category:1975|*1975-01]]\n[[Category:Months in the 1970s|*1975-01]]\n", "text_old": "{{Events by month|1975}}\n{{calendar|year=1975|month=January}}\n\nThe following events occurred in '''January 1975''':\n\n[[File:DengXiaoping.jpg|200px|left|thumb|January 17, 1975: Deng Xiaoping returns to power]]\n[[File:SpaceMountainMK.jpg|300px|right|thumb|January 15, 1975: Space Mountain roller coaster opens]]\n[[File:Landsat-1.jpg|200px|left|thumb|January 22, 1975: Landsat 2 launched into space]]\n\n==[[January 1]], 1975 (Wednesday)==\n*Former U.S. Attorney General [[John N. Mitchell]], former presidential Chief of Staff [[H. R. Haldeman]] and [[John Ehrlichman]] were found guilty by a jury or 9 women and 3 men, on charges of conspiracy, obstruction of justice, and perjury in the cover-up of the [[Watergate scandal]].  Robert C. Mardian, a fourth defendant, was found guilty on one count of conspiracy.<ref>\"4 EX-NIXON AIDES CONVICTED, FACE LONG COVERUP TERMS\", ''Pittsburgh Press'', January 2, 1975, p1</ref><ref>\"Tapes Tipped the Scales\", ''Milwaukee Journal'', January 2, 1975, p1</ref>\n*In college football, the previously-undefeated Alabama Crimson Tide, ranked #1 in the UPI poll and #2 by the AP, lost to #9 Notre Dame, 13-11, in the Orange Bowl, giving Irish coach [[Ara Parseghian]] a victory in his final game.<ref>\"End Of Ara Era: Irish Stem Tide\", ''Pittsburgh Press'', January 2, 1975, p41</ref>  The #5 USC Trojans, going for a 2-point conversion rather than kicking an extra point, defeated #3 Ohio State (#2 in UPI), 18-17, to win the Rose Bowl before a crowd of 106,000.<ref>\"Trojans Disdain Tie in 18-17 Victory\", ''Milwaukee Journal'', January 2, 1975, p2-1</ref> Oklahoma University, ranked #1 by the AP, and was ineligible for a bowl and for a ranking in the UPI Coaches' Poll, while #4 Michigan was not invited to a bowl.\n*The [[Khmer Rouge]] began the campaign that would put it in control of [[Cambodia]], cutting off the supply lines to [[Phnom Penh]].<ref name=Kissinger>Henry Kissinger, ''Years of Renewal'' (Simon and Schuster, 2000) p502</ref>\n*Knighthood was conferred by [[Queen Elizabeth II]] on comedian [[Charlie Chaplin]], author [[P. G. Wodehouse]], athlete [[Roger Bannister]], and cricket legend [[Gary Sobers]].<ref>\"Charlie Chaplin, P.G. Wodehouse Knighted\", ''St. Petersburg Times'', January 2, 1975, p2-A</ref>\n*In fiction, the 2000 novel ''[[White Teeth]]'', by [[Zadie Smith]], opens with  Archie Jones making an attempt at suicide on January 1, 1975.<ref>Zadie Smith, ''White Teeth: A Novel'' (Random House, 2000) p3</ref>\n*The new Constitution of Sweden came into effect.<ref>Heather Knowles, ''Passport Series: Western Europe'' (Lorenz Educational Press, 2010) p149</ref>\n\n==[[January 2]], 1975 (Thursday)==\n*[[Lalit Narayan Mishra]], the Railway Minister of India, was assassinated as he attended a ceremony to dedicate a new railway line at [[Samastipur]] in the [[Bihar]] State.  Mishra was fatally injured by a bomb that had been placed under the speaker's [[dais]], in a blast that killed another person and injured 23 other people, and died the next day.<ref>\"Blast Kills Rail Chief in India\", ''Milwaukee Journal'', January 3, 1975, p1-2</ref>  Members of the terrorist group [[Ananda Marg]] claimed responsibility for the blast, aiming to retaliate for the imprisonment of their leader, [[Prabhat Ranjan Sarkar]].<ref>Sean Anderson and Stephen Sloan, ''Historical Dictionary of Terrorism (Scarecrow Press, 2009) p20</ref>\n*Bangladesh Marxist leader [[Siraj Sikder]] was arrested, then shot and killed on orders by that nation's president, [[Sheikh Mujibur Rahman]].  Mujibur himself would be assassinated seven months later.<ref>S. Mahmud Ali, ''Understanding Bangladesh'' (Columbia University Press, 2010) p305</ref>\n*The bill approving the [[Federal Rules of Evidence]] was signed into law by U.S. President Ford.<ref>\"Who's Making the Rules Around Here Anyway?\", by Cary H. Copeland, ''ABA Journal'' (May 1976) p665</ref>\n*The [[World Tourism Organization]] (WTO) was established by the [[United Nations]], replacing the International Union of Official Travel Organizations (IUOTO).<ref>Edmund Jan Osma\u0144czyk and Anthony Mango, ''Encyclopedia of the United Nations and Agreements'', Volume 4 (Taylor & Francis, 2003) p2757</ref>\n*The [[1974 USC Trojans football team|USC Trojans]] were ranked #1 in the final UPI [[college football]] poll, taken of college coaches, giving them a share of the mythical national championship.<ref>\"Southern Cal Ranked No. 1\", ''Milwaukee Journal'', January 2, 1975, p2-10</ref>\n*'''Died:''' [[Chilaiditi syndrome|Dimitrios Chiladiti]], 91, Greek radiologist\n\n==[[January 3]], 1975 (Friday)==\n*The [[1974 Oklahoma Sooners football team|University of Oklahoma Sooners]] were given the number 1 ranking in the final AP sportswriters poll of the [[1974 college football season]], and a share of the unofficial national college football championship.  The Sooners had been the only undefeated and untied team, but had been ineligible for postseason play, and were not included in the UPI coaches' poll. The USC Trojans, #1 in UPI, were 2nd in the AP poll.<ref>\"Oklahoma Picked No. 1\", ''Milwaukee Sentinel'', January 4, 1975, p2-3</ref>\n*In the largest return in history of U.S. government land to an American Indian tribe, 250 square miles of the [[Grand Canyon National Monument]] were deeded back to the [[Havasupai people]] with the signing of a bill by President Ford.  The 400 members of the tribe had been limited to a reservation of only 518 acres, less than one square mile, at the bottom of Havasu Canyon, since 1882.  The legislation also enlarged the National Park by adding 687,000 acres to bring its total size to 1,875 square miles.<ref>Todd R. Berger, ''It Happened at Grand Canyon'' (Globe Pequot, 2007) p126</ref>\n*'''Died:''' [[Milton Cross]], 77, announcer since 1931 for the weekly radio broadcasts of the [[Metropolitan Opera]].  Cross, known to his fans as \"Mr. Opera\", was preparing for the next day's show when he collapsed at his home.\n\n==[[January 4]], 1975 (Saturday)==\n*[[Henry Boucha]] of the [[Minnesota North Stars]], who had been the NHL's Rookie of the Year two years earlier, suffered a career ending eye injury after being high-sticked by [[Dave Forbes]] of the [[Boston Bruins]] during Boston's 8-0 win.  Forbes would become the first American professional athlete to be criminally indicted for a crime committed in the course of a game, although the trial ended in a hung jury.  In 1980, Boucha settled a lawsuit against Forbes, the Bruins and the NHL for $1,500,000.<ref>\nStanley H. Teitelbaum, ''Sports Heroes, Fallen Idols'' (University of Nebraska Press, 2008) p204</ref>\n*U.S. President [[Gerald R. Ford]] signed legislation making 55 miles per hour the maximum speed limit across the United States, making permanent what had been a temporary order in 1973 by President Nixon.<ref>\"Ford Makes 55 mph Permanent, Signs Bill To Aid Jobless\", ''Pittsburgh Press'', January 5, 1975, p1</ref>\n*Executive Order 11828 created the Commission on CIA Activities within the United States, chaired by U.S. Vice-President [[Nelson Rockefeller]].<ref>W. Thomas Smith, ''[[Encyclopedia of the Central Intelligence Agency]]'' (Infobase Publishing, 2003) p90</ref>\n*[[Wimbledon F.C.|Wimbledon]] become the first non league club to win at a [[Football League First Division|First Division]] club in the [[1974\u201375 FA Cup|F A cup]] third round since the creation of the [[Football League Third Division|Third Division]] in [[1920\u201321 in English football|1920]]. [[Altrincham F.C.|Altrincham]] almost achieve the same objective when holding [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] to a draw. Thirty-one of the Thirty-two ties take place with cup holders, [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] defeating [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke]] while [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham]] win at [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] at the start of their ultimately victorious cup run.<ref>http://www.statto.com/football/stats/results/1975-01-04</ref>\n*'''Died:''' \n**[[Bob Montana]], 54, American comic strip artist who created the characters in [[Archie Comics]]\n**[[Carlo Levi]], 71, Italian novelist and legislator\n\n==[[January 5]], 1975 (Sunday)==\n*''[[The Wiz]]'', a musical adaptation of ''[[The Wonderful Wizard of Oz]]'' with an African-American cast, opened on Broadway.  It would go on to win two Tony Awards and run for 1,672 performances.<ref>Michael Patrick Hearn, ed., ''The Annotated Wizard of Oz'' (W. W. Norton & Company, 2000)</ref>\n*The [[Tasman Bridge]] in [[Tasmania]], [[Australia]], [[Tasman Bridge disaster|was struck]] by the bulk ore carrier ''Lake Illawarra'', killing 12 people.   The ship struck a support on the mile-long bridge at about 9:00 pm, bringing down a {{convert|240|ft|m|adj=mid|-long}} section on top of it, and sank.  Three vehicles on the bridge plunged into the [[River Derwent (Tasmania)|River Derwent]] below.<ref>\"5 Die As Ship Hits Aussie Span, Sinks\", ''Pittsburgh Post-Gazette'', January 6, 1975, p1</ref>\n*The leaders of the three military groups fighting for the independence of Angola- Jonas Savimbi of UNITA, Agostinho Neto of MPLA, and Holden Roberto of FNLA- signed the Mombasa Agreement in Kenya's capital, under the sponsorship of President Jomo Kenyatta, pledging to work together to negotiate with Portugal.  The united front lasted only a few months, after the United States allied with UNITA and the Soviet Union assisted the MPLA.<ref>W. Martin James III, ''A Political History of the Civil War in Angola, 1974-1990'' (Transaction Publishers, 2011) p55</ref><ref name=Angola>W. Martin James, ''Historical Dictionary of Angola'' (Scarecrow Press, 2011) p169</ref>\n*'''Born:''' \n**[[Mike Grier]], the first African-American NHL player (1996\u20132011) to be born and trained in the United States; in [[Detroit]]; \n**[[Warrick Dunn]], American NFL running back, in [[Baton Rouge]], [[Louisiana]]\n**[[Bradley Cooper]], American TV actor (''Alias''), in [[Philadelphia]]\n*'''Died:''' \n**[[Don Wilson (baseball)|Don Wilson]], 29, American MLB pitcher for the Houston Astros (1966\u20131974), by carbon monoxide poisoning\n**[[Gottlob Berger]], 79, convicted German SS General and Nazi war criminal who spent six years at Spandau prison\n**[[Rudolf Demme]], 80, German Panzer division general who spent ten years in a Soviet prison\n\n==[[January 6]], 1975 (Monday)==\n*The game show ''[[Wheel of Fortune (US daytime game show)|Wheel of Fortune]]'', created by [[Merv Griffin]] and inspired by the children's game [[Hangman (game)|\"Hangman\"]], premiered on [[NBC]] at 10:30 am Eastern time.  The original hosts were [[Chuck Woolery]] and [[Susan Stafford]], who would be replaced in 1982 by [[Pat Sajak]] and [[Vanna White]], respectively.<ref>Horace Newcomb, ''Encyclopedia of Television'' (CRC Press, 2004) p2527</ref>\n*After the sale of gold was legalized in the United States, for the first time since 1933, on December 31, the U.S. Treasury conducted its first auction of a part of its gold reserves, setting aside an unprecedented 2,000,000 ounces for sale, in individual 400 ounce gold bricks, valued at $70,000 apiece based on the European market price of $175 an ounce.  The first sealed bid that was opened was for $156 an ounce by the investment firm of Austern and Paul.<ref>\"Big gold auction opens to 200 bids\", ''Miami News'', January 6, 1975, p1</ref>\n*''[[AM America]]'', which would later be replaced by ''[[Good Morning America]]'', made its television debut on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] at 7:00 am Eastern time.  Intended to compete against the ''Today'' show and ''The CBS Morning News'', the news series was hosted by [[Bill Beutel]], with co-hosts [[Stephanie Edwards (TV personality)|Stephanie Edwards]] and [[Peter Jennings]].\n*''[[Another World (TV series)|Another World]]'', an afternoon soap opera airing on NBC since 1964 as a 30-minute show, expanded to 60 minutes.  It was the first ongoing attempt of a U.S. serial to air in a time slot of that length, and would be the beginning of a wave of other soaps expanding to 60-minute lengths.  The last long-running 30-minute serial to expand to 60 minutes would be ''[[The Young and the Restless]]'' in 1980.\n*An attempt by [[Malcolm Forbes]] to become the first person to fly a balloon across the Atlantic Ocean, ended before it started.  Multimillionaire publisher Forbes and aerospace scientist Thomas Heinsheimer were preparing to lift off from [[Santa Ana, California]] in the ''Windborne'' for a 7,000 mile trip.<ref>\"2 Safe As Balloons Burst\", ''Pittsburgh Press'', January 6, 1975, p1</ref>\n*'''Born:''' [[Ricardo Santos (beach volleyball)|Ricardo Santos]], Brazilian beach volleyball player, and 2004 Olympic gold medalist; in [[Salvador, Bahia]], [[Brazil]]\n*'''Died:''' [[Burton K. Wheeler]], 92, isolationist U.S. Senator for Montana from 1923 to 1947\n\n==[[January 7]], 1975 (Tuesday)==\n*The South Vietnamese province of [[Phuoc Binh]] became the first to be captured by Viet Cong invaders, who led an assault with tanks and three infantry divisions.<ref>\"Viet Reds Capture An Entire Province\", ''Pittsburgh Press'', January 4, 1975, p1</ref>  Out of 5,400 South Vietnamese Army defenders, only 850 survived, and twenty Vietnam Air Force planes were shot down; local officials were summarily executed.<ref>Spencer Tucker, ''Vietnam'' (UCL Press, 1999)</ref>   U.S. Secretary of State [[Henry Kissinger]] would later write, \"Phuoc Binh was the test case\" for the North Vietnamese government to decide whether to proceed with trying to conquer South Vietnam, and \"If the United States reacted, there was still a chance for Hanoi to withdraw from the brink.\" <ref name=Kissinger/>\n*The [[Louisiana Tech Lady Techsters basketball|women's basketball team of Louisiana Tech]], which would go on to win three national championships and more than 80% of its games, played its very first game, and lost, 59-55, to visiting [[Southeastern Louisiana University]].<ref>''Louisiana Tech Lady Techsters Basketball 2010-11 Media Guide'', p122</ref> The crowd for the first was about 45 people.<ref>Kim Mulkey, ''Won't Back Down: Teams, Dreams, and Family'' (Da Capo Press, 2008) p20</ref>\n\n==[[January 8]], 1975 (Wednesday)==\n*''[[The Boston Globe]]'' broke an exclusive story that Soviet leader [[Leonid Brezhnev]] was going to arrive in Boston's [[Dana\u2013Farber Cancer Institute|Sidney Farber Cancer Center]] to receive treatment for [[leukemia]].<ref>\"Brezhnev reportedly coming to Boston cancer center today\", ''Boston Globe'', January 8, 1975, p1</ref>  The hospital, the Kremlin and the White House quickly denied the story <ref>\"Brezhnev Boston trip denied\", ''Miami News'', January 8, 1975, p1; \"Cancer story 'false'\", ''Ottawa Citizen'', January 7, 1975, p4</ref> and the ''Globe'' soon admitted that it had been the victim of a hoax.<ref>\"Boston Fooled by Hoax on Brezhnev Visit\", ''Milwaukee Journal'', January 30, 1975, p4</ref>  Brezhnev, who did not have leukemia and who was not coming to the United States, would live on until 1982.\n*After [[South Vietnam]]'s Phuoc Long province had been conquered without any intervention by the United States, the Politburo of North Vietnam's Communist Party approved \"Campaign 275\", to \"liberate\" the rest of South Vietnam, starting with a full-scale attack on the Central Highlands.  Party First Secretary [[L\u00ea Du\u1ea9n]]  ordered strikes on [[Bu\u00f4n Ma Thu\u1ed9t]], [[Tuy H\u00f2a]], [[Qui Nh\u01a1n]], [[Hu\u1ebf]] and [[Da Nang]].<ref>J. Edward Lee and Toby Haynsworth, ''Nixon, Ford, and the Abandonment of South Vietnam'' (McFarland, 2002) p83</ref>\n*[[Ella Grasso]] became [[Governor of Connecticut]], the first female U.S. governor who did not succeed her husband.<ref>\"Mrs. Grasso Sees Hard Times Ahead\", ''Milwaukee Journal'', January 9, 1975, p3</ref>\n*Convicted Watergate conspirators [[John W. Dean III]], [[Jeb Stuart Magruder]] and [[Herbert W. Kalmbach]] were released from prison after serving sentences ranging from four months to seven months.<ref>\"Sirica Frees Dean, 2 Others in Scandal\", ''Milwaukee Journal'', January 8, 1975, p1</ref>\n*'''Died:''' \n**[[Richard Tucker]], 61, American operatic tenor, while on tour with the Metropolitan Opera\n**[[David Marshall Williams|David \"Carbine\" Williams]], 74, inventor of M-1 carbine rifle, portrayed by Jimmy Stewart in the 1952 film ''[[Carbine Williams]]''\n\n==[[January 9]], 1975 (Thursday)==\n*Denmark's Liberal Party, led by Prime Minister [[Poul Hartling]], gained seats in the election for the Parliament, the 179 seat Folketing, to increase its share to 42 members.  The Social Democrats gained as well, winning 53 seats.<ref>\"Danes Vote; Coalition May Result\", ''Milwaukee Journal'', January 10, 1975, p4</ref>\n*A mountain in Mexico called the Mountain of Butterflies where many monarch butterflies go at wintertime is discovered.\n*\"The Beatles & Co., Ltd.\", the corporation created by [[John Lennon]], [[Paul McCartney]], [[George Harrison]] and [[Ringo Starr]] to pay them as employees in order to effect a savings on taxes, was formally dissolved by a court in London, four years after McCartney had filed suit in the year after the band's breakup.<ref>Peter Doggett, ''You Never Give Me Your Money: The Beatles After the Breakup'' (HarperCollins, 2010) p28</ref>\n*'''Died:''' \n**[[Li Fuchun]], 74, Communist Chinese economic planner\n**[[Virginia Ellis Jenckes]], 77, U.S. Representative, 1933\u201339 and first woman to represent Indiana in Congress\n**[[Pierre Fresnay]], 77, French actor\n\n==[[January 10]], 1975 (Friday)==\n*[[Pope Paul VI]] broke a 900-year-old policy by accepting a woman as an envoy from to the Vatican.  [[Bernadette Olowo]] was appointed by [[Uganda]], which had 3.5 million Roman Catholics, more than any other nation in Africa, and was also that nation's ambassador to [[West Germany]].  A spokesman for the Vatican said, \"The acceptance of a woman ambassador will be subject to the same rules as men,\" including good moral behavior and compliance with for Roman Catholic doctrine.  The year before, the Pope had rejected an Australian nomination of a woman ambassador because she was a divorcee.  Forty years earlier, [[Pope Pius XI]] had declared that women should not work at any occupation outside of the home.<ref>\"First female envoy gets Pope's approval\", ''St. Petersburg Times'', January 11, 1975, p5-B</ref>\n*The [[Queen Elizabeth 2]] began its first round-the-world cruise, departing New York City under tight security with 1,200 passengers.<ref>\"Security Tight as Luxury Ship Starts Journey\", ''Milwaukee Journal'', January 11, 1975, p2</ref>\n*'''Born:''' [[Jake Delhomme]], American NFL quarterback, in [[Breaux Bridge, Louisiana]]\n\n==[[January 11]], 1975 (Saturday)==\n*[[Soyuz 17]], with Soviet cosmonauts [[Aleksei Gubarev]] and [[Georgi Grechko]], both 43 and making their first flights, lifted off from the Baikonur space center and docked successfully with the [[Salyut 4]] space station, becoming the first men to occupy it.<ref>\"2 Cosmonauts Settle Into Salyut 4 'Home'\", ''Pittsburgh Post-Gazette'', January 13, 1975, p3</ref>  They would return to Earth on February 7 after setting a new record for most days (28) spent in outer space.<ref>Philip Baker, ''The Story of Manned Space Stations: An Introduction'' (Springer, 2007) p53</ref>\n*The last remains of the rocket that had launched [[Skylab]] into orbit in 1973, re-entered the atmosphere and burned up at about 3:00 pm EST.<ref>\"Remains of Rocket End Journey\", ''Milwaukee Journal'', January 11, 1975, p3</ref>\n*[[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]] defeat [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]] 2-0 to maintain a one-point lead in the English Soccer First Division with sixteen games remaining. [[Roger Osborne]] and [[David Johnson (footballer born 1951)|David Johnson]] are the goal scorers. \n*'''Died:''' [[Paul Peter Meouchi]], 80, Lebanese Maronite priest and first Maronite to serve in the Vatican's college of cardinals\n\n==[[January 12]], 1975 (Sunday)==\n*The [[Pittsburgh Steelers]] defeated the [[Minnesota Vikings]] 16\u20136 at [[Tulane Stadium]] in [[New Orleans, Louisiana]], to win [[Super Bowl IX]] and their first NFL championship in their 42-year history.  The Steelers led 2-0 at halftime after Dwight White sacked Vikings' quarterback [[Fran Tarkenton]] in the end zone, and only 9-6 in the last quarter until Pittsburgh drove to another touchdown late in the game.<ref>\"SUPER STEELERS WIN, 16-6\", ''Pittsburgh Post-Gazette'', January 13, 1975, p1</ref>\n*Caryn Campbell vanished while walking from the lobby to her room at the Wildwood Inn at [[Snowmass, Colorado]].  She was the 15th victim of serial killer [[Ted Bundy]], but the first for whose murder he ever stood trial.<ref>\nKevin M. Sullivan, ''The Bundy Murders: A Comprehensive History'' (McFarland, 2009) pp119-124</ref>\n*[[Maharishi Mahesh Yogi]], guru of the [[Transcendental Meditation]] movement, declared to a gathering of thousands of his followers, at [[Hertenstein, Lucerne|Hertenstein]], on [[Lake Lucerne]] in Switzerland, that the dawn of the new Age of Enlightenment had arrived.<ref>Bob Oates, ''Celebrating the Dawn: Maharishi Mahesh Yogi and the TM Technique'' (Putnam, 1976) p57</ref>\n\n==[[January 13]], 1975 (Monday)==\n*The Chrysler Corporation began offering rebates of up to $400 on specific models of new cars and light trucks in what was described as \"an unprecedented five week campaign\".  The move was driven by an inventory of 340,000 unsold 1975 models, with the incentive of paying customers rather than reducing the sticker price.<ref>\"Chrysler Rebates May Set Trend\", ''Milwaukee Journal'', January 8, 1975, p1</ref>\n*Terrorists attempted to shoot down an El Al airliner that was preparing to take off from Orly airport in Paris on a flight to New York with 136 passengers.  The missile failed to hit due to the pilot's evasive action, and struck a Yugoslavian DC-9 that had not yet boarded, but failed to explode.  A second attempt was made six days later, and the two tries were traced to the Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine, to Muamar Gadhafi, and to the international terrorist [[Ilich Ramirez Sanchez]] (Carlos).<ref>\nRuwantissa Abeyratne, ''Aviation Security Law'' (Springer, 2010) p30</ref>\n*The coldest [[wind chill]] ever recorded in North America was measured at [[Kugaaruk]],  in the [[Nunavut]] territory of [[Canada]] (formerly Pelly Bay, Northwest Territories).  An air temperature of -60&nbsp;\u00b0F and a wind speed of 35&nbsp;mph combined for a wind chill factor of -135&nbsp;\u00b0F (-78&nbsp;\u00b0C) <ref>Christopher C. Burt and Mark Stroud, ''Extreme Weather: A Guide & Record Book'' (W. W. Norton & Company, 2007) p58</ref>\n*In a crime that shocked all of [[India]], terrorists from the [[Mizo National Front]] (MNF) charged into the police headquarters at [[Aizawl]], capital of the [[Mizoram]] state, and murdered the three top officials- Inspector General G.S. Arya, Deputy Inspector Sewa and Police Superintendent Panchapakesan.<ref>\nSuhas Chatterjee, ''Making of Mizoram: Role of Laldenga'' (M.D. Publications Pvt. Ltd., 1994) p244</ref>\n\n==[[January 14]], 1975 (Tuesday)==\n*The [[House Un-American Activities Committee]], most notable for its investigations and accusations of Communist infiltration of Hollywood, was disbanded by the U.S. House of Representatives after 37 years.  In 1969, it had been renamed the \"Committee on Internal Security\".<ref>Richard Gid Powers, ''Not without Honor: The History of American Anticommunism'' (Yale University Press, 1998) p353; \"Democrats Vote to Abolish Security Committee\", ''Sarasota Herald-Tribune'', January 14, 1975, p5-A</ref>\n*U.S. Secretary of State [[Henry Kissinger]] announced that the Soviet Union was rescinding its agreement to a trade deal with the United States, eleven days after the [[Jackson\u2013Vanik amendment]] to the [[Trade Act of 1974]] had been signed into law.  The amendment, sponsored by U.S. Senator and Democratic presidential candidate [[Henry M. Jackson]] (as well as U.S. Representative [[Charles Vanik]]) provided that nations with \"non-market economies\" that restricted emigration were to be denied [[most favored nation]] status, and had been aimed at putting pressure on the Soviet Union to drop its opposition to allowing its Jewish citizens to emigrate.  Soviet First Secretary [[Leonid Brezhnev]] had sent a letter to U.S. President Ford on December 25, warning that the amendment was unacceptable.  The amendment had the opposite effect, with Jewish emigration decreasing by 35% between 1974 and 1975.<ref>Robert G. Kaufman, ''Henry M. Jackson: A Life in Politics'' (University of Washington Press, 2000) p280-281; \"Trade Pact Repudiated By Russia\", ''Pittsburgh Press'', January 15, 1975, p1</ref>\n*The [[Registration Convention|Convention on Registration of Launched Objects into Outer Space]], an international treaty requiring the signatory nations to keep the United Nations informed of the orbital details of any object launched into outer space, was signed in New York, and went into effect on September 15, 1976.<ref>Francis Lyall and Paul B. Larsen, ''Space Law: A Treatise'' (Ashgate Publishing, 2009) p85</ref>\n*U.S. Vice-President [[Nelson Rockefeller]] was named by President Ford to chair a special commission to investigate domestic spying by the [[Central Intelligence Agency]].<ref>Bruce P. Montgomery, ''Richard B. Cheney and the Rise of the Imperial Vice Presidency'' (ABC-CLIO, 2009) p29</ref>\n\n==[[January 15]], 1975 (Wednesday)==\n*The [[Alvor Agreement]] was signed at the Penina Golfe Hotel in [[Alvor (Portim\u00e3o)|Alvor]], [[Portugal]], by the chiefs of the three groups fighting for the independence of [[Angola]] (Savimbi, Neto and Roberto) and President Costa Gomes of [[Portugal]], after which the Portuguese government announced a date of November 11, 1975, for the independence of the colony of Portuguese West Africa as Angola.<ref name=Angola/><ref>\"Angola to Become Independent Nov. 11\", ''Pittsburgh Post-Gazette'', January 16, 1975, p4</ref><ref>Witney W. Schneidman, ''Engaging Africa: Washington and the Fall of Portugal's Colonial Empire'' (University Press of America, 2004) p198</ref>\n*[[Space Mountain (Magic Kingdom)|Space Mountain]], an enclosed roller coaster, operated in near darkness, opened at [[Walt Disney World]] in Florida, and later was duplicated at the other Disney parks.<ref>Susan Veness, ''The Hidden Magic of Walt Disney World'' (Adams Media, 2009) p54; \"Disney World Opens Space Mountain\", ''Lakeland (FL) Ledger'', January 17, 1975, p1D</ref>\n*CIA Director [[William Colby]] confirmed the reports from ''New York Times'' reporter [[Seymour Hersh]] and revealed to a U.S. Senate subcommittee that the agency had violated its charter by spying on American citizens for activities within the United States.<ref>\"CIA ADMITS SPYING INSIDE U.S.\", ''Pittsburgh Press'', January 15, 1975, p1; Frank J. Smist, Jr., ''Congress Oversees the United States Intelligence Community, 1947-1994'' (University of Tennessee Press, 1994) p27</ref>\n*'''Born:''' [[Mary Pierce]], Canadian-born French professional tennis player; winner of Australian Open, 1995, and French Open, 2000; in [[Montreal]]\n*'''Died:''' [[Ernest Koliqi]], 78, Albanian poet\n\n==[[January 16]], 1975 (Thursday)==\n[[File:Raymond burr ironside.JPG|100px|right|thumb|Ironside]] \n*A U.S. District Court jury awarded $12,000,000 to 1,200 anti-war demonstrators who had been illegally arrested on May 5, 1971 while they listened to a speech by Congressman [[Ronald Dellums]] of California at the U.S. Capitol.  The amount was ordered payable by the District of Columbia government, following the suit by the ACLU.  Many of the group had been detained at makeshift compounds, including the RFK Stadium.  The ACLU had located 900 of the named plaintiffs <ref>\"D.C. Protesters Get $12 Million\",  ''Pittsburgh Press'', January 17, 1975, p1; \"Calls Pour In For Share Of D.C. Suit\", ''Pittsburgh Press'', January 18, 1975, p3</ref>\n*The NBC television show [[Ironside (TV series)|''Ironside'']], starring [[Raymond Burr]] as wheelchair-bound police detective Robert Ironside, showed its 199th and final episode after a run of eight seasons.<ref>\"'Ironside' Ending Tonight\", ''Ocala (FL) Star-Banner'', January 16, 1975, p12B</ref>\n\n==[[January 17]], 1975 (Friday)==\n*At the first meeting of China's National People's Congress in ten years, [[Zhou Enlai]] was re-elected as Prime Minister, and [[Deng Xiaoping]], who had been in disgrace with the Communist Party for eight years, was elected as a Vice-Premier and Vice-Chairman of the party.  Yeh Chin-ying was made Defense Minister, filling a spot left vacant by the death of the vilified [[Lin Biao]].<ref>\"China Re-elects Ailing Chou\" ''Pittsburgh Press'', January 18, 1975, p1</ref>  A new Constitution for the People's Republic was promulgated on the same day.<ref>Xing Lu, ''Rhetoric of the Chinese Cultural Revolution: the Impact on Chinese Thought, Culture, and Communication'' University of South Carolina Press, 2004 p76</ref>\n*After the French Chamber of Deputies voted 284-189 in favor of legalization of abortion, the law proposed by [[Simone Veil]] went into effect, allowing abortion on demand during the first ten weeks of pregnancy.<ref>Melanie Latham, ''Regulating Reproduction: A Century of Conflict in Britain and France'' (Manchester University Press, 2002) p123</ref>\n*'''Born:''' [[Tony Brown (rugby union)|Tony Brown]], New Zealand rugby union football player, in [[Balclutha, New Zealand|Balclutha]]\n*'''Died:''' General [[Gustavo Rojas Pinilla]], 74, [[President of Colombia]] from 1953 to 1957\n\n==[[January 18]], 1975 (Saturday)==\n*The first of 253 episodes of ''[[The Jeffersons]]'' was telecast, as [[Sherman Hemsley]], [[Isabel Sanford]] and [[Mike Evans (actor)|Mike Evans]] took their recurring characters on ''[[All in the Family]]'' (George, Louise and Lionel Jefferson) to a spinoff TV series that would run for eleven seasons, concluding in 1985.<ref>James S. Olson, ''Historical Dictionary of the 1970s'' (Greenwood Publishing Group, 1999) p210</ref>\n*The derailment of a train near [[Cairo]] killed 27 persons in Egypt and injured 52.<ref>\"Derailment Kills 27\", ''Pittsburgh Press'', January 19, 1975, p1</ref>\n*Everton became the new leaders of the English Soccer First Division with 16 games remaining after a brace from [[Bob Latchford]] and an own goal from [[Archie Styles]] that secured a 3-0 victory at [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]]. Previous leader Ipwsich was defeated, 1-2, at [[Carlisle United F.C.|Carlisle United]].<ref>http://www.statto.com/football/stats/results/1975-01-18</ref>\n\n==[[January 19]], 1975 (Sunday)==\n[[File:US Atomic Energy Commission logo.jpg|150px|left|thumb|AEC out]]\n[[File:US-NuclearRegulatoryCommission-Logo.svg|150px|right|thumb|NRC in]]\n[[File:Seal of the United States Energy Research and Development Administration.png|150px|right|thumb|ERDA]]\n*The [[United States Atomic Energy Commission]] was split up into the [[Nuclear Regulatory Commission]] (NRC) and the [[Energy Research and Development Administration]] (ERDA), under the terms of the [[Energy Reorganization Act of 1974]].  The NRC assumed the functions of regulating private nuclear power plants, while ERDA oversaw nuclear weapons.<ref>Barton C. Hacker, ''Elements of Controversy: the Atomic Energy Commission and Radiation Safety in Nuclear Weapons Testing, 1947-1974'' (University of California Press, 1994) p254</ref>\n*Three Arab gunmen went to the observation deck at the [[Orly Airport]] in [[Paris]] and tried to shoot down at [[El Al]] 747 jumbo jet as it was taking off from Paris to [[Tel Aviv]] with 220 people on board.    After police prevented them from succeeding, the gunmen fired machine guns into the crowd and threw grenades, wounding 78 people, then took ten hostages.  After 17 hours, the men were allowed to depart on a flight to Iraq after freeing all of their hostages.<ref>\"ARABS FREE 10, FLY TO MIDDLE EAST\", ''Pittsburgh Press'', January 20, 1975, p1</ref>\n*[[1975 Kinnaur earthquake|A 6.8 magnitude earthquake]] struck in the state of [[Himachal Pradesh]], [[India]], at 1:30 pm local time, killing 47 people, mostly in the township of Kaurik.<ref>\"Quake Kills 14\" ''Pittsburgh Press'', January 20, 1975, p1; S. S. Negi, ''Discovering the Himalaya'' (Indus Publishing, 2002) p500</ref>\n*A group of four surfers became the first to ride the 15 foot breaker at [[Kaena Point]] in [[Hawaii]], described in at least one source as \"the final big-wave frontier\".<ref>Matt Warshaw, ''The Encyclopedia of Surfing'' (Houghton Mifflin Harcourt, 2005) p265</ref>\n*Seven-year old Patrick Toner was killed by an [[Provisional Irish Republican Army|IRA]] booby trap bomb near his home in [[Forkhill]], [[Northern Ireland]] <ref name=\"cain.ulst.ac.uk\">http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/sutton/chron/1975.html</ref> \n*'''Died:''' [[Thomas Hart Benton (painter)|Thomas Hart Benton]], 85, known for his painting of [[mural]]s across the United States, died the day after completing his final work, entitled ''The Sources of Country Music''.<ref>Lawrence O. Christensen, ''Dictionary of Missouri Biography'' (University of Missouri Press, 1999) p64</ref>\n\n==[[January 20]], 1975 (Monday)==\n* Work was abandoned on the [[United Kingdom|British]] end of the [[Channel Tunnel]].  The House of Commons approved cancellation of the project, 294-218, after Environment Secretary [[Anthony Crosland]] said that the nation could no longer afford the cost, which had increased to $4.6 billion.<ref>\"Majority of 76 for decision to drop Chunnel project\", ''Glasgow Herald'', January 21, 1975, p3</ref>  Crosland, 56, said that he expected that the tunnel would be finished during his lifetime,<ref>\"Channel Tunnel Plan Shelved\", ''Milwaukee Journal'', January 21, 1975, p7</ref> but he died two years later.  Work was restarted in 1986 as a private venture, and the tunnel was completed in 1994.<ref>Graham Anderson and Ben Roskrow, ''The Channel Tunnel Story'' (Taylor & Francis, 1994) p1</ref>\n*The [[Passamaquoddy people|Passamaquoddy]] and the [[Penobscot people|Penobscot]] Indian tribes received a major victory in their  lawsuit against the [[U.S. Department of the Interior]] and their claims against the [[State of Maine]], when U.S. District Judge [[Edward T. Gignoux]] ruled in [[Portland, Maine|Portland]] that the Interior Department had to intervene on their side in the case, based on the [[Nonintercourse Act]] of 1790.<ref>\"Maine Indians upheld in landmark suit against U.S.\", ''Bangor Daily News'', January 22, 1975, p1</ref>  The two small tribes would go on to obtain an $81,500,000 settlement and build a huge gambling empire.<ref>Kim Isaac Eisler, ''Revenge of the Pequots: How a Small Native American Tribe Created the World's Most Profitable Casino'' (University of Nebraska Press, 2002) p75</ref>\n*[[Life University]], founded by [[Sid E. Williams]] and located in [[Marietta, Georgia]], held its first classes, as Life Chiropractic College, with 22 students enrolled.  By 1995, it had more than 4,000 students.<ref>Sid E. Williams, ''Lasting Purpose: A Mindset for Success'' (HCI, 1996) p147</ref>\n*[[Michael Ovitz]], [[Michael Rosenfeld]], Ron Meyer, Bill Haber, and Rowland Perkins founded the [[Creative Artists Agency]] after departing from the William Morris agency, and built CAA into one of the most powerful groups of sports agents and entertainment agents.<ref>Robert Slater, ''Ovitz: The Inside Story of Hollywood's Most Controversial Power Broker'' (McGraw Hill, 1997) p209</ref>\n*Provisional IRA member, Kevin Coen was killed by soldiers while attempting to hijack a bus in [[Kinawley]], Northern Ireland.<ref name=\"cain.ulst.ac.uk\"/>\n*'''Born:''' [[David Eckstein]], American MLB baseball player and 2006 World Series MVP; in [[Sanford, Florida]]\n*'''Died:''' [[Kay Summersby]], 66, wartime chauffeur for General Dwight Eisenhower who wrote about their extramarital relationship in her book, ''Past Forgetting''\n\n==[[January 21]], 1975 (Tuesday)==\n*In the English town of [[Todmorden]], Dr. [[Harold Shipman]], a young general practitioner, made a house call to 73-year-old widow Lily Crossley, who died half an hour after he left.  Later in the day, he visited Elizabeth Pearce, 84, who died a few minutes later of what he listed as a cerebral hemorrhage.  At the close of the day, he visited Robert Lingard, 63, who died minutes later of what Dr. Shipman described as a heart attack.<ref>Wensley Clarkson, ''The Good Doctor'' (Macmillan, 2002) pp60-61</ref> They were the first of hundreds of Dr. Shipman's patients to die after he treated them, until his arrest in 1998.  Officially, there were 215 confirmed victims, and he was suspected in the deaths of another 200.<ref>\"Shipman, Harold Frederick\", in ''The Encyclopedia of Serial Killers'' by Michael Newton (Infobase Publishing, 2006) pp239-241</ref>\n*The bodies of ten men and three women were found at Club Gargantua, a topless bar in [[Montreal]], victims of an apparent gangland slaying.  The club's manager was shot, and the entire group was herded into a storeroom, which was then padlocked and set afire.<ref>\"13 Slain Gang-Style At Bar In Montreal\",  ''Pittsburgh Press'', January 21, 1975, p1</ref>   The gangster suspected in the murders, Richard Blass, nicknamed \"The Cat\" for his ability to elude attempts on life and to escape jail three times, was killed three days later by Montreal police after going for his gun when he was cornered.<ref>\"Montreal Blaze Suspect Slain\",  ''Pittsburgh Press'', January 25, 1975, p3</ref>\n*The United States Supreme Court rendered its decision in ''[[Taylor v. Louisiana]]'', invalidating a Louisiana state law that exempted women from jury duty unless they specifically requested to be eligible.<ref>Sara Dubow, ''Ourselves Unborn: A History of the Fetus in Modern America'' (Oxford University Press, 2010) p211</ref>\n*The [[National Hockey League]] became the first American sports league to allow women journalists into the players' locker room for interviews, a privilege formerly reserved for men.  The NBA followed suit later in the year, with MLB and the NFL not admitting female reporters until later.<ref>Ray Gamache, ''A History of Sports Highlights: Replayed Plays from Edison to ESPN''  (McFarland, Jul 11, 2010) pp148-149</ref>  The two women included in the press at the game in Montreal (which the Wales Conference won 7-1 over the Campbell Conference), were Robin Herman of the ''[[New York Times]]'' and Marcelle St. Cyr of Montreal redio station CKLM.<ref>\"Everyone welcome\", ''Regina Leader-Post'', January 21, 1975, p23</ref>\n*Two would-be IRA bombers, John Kelly and John Stone, were killed when the bomb they are transporting detonates prematurely in Victoria Street, [[Belfast]], Northern Ireland. Only the bombers are killed in the explosion.<ref name=\"cain.ulst.ac.uk\"/>\n\n==[[January 22]], 1975 (Wednesday)==\n*Almost 50 years after it had been proposed, the United States ratified the Geneva Protocol of 1925, a treaty to ban use of poison gases in wartime as President Ford signed the measure.  The U.S. Senate had voted in favor of ratification, 93-0, on December 16, 1974.<ref>\"Started By Coolidge, Treaty Finally Law\",  ''Pittsburgh Press'', January 23, 1975, p1</ref>\n*[[Landsat 2]], the second in a series of American satellites designed to photograph images around the world, was launched from [[Vandenberg Air Force Base]] at 9:56 am.<ref>\"New Satellite Put Into Orbit To Film Earth\", ''Sarasota Herald-Tribune'',  January 23, 1975, p16-A</ref>  Nine days earlier, ERTS-1 (launched on [[July 1972|July 23, 1972]]) was renamed [[Landsat 1]] while in orbit above the Earth.  Landsat 2 was removed from service on February 25, 1982.<ref>Kali Charan Sahu, ''Textbook of Remote Sensing and Geographical Information Systems'' (Atlantic Publishers, 2007) p172</ref>\n*A crowd of 3,000 people, angry about the mishandling of flood relief by Governor Khlai Chitphithak of [[Nakhon Si Thammarat Province]] in [[Thailand]], attacked his official residence and burned it to the ground.  The Governor was able to escape the city and to flee to Bangkok.<ref>Benedict Anderson, ''The Spectre of Comparisons: Nationalism, Southeast Asia, and the World'' (Verso, 1998) p161</ref>\n* [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] will face [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]] in the English Soccer [[Football League Cup]] Final after the former defeat [[Chester City F.C.|Chester City]] 3-2 on the night and 5-4 on aggregate while the latter defeat [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] 1-0 on the night and 3-2 on aggregate in the second leg of their semi final ties. [[Brian Little (footballer)|Brian Little]], for Villa, and [[Colin Suggett]], for Norwich, are the winning goal scorers.<ref>http://www.statto.com/football/stats/results/1975-01-22</ref>\n\n==[[January 23]], 1975 (Thursday)==\n*Dr. [[Andreas Gruentzig]], a heart surgeon at the [[University of Zurich]], successfully inflated a double-lumen balloon [[catheter]] (which he had designed with his wife, assistant to her husband) to dilate the iliac artery of a dog without the side effects of creating an embolism.  Later in the year, on September 24, he would first test the method on a [[coronary artery]], and on September 16, 1976, he would use the technique for the first [[angioplasty]] on a human being.<ref>Adrian Thomas, et al., ''Classic Papers in Modern Diagnostic Radiology (Springer, 2005) p514</ref>\n*U.S. President Gerald Ford signed a proclamation for an eventual three-dollar per barrel fee on imported oil, with a one dollar fee effective on February 1, followed by similar increases on March 1 and April 1.  Ten northeastern States would receive rebates on the fees due to their heavier reliance on imported oil.  Congress voted to delay the increase for 90 days, and a federal court eventually ruled that the President did not have the power to implement fees independently of Congress.<ref>Yanek Mieczkowski, ''Gerald Ford and the Challenges of the 1970s'' (University Press of Kentucky, 2005) pp232-233; \"Ford Boosts Foreign Oil Tariff\", ''Pittsburgh Post-Gazette'', January 24, 1975, p1</ref>\n*The first measurement of astronomical data by an [[Occultation#Occultations by asteroids|asteroidal occultation]] took place as astronomers in North America gathered information from the passage of [[433 Eros]] between the Earth and the star [[Kappa Geminorum]].<ref>Stephen J. Edberg and David H. Levy, ''Observing Comets, Asteroids, Meteors, and the Zodiacal Light'' (Cambridge University Press, 1994) p103</ref>\n*'''Born:''' [[Tito Ortiz]], American martial artist; UFC light heavyweight champion, 2000 to 2003; in [[Santa Ana, California]]\n\n==[[January 24]], 1975 (Friday)==\n[[File:Keith Jarrett-commons.jpg|100px|right|thumb|Jarrett]]\n*[[Jazz]] [[pianist]] [[Keith Jarrett]] played the solo [[improvisation]] '[[The K\u00f6ln Concert]]' at the [[Cologne Opera]].  The live performance became the best-selling piano recording in history.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allaboutjazz.com/php/musician.php?id=7984 |title=Keith Jarrett - Biography |work=[[All About Jazz]] |accessdate=2011-04-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110318092416/http://www.allaboutjazz.com/php/musician.php?id=7984 |archivedate=2011-03-18 }}</ref><ref>David Davies, ''Philosophy of the Performing Arts'' (John Wiley & Sons, 2011) p135</ref>\n*Dr. [[Donald Coggan]] was made the new [[Archbishop of Canterbury]], the administrator of the Church of England.<ref>\"Anglicans Install 101st Archbishop\",  ''Pittsburgh Press'', January 24, 1975, p4</ref>\n*A bomb, planted by the Puerto Rican nationalist group FALN, killed 4 people and injured 58 at the Anglers Club in New York City.  The club was located in the dining room of the Frances Tavern, where George Washington had given his Farewell Address in 1783.  A note from the group said that the bombing was in retaliation for a blast on January 11 in [[Mayag\u00fcez]], which the FALN said had been placed by the CIA, and had killed 2 people and injured 11.<ref>\"N.Y. Bomb Kills 4, Injures 40\",  ''Pittsburgh Press'', January 25, 1975, p1; David N. Bossie, ''Hillary: The Politics of Personal Destruction'' (Thomas Nelson Inc, 2008)</ref>\n*Dr. [[Jeffrey MacDonald]] was arrested at his home in [[Huntington Beach, California]] after being indicted by a federal grand jury in North Carolina, for the February 17, 1970 murders of his wife and two daughters while he had been in the U.S. Army.  Murder charges had been brought against MacDonald but dropped that year for lack of evidence.  MacDonald maintained that the killings had been done by four hippies who chanted \"Acid is groovy, kill the pigs\" before beating him unconscious, and that he had woken to find his family dead.<ref>\"Ex-Army Doctor Arrested Again In Family Killing\", ''Pittsburgh Post-Gazette'', January 25, 1975, p2</ref>  MacDonald was freed on bail a week later.  His case came to trial in 1979, and he was found guilty of murder and sentenced to life imprisonment.  A federal court reversed the conviction in 1980 and MacDonald was freed on bail again, then re-arrested and imprisoned in 1982 after the verdict was upheld.<ref>Jerry Allen Potter and Fred Bost, ''Fatal Justice: Reinvestigating the MacDonald Murders'' (W. W. Norton & Company, 1997)</ref>\n*Only seven months after its launch, the [[Salyut 3]] space station was deorbited by the Soviet Union, a day after the secret test-firing of its defensive cannon.  It was later determined that the firing of the shells had not played a role in taking the station out of orbit.  Salyut 3 re-entered the atmosphere over the Pacific Ocean and burned up.<ref>Ben Evans, ''Foothold in the Heavens: The Seventies'' (Springer, 2010) p286; \"Salyut 3 Ends Mission, Burns in Space\", ''Milwaukee Sentinel'', January 25, 1975</ref>\n*British soldier Thomas Lea died eight months after being injured in an IRA bomb attack in Belfast, Northern Ireland.<ref name=\"cain.ulst.ac.uk\"/>\n*'''Died:''' [[Larry Fine]], 72, who had been one of [[The Three Stooges]] along with [[Moe Howard]] (who would die on May 4) and [[Curly Howard]]\n\n==[[January 25]], 1975 (Saturday)==\n*[[Sheikh Mujibur Rahman]], the first [[President of Bangladesh]], declared a state of emergency and was authorized to rule by decree.  Shortly afterward, the legislature, dominated by the [[Awami League]] party, banned all opposition political parties.<ref>Craig Baxter and Syedur Rahman, ''Historical Dictionary of Bangladesh''  (Scarecrow Press, 2003) p20</ref>\n*Liverpool's defence of the English Soccer F A cup ended in the fourth round when they were defeated 0-1 at Ipswich Town with a goal from [[Mick Mills]]. Eventual cup winners, West Ham were held to a 1-1 draw in their tie against [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]].<ref>http://www.statto.com/football/stats/results/1975-01-25</ref>\n*'''Born:''' \n**[[Ricky Rodriguez]], described by the [[Family International]] cult as the first product of \"[[flirty fishing]]\" and heir apparent to cult leader [[David Berg]] (d. 2005)\n**[[Tim Montgomery]], American track athlete, 2000 Olympic gold medalist; in [[Gaffney, South Carolina]]\n\n==[[January 26]], 1975 (Sunday)==\n*[[Immaculata University]] defeated the [[University of Maryland]] 80-48 in the first nationally televised [[women's basketball]] game in the [[United States]].<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=TYZPAAAAIBAJ&sjid=iQUEAAAAIBAJ&pg=3918,4742960&dq=immaculata&hl=en \"Women Cagers Make TV Debut\"], ''Ocala (FL) Star-Banner\", January 27, 1975, p2B</ref>\n*In what the ''New York Times'' described as [[1975 Thai general election|\"Thailand's freest and fairest national election in history]], the winners were divided among 22 political parties for the 269 seat House of Representatives.<ref>\"Thailand's Free Election\", ''New York Times'', February 3, 1975</ref>  The [[Democrat Party (Thailand)|Democrat Party]] won 72 of the available seats, or roughly 27%, and [[Seni Pramoj]] formed a coalition government that would last only two weeks, before he was replaced by his brother.<ref>Takashi Shiraishi and P. N. Abinales,''After the Crisis: Hegemony, Technocracy and Governance in Southeast Asia'' (Trans Pacific Press, 2005) p28</ref>\n*The [[Order of Australia]] was created.<ref>Christopher McCreery, ''The Order of Canada: its origins, history, and development'' (University of Toronto Press, 2005)</ref>\n*An IRA booby trap bomb, left at the Air Training Corps premises in Belfast, Northern Ireland killed sixteen-year-old cadet, Edward Wilson.<ref name=\"cain.ulst.ac.uk\"/>\n\n==[[January 27]], 1975 (Monday)==\n*The U.S. Senate voted 82-4 to establish its own special committee to investigate the CIA, with Frank Church of Idaho as the chairman.<ref>L. Britt Snider, ''Agency and the hill: the cia's relationship with congress'' (Government Printing Office, Aug 7, 2008) p34</ref>\n\n==[[January 28]], 1975 (Tuesday)==\n*[[Japan]] and the [[Soviet Union]] signed an agreement for a joint venture of drilling for oil on [[Sakhalin Island]], former Japanese territory that became part of the USSR.  In return for funding of the development, Japan would receive \"a significant discount on half of the pumped oil\" for ten years.<ref>Werner D. Lippert, ''The Economic Diplomacy of Ostpolitik: Origins of NATO's Energy Dilemma'' (Berghahn Books, 2010) p169</ref>\n*'''Died:''' \n**[[Anton\u00edn Novotn\u00fd]], 70, President of Czechoslovakia 1957-1968\n**[[Arthur Judson]], 93, artists' manager for New York Philharmonic and Philadelphia Orchestra and a co-founder of the Columbia Broadcasting System\n\n==[[January 29]], 1975 (Wednesday)==\n*The [[Weatherman (organization)|Weather Underground]] bombed the U.S. [[State Department]] main office in [[Washington, D.C.]].<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=_UE0AAAAIBAJ&sjid=x-sFAAAAIBAJ&pg=1310,3707494&dq=weather+underground&hl=en \"State Department Bombed\"], ''Miami News'', January 28, 1975, p1</ref>\n*Seventeen-year-old Robert McCullough, a Catholic, was killed by the [[Ulster Defence Association|UDA]] at his workplace in Belfast, Northern Ireland. The murder was thought to be a random sectarian retaliation for the murder of a teenage Protestant in an IRA bomb three days earlier.<ref name=\"cain.ulst.ac.uk\"/>\n*'''Born:''' [[Sara Gilbert]], American TV actress ([[Roseanne (TV series)|''Roseanne'']]) and panelist ([[The Talk (U.S. TV series)|''The Talk'']]); as Sara Rebecca Abeles in [[Santa Monica, California]]\n\n==[[January 30]], 1975 (Thursday)==\n*A professor of architecture in [[Budapest]] applied to the patent office in [[Hungary]] for his invention, which he called ''Terbeli logikai jatek'' (\"Spatial logic game\")\n[[Rubik's Cube|''B\u0171v\u00f6s Kocka'']] (\"Magic Cube\").  Patent #HU 170,062 was granted on March 28, 1977 to [[Ern\u0151 Rubik]].  <ref>[https://www.wired.com/2009/01/dayintech-0130/ \"Jan. 30, 1975: Rubik Applies for Patent on Magic Cube\", ''This Day in Tech'', ''Wired'' magazine, January 30, 2009</ref> <ref>[https://www.lens.org/lens/patent/040-568-871-927-77X HU 170062 B\"], Lens.org, Queensland University of Technology</ref> <ref>[https://www.hipo.gov.hu/en/node/2744 \"Rubik Ern\u0151: T\u00e9rbeli logikai j\u00e1t\u00e9k\"], Hungarian Intellectual Property Office (in Hungarian)</ref>\n*[[Turkish Airlines Flight 345]] fell into the Sea of Marmara while coming in for a landing in [[Istanbul]].  Electric power at the airport failed as the plane, arriving from [[Izmir]] was descending, and the pilot abandoned the landing, and was circling when the jet fell from the sky.  All 38 passengers and the crew of 4 were killed.<ref>\"Turkish Jet Crashes; 41 Aboard\", ''Milwaukee Sentinel'', January 31, 1975, p1; [http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19750130-0 Aviation Safety Network]</ref>\n*The area around the wreckage of the gunboat [[USS Monitor|USS ''Monitor'']], which had sunk in 1862 off of [[Cape Hatteras, North Carolina]], was designated at the first [[National Marine Sanctuary]] in the United States.  The ship, which had fought the CSS Merrimac in the most famous naval battle of the American Civil War, had become an artificial reef over 110 years prior to its location on August 27, 1973.<ref>Paul R. Clancy, ''Ironclad: The Epic Battle, Calamitous Loss, and Historic Recovery of the USS Monitor'' (McGraw-Hill Professional, 2005) p31; \"Monitor Safe From Modern Ocean Peril\", ''Toledo Blade'', January 30, 1975, p7</ref>\n*The January 31 deadline for [[Draft evasion#Vietnam War|amnesty for draft dodgers]] who fled from the United States during the Vietnam War was extended to March 1.  To that time, about 7,400 of 137,000 eligible had participated in the program, which required one year of volunteer service to avoid prosecution.<ref>\"Ford Extends Clemency Plan 1 Month, ''Milwaukee Sentinel'', January 31, 1975, p3</ref>\n\n==[[January 31]], 1975 (Friday)==\n*The last victim, of the [[serial killer]] known as the \"Skid Row Slasher\", was claimed after Clyde Hay, a 43-year-old cash register repairman, was found dead in his home in Hollywood, California.  Hay was the killer's ninth victim in two months.  The first seven had been transients in Los Angeles.  Two days later, the killer was forced to flee during his next murder attempt, but left a clue that would end his spree. [[Vaughn Greenwood]] would be convicted on nine counts of first degree murder almost two years later.<ref>\"Greenwood, Vaughn Orrin\", in ''The Encyclopedia of Serial Killers'', by Michael Newton (Infobase Publishing, 2006) pp101-102</ref>\n*Twenty-seven people on board the Greek oil tanker SS ''Corinthos'' were killed after their ship was struck by the American freighter ''Edgar M. Queeny''.  The ''Corinthos'' had been docked at [[Marcus Hook, Pennsylvania]], and was  unloading its cargo of crude oil at a dockside refinery operated by [[British Petroleum]], when it was struck by the freighter, which was making a course change.<ref>\"Two Dead, 25 Missing As Ship Rams Tanker\", ''Sarasota (FL) Herald-Tribune'', February 1, 1975, p1</ref>\n*[[Royal Ulster Constabulary|RUC]] Constable George Coulter was shot dead by the IRA while at a mobile Police patrol near [[Dungannon]], Northern Ireland. He is the ninth and last official Northern Ireland troubles related fatality during the month and the only Police Officer killed<ref name=\"cain.ulst.ac.uk\"/>\n*'''Born:''' [[Preity Zinta]], Indian film actress, in [[Shimla]], [[Himachal Pradesh]] state.\n*'''Died:''' \n**[[Bernard Fitzalan-Howard, 16th Duke of Norfolk]], 66, the [[Earl Marshal]] of the United Kingdom who choreographed coronations, funerals and other state occasions\n**[[Ida May Fuller]], 100, former legal secretary and first American to ever receive social security benefits\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Events by month links}}\n\n[[Category:January|1975]]\n[[Category:1975|*1975-01]]\n[[Category:Months in the 1970s|*1975-01]]\n", "name_user": "Mandsford", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eJanuary 30, 1975 (Thursday)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/January_1975"}
{"title_page": "Parra", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{About|the name|other uses|Parra (disambiguation)}}\n'''Parra''' is a Spanish and Portuguese  surname, meaning [[grapevine]] or [[Trellis (architecture)|trellis]],<ref>[https://www.houseofnames.com/parrilla-family-crest \"Parrilla Surname, Family Crest & Coat of Arms], House of Names</ref> for example, a [[pergola]]. It is taken from the word meaning [[latticework]] and the vines raised on it.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://buscon.rae.es/draeI/SrvltConsulta?TIPO_BUS=3&LEMA=parra|title=Diccionario de le lengua Espa\u00f1ola|publisher=Real Academia Espa\u00f1ola}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wordreference.com/definicion/parra|title=parra|publisher=Word Reference}}</ref>\n\n== Etymology and history ==\nAmong [[Sephardi Jews]], the surname is a [[Toponymic surname|toponymic]] from the town of [[La Parra|La Parra, Badajoz]] in [[Spain]], where there was a large [[Spanish Jews|Jewish community]]<ref>{{Cite book|last=\u00c1lvarez, Ana Mar\u00eda L\u00f3pez, and Ricardo Izquierdo Benito.|first=|title=Juder\u00edas y sinagogas de la Sefarad medieval. Vol. 73|publisher=University of Castilla La Mancha|year=2003|isbn=|location=|pages=5}}</ref>[http://www.nameyourroots.com/names/report.pdf?name1=Parra&printed_versi] before their expulsion from the Crowns of [[Crown of Castile|Castile]] and [[Crown of Aragon|Aragon]] by the [[Alhambra Decree]] in 1492.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Melammed|first=Ren\u00e9e Levine|date=April 1995|title=Jane S. Gerber. The Jews of Spain: A History of the Sephardic Experience. New York: Free Press, 1992. xxv, 333 pp.|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1017/s0364009400006577|journal=AJS Review|volume=20|issue=1|pages=219\u2013222|doi=10.1017/s0364009400006577|issn=0364-0094}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Graizbord|first=David|date=2007|title=Joseph P\u00e9rez. History of a Tragedy: The Expulsion of the Jews from Spain. Intro. by Helen Nader. Trans. Lysa Hochroth. Hispanisms 6. Champaign : University of Illinois Press,  2007. xvi + 150 pp. index. append. $35. ISBN: 978-0-252-03141-0.|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1353/ren.2007.0376|journal=Renaissance Quarterly|volume=60|issue=4|pages=1330\u20131332|doi=10.1353/ren.2007.0376|issn=0034-4338}}</ref> Many descendants with the surname<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.delaparrafamily.com/family_website_winery_002.htm|title=About Us|website=www.delaparrafamily.com|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>, some of them ''[[converso]]'',<ref>{{Cite journal|date=December 1998|title=Miriam Bodian. ''Hebrews of the Portuguese Nation: Conversos and Community in Early Modern Amsterdam''. (The Modern Jewish Experience.) Bloomington: Indiana University Press. 1997. Pp. xiii, 219. $35.00|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1086/ahr/103.5.1617|journal=The American Historical Review|doi=10.1086/ahr/103.5.1617|issn=1937-5239}}</ref> went into exile in [[Portugal]] and the [[Netherlands]], especially in [[Sephardic Jews in the Netherlands|Amsterdam]]. In Spain, numerous conversions took place, which is why the surname appears on the lists of the Catholic Church and the [[Inquisition]]. It is believed that the origin of the surname lies in the symbolism of the vine and the grapevine, which for the Jewish people means the [[People of Israel]] that grows and multiplies. Thus the fields of vines were called \"fields of roses\" because [[Israel]] was the \"mystical rose\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.radiosefarad.com/el-origen-de-los-apellidos-parra-habif-javid-nahmias-nahamias-y-espinosa/|title=El origen de los apellidos Parra, Habif (Javid), Nahmias (Naham\u00edas) y Espinosa {{!}} Radio Sefarad|language=es|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\nAt the beginning of the 19th century in the city of [[Buda]], in [[Hungary]], more than half a thousand Sephardic Jews were listed with the surname Parra.\n\n==People with the surname==\n* [[\u00c1ngel Parra (judoka)]] (born 1983), Spanish judoka\n* [[Beatriz Parra Durango]] (born 1940), Ecuadorian classical soprano\n* [[Carolina Parra]] (born 1978), Brazilian musician\n* [[Derek Parra]] (born 1970), U.S. Olympic gold medalist speed skater\n* [[Fabio Parra]] (born 1959), Colombian road cyclist\n* [[Facundo Parra]] (born 1985), Argentine footballer\n* [[Francisco Parra Cap\u00f3]] (1871 \u2013 c. 1945), mayor of Ponce, Puerto Rico, from 1921 to 1923\n* [[Francisco Parra Duper\u00f3n]] (1827\u20131899), Puerto Rican lawyer and banker\n* [[Gabriel Parra]] (1947\u20131988), Chilean drummer of the folk group Los Jaivas, not related to the Parra family (see below)\n* [[Gerardo Parra]] (born 1987), Venezuelan professional baseball player \n* [[Ib\u00e1n Parra]] (born 1977), Spanish footballer\n* [[Joaqu\u00edn Parra]] (born 1961), Spanish footballer\n* [[John Parra]] (born 1974), Colombian road cyclist\n* [[Jos\u00e9 Parra (baseball)]] (born 1972), Dominican baseball player\n* [[Jos\u00e9 Parra Mart\u00ednez]] (1925\u20132016), Spanish footballer \n* [[Juanita Parra]] (born 1970), Chilean drummer of the folk group Los Jaivas, daughter of Gabriel Parra\n* [[Lorenzo Parra]] (born 1978), Venezuelan flyweight boxer\n* [[Manny Parra]] (born 1982), Mexican-American baseball player\n* [[Marco Parra]] (born 1985), Mexican footballer\n* [[Marco Parra S\u00e1nchez]] (born 1969), Peruvian politician\n* [[Morgan Parra]] (born 1988), French rugby union player of Portuguese origin\n* [[Parra family]], Chilean family known for its many artists\n** [[Violeta Parra]] (1917\u20131967), Chilean folk singer\n** [[Nicanor Parra]] (1914\u20132018), Chilean mathematician and poet, brother of Violeta\n** [[Roberto Parra Sandoval]] (1921\u20131995), Chilean folk singer, brother of Violeta\n** [[\u00c1ngel Parra]] (1943\u20132017), Chilean folk singer, son of Violeta\n** [[Isabel Parra]] (born 1939), Chilean folk singer, daughter of Violeta\n** [[Catalina Parra]] (born 1940), Chilean artist, daughter of Nicanor\n** [[Colombina Parra]] (born 1970), Chilean rock musician and singer, daughter of Nicanor\n** [[Javiera Parra]] (born 1968), Chilean rock musician and singer, granddaughter of Violeta\n\n===De la Parra===\n* [[Adolfo de la Parra]] (born 1946), Mexican drummer, a member of Canned Heat\n* [[Alondra de la Parra]] (born 1980), Mexican conductor, sister of Mane de la Parra\n* [[Emo\u00e9 de la Parra]] (born 1955), Mexican actress and academic, aunt of Alondra and Mane de la Parra\n* [[Mane de la Parra]] (born 1982), Mexican singer and actor, brother of Alondra de la Parra\n* [[Marco Antonio de la Parra]] (born 1952), Chilean psychiatrist, writer, and dramatist\n* [[Pim de la Parra]] (born 1940), Surinamese-Dutch film director\n* [[Teresa de la Parra]] (1889\u20131936), Venezuelan novelist\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Surname}}\n[[Category:Portuguese-language surnames]]\n[[Category:Spanish-language surnames]]\n[[Category:Jewish surnames]]\n[[Category:Sephardi Jewish culture in Europe]]\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Parra (Surname)}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{About|the name|other uses|Parra (disambiguation)}}\n'''Parra''' is a Spanish and Portuguese  surname, meaning [[grapevine]] or [[Trellis (architecture)|trellis]],<ref>[https://www.houseofnames.com/parrilla-family-crest \"Parrilla Surname, Family Crest & Coat of Arms], House of Names</ref> for example, a [[pergola]]. It is taken from the word meaning [[latticework]] and the vines raised on it.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://buscon.rae.es/draeI/SrvltConsulta?TIPO_BUS=3&LEMA=parra|title=Diccionario de le lengua Espa\u00f1ola|publisher=Real Academia Espa\u00f1ola}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wordreference.com/definicion/parra|title=parra|publisher=Word Reference}}</ref>\n\n== Etymology and history ==\nAmong [[Sephardi Jews]], the surname is a [[Toponymic surname|toponymic]] from the town of [[La Parra|La Parra, Badajoz]] in [[Spain]], where there was a large [[Spanish Jews|Jewish community]]<ref>{{Cite book|last=\u00c1lvarez, Ana Mar\u00eda L\u00f3pez, and Ricardo Izquierdo Benito.|first=|title=Juder\u00edas y sinagogas de la Sefarad medieval. Vol. 73|publisher=University of Castilla La Mancha|year=2003|isbn=|location=|pages=5}}</ref> before their expulsion from the Crowns of [[Crown of Castile|Castile]] and [[Crown of Aragon|Aragon]] by the [[Alhambra Decree]] in 1492.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Melammed|first=Ren\u00e9e Levine|date=April 1995|title=Jane S. Gerber. The Jews of Spain: A History of the Sephardic Experience. New York: Free Press, 1992. xxv, 333 pp.|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1017/s0364009400006577|journal=AJS Review|volume=20|issue=1|pages=219\u2013222|doi=10.1017/s0364009400006577|issn=0364-0094}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Graizbord|first=David|date=2007|title=Joseph P\u00e9rez. History of a Tragedy: The Expulsion of the Jews from Spain. Intro. by Helen Nader. Trans. Lysa Hochroth. Hispanisms 6. Champaign : University of Illinois Press,  2007. xvi + 150 pp. index. append. $35. ISBN: 978-0-252-03141-0.|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1353/ren.2007.0376|journal=Renaissance Quarterly|volume=60|issue=4|pages=1330\u20131332|doi=10.1353/ren.2007.0376|issn=0034-4338}}</ref> Many descendants with the surname, some of them ''[[converso]]'',<ref>{{Cite journal|date=December 1998|title=Miriam Bodian. ''Hebrews of the Portuguese Nation: Conversos and Community in Early Modern Amsterdam''. (The Modern Jewish Experience.) Bloomington: Indiana University Press. 1997. Pp. xiii, 219. $35.00|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1086/ahr/103.5.1617|journal=The American Historical Review|doi=10.1086/ahr/103.5.1617|issn=1937-5239}}</ref> went into exile in [[Portugal]] and the [[Netherlands]], especially in [[Sephardic Jews in the Netherlands|Amsterdam]]. In Spain, numerous conversions took place, which is why the surname appears on the lists of the Catholic Church and the [[Inquisition]]. It is believed that the origin of the surname lies in the symbolism of the vine and the grapevine, which for the Jewish people means the [[People of Israel]] that grows and multiplies. Thus the fields of vines were called \"fields of roses\" because [[Israel]] was the \"mystical rose\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.radiosefarad.com/el-origen-de-los-apellidos-parra-habif-javid-nahmias-nahamias-y-espinosa/|title=El origen de los apellidos Parra, Habif (Javid), Nahmias (Naham\u00edas) y Espinosa {{!}} Radio Sefarad|language=es|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\nAt the beginning of the 19th century in the city of [[Buda]], in [[Hungary]], more than half a thousand Sephardic Jews were listed with the surname Parra.\n\n==People with the surname==\n* [[\u00c1ngel Parra (judoka)]] (born 1983), Spanish judoka\n* [[Beatriz Parra Durango]] (born 1940), Ecuadorian classical soprano\n* [[Carolina Parra]] (born 1978), Brazilian musician\n* [[Derek Parra]] (born 1970), U.S. Olympic gold medalist speed skater\n* [[Fabio Parra]] (born 1959), Colombian road cyclist\n* [[Facundo Parra]] (born 1985), Argentine footballer\n* [[Francisco Parra Cap\u00f3]] (1871 \u2013 c. 1945), mayor of Ponce, Puerto Rico, from 1921 to 1923\n* [[Francisco Parra Duper\u00f3n]] (1827\u20131899), Puerto Rican lawyer and banker\n* [[Gabriel Parra]] (1947\u20131988), Chilean drummer of the folk group Los Jaivas, not related to the Parra family (see below)\n* [[Gerardo Parra]] (born 1987), Venezuelan professional baseball player \n* [[Ib\u00e1n Parra]] (born 1977), Spanish footballer\n* [[Joaqu\u00edn Parra]] (born 1961), Spanish footballer\n* [[John Parra]] (born 1974), Colombian road cyclist\n* [[Jos\u00e9 Parra (baseball)]] (born 1972), Dominican baseball player\n* [[Jos\u00e9 Parra Mart\u00ednez]] (1925\u20132016), Spanish footballer \n* [[Juanita Parra]] (born 1970), Chilean drummer of the folk group Los Jaivas, daughter of Gabriel Parra\n* [[Lorenzo Parra]] (born 1978), Venezuelan flyweight boxer\n* [[Manny Parra]] (born 1982), Mexican-American baseball player\n* [[Marco Parra]] (born 1985), Mexican footballer\n* [[Marco Parra S\u00e1nchez]] (born 1969), Peruvian politician\n* [[Morgan Parra]] (born 1988), French rugby union player of Portuguese origin\n* [[Parra family]], Chilean family known for its many artists\n** [[Violeta Parra]] (1917\u20131967), Chilean folk singer\n** [[Nicanor Parra]] (1914\u20132018), Chilean mathematician and poet, brother of Violeta\n** [[Roberto Parra Sandoval]] (1921\u20131995), Chilean folk singer, brother of Violeta\n** [[\u00c1ngel Parra]] (1943\u20132017), Chilean folk singer, son of Violeta\n** [[Isabel Parra]] (born 1939), Chilean folk singer, daughter of Violeta\n** [[Catalina Parra]] (born 1940), Chilean artist, daughter of Nicanor\n** [[Colombina Parra]] (born 1970), Chilean rock musician and singer, daughter of Nicanor\n** [[Javiera Parra]] (born 1968), Chilean rock musician and singer, granddaughter of Violeta\n\n===De la Parra===\n* [[Adolfo de la Parra]] (born 1946), Mexican drummer, a member of Canned Heat\n* [[Alondra de la Parra]] (born 1980), Mexican conductor, sister of Mane de la Parra\n* [[Emo\u00e9 de la Parra]] (born 1955), Mexican actress and academic, aunt of Alondra and Mane de la Parra\n* [[Mane de la Parra]] (born 1982), Mexican singer and actor, brother of Alondra de la Parra\n* [[Marco Antonio de la Parra]] (born 1952), Chilean psychiatrist, writer, and dramatist\n* [[Pim de la Parra]] (born 1940), Surinamese-Dutch film director\n* [[Teresa de la Parra]] (1889\u20131936), Venezuelan novelist\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Surname}}\n[[Category:Portuguese-language surnames]]\n[[Category:Spanish-language surnames]]\n[[Category:Jewish surnames]]\n[[Category:Sephardi Jewish culture in Europe]]\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Parra (Surname)}}\n", "name_user": "SefaradSha", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parra"}
{"title_page": "Der Stahlhelm, Bund der Frontsoldaten", "text_new": "{{About|the German first World War ex-servicemen's organization existing from 1918 to 1935|other uses|Stahlhelm (disambiguation)}}\n{{More citations needed|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use American English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Italic title}}\n{{Infobox organization\n| name                = ''Der Stahlhelm,<br/>Bund der Frontsoldaten''\n| logo                = Stahlhelm logo.svg\n| logo_caption        = The logo of the organization\n| image               = Steel helmet (Stahlhelm) banner, R\u00e4bke, Wolfenb\u00fcttel, c. 1930 AD - Braunschweigisches Landesmuseum - DSC04747.JPG\n| caption             = Banner of the R\u00e4bke steel helmet group\n| named_after         = ''[[Stahlhelm]]''\n| merged              = ''[[Sturmabteilung]]''\n| formation           = {{start date|1918|12|25}}\n| founder             = [[Franz Seldte]]\n| founding_location   = [[Magdeburg]]\n| extinction          = {{end date|1935|11|07}} <small>(as Nationalsozialistischer Deutscher frontk\u00e4mpfer-Bund (Stahlhelm))</small>\n| type                = {{Nowrap|Ex-[[Serviceman|servicemen]]'s}} organization\n| purpose             = Maintain peace and order, and foster comradeship founded in the field\n| headquarters        = [[Berlin]]\n| origins             = End of [[World War I]] and the [[German Revolution of 1918\u20131919|German Revolution of 1918]]\n| area_served         = [[Germany]]\n| membership          = 1,500,000\n| membership_year     = 1933\n| language            = [[German language|German]]\n| leader_title        = Federal Leader\n| leader_name         = [[Franz Seldte]]\n| leader_title2       = Federal Deputy Leader\n| leader_name2        = [[Theodor Duesterberg]]\n| key_people          = Honorary Federal Leader<br/>''Generalfeldmarschall'' [[August von Mackensen|August von Mackensen]]\n| publication         = {{Unbulleted list|''Der Stahlhelm''|''Die Standarte''}}\n| subsidiaries        = {{Unbulleted list|''Jungstahlhelm''|''Ringstahlhelm''|''Scharnhorst''|''Stahlhelm-Landsturm''}}\n| affiliations        = ''[[German National People's Party|Deutschnationale Volkspartei]]''\n}}\n'''Der Stahlhelm, Bund der Frontsoldaten''' ({{lang-en|The Steel helmet, League of front-line Soldiers}}), commonly known as '''Der Stahlhelm''' ({{lang-en|The Steel helmet}}), was a German [[World War I|first World War]] ex-[[Serviceman|servicemen]]'s organisation existing from 1918 to 1935. It was part of the \"[[Black Reichswehr]]\" and in the late days of the [[Weimar Republic]] operated as the armed branch of the national conservative [[German National People's Party]] (DNVP), placed at party gatherings in the position of armed security guards (''Saalschutz'').\n\n==History==\n===Weimar Republic (1918\u20131933)===\n[[File:FranzSeldte1933.jpeg|thumb|left|upright=0.7|Franz Seldte in 1933]]\n''Der Stahlhelm'' was formed on December 25, 1918, in [[Magdeburg]], [[Weimar Republic|Germany]], by the factory owner and first World War-disabled [[Military reserve force|reserve]] officer [[Franz Seldte]]. After the [[armistice with Germany|November 11th armistice]], the Army had been split up and the newly established German ''[[Reichswehr]]'' according to the [[Treaty of Versailles]] was to be confined to no more than 100,000 men. Similar to the numerous ''[[Freikorps]]'', which upon the [[German Revolution of 1918\u20131919|Revolution of 1918\u20131919]] were temporarily backed by the [[Council of the People's Deputies]] under Chancellor [[Friedrich Ebert]] ([[Ebert\u2013Groener pact]]), ''Der Stahlhelm'' ex-servicemen's organization was meant to form a [[paramilitary]] organization. \n\nThe league was a rallying point for [[Revanchism|revanchist]] and [[German nationalism|nationalistic]] forces from the beginning. Within the organization a worldview oriented toward the prior [[German Empire|Imperial]] regime and the [[House of Hohenzollern|Hohenzollern]] monarchy predominated, many of its members promoting the ''Dolchstosslegende'' (\"[[Stab-in-the-back legend]]\") and the \"November Criminals\" bias against the [[Weimar Coalition]] government. Its journal, ''Der Stahlhelm'', was edited by Count [[Hans-J\u00fcrgen von Blumenthal]], later hanged for his part in the [[July 20 plot]]. Financing was provided by the ''Deutscher Herrenklub'', an association of German industrialists and [[business magnate]]s with elements of the [[East Elbia]]n landed gentry (''[[Junker (Prussia)|Junker]]''). [[History of the Jews in Germany|Jewish]] veterans were denied admission and formed a separate ''[[Reichsbund j\u00fcdischer Frontsoldaten]]''.\n\nAfter the failed [[Kapp Putsch]] of 1920, the organization gained further support from dissolved ''Freikorps'' units. In 1923 the former DNVP politician [[Theodor Duesterberg]] joined ''Der Stahlhelm'' and quickly rose to Seldte's deputy and long\u2013time rival. From 1924 on, in several subsidiary organizations, veterans with front line experience as well as new recruits would provide a standing armed force in support of the ''Reichswehr'' beyond the 100,000 men allowed. With 500,000 members in 1930, the league was the largest paramilitary organization of [[Weimar Republic]]. In the 1920s ''Der Stahlhelm'' received political support from Fascist Italy's ''[[Duce]]'' [[Benito Mussolini]].<ref>Stanley G. Payne. ''Fascism: Comparison and Definition''. University of Wisconsin Press, 1980. {{ISBN|9780299080648}}. Pp. 62.</ref>\n\n[[File:Bundesarchiv B 145 Bild-P046284, Berlin, Reichspr\u00e4sidentenwahl, Werbung \"Stahlhelm\".jpg|thumb|left|''Der Stahlhelm'' propaganda car in Berlin promoting DNVP nominee Theodor Duesterberg for president of the German Reich in the 1932 election]]\nAlthough ''Der Stahlhelm'' was officially a non-party entity and above party politics, after 1929 it took on an anti-republican and anti-democratic character. Its goals were a German dictatorship, the preparation of a revanchist program, and the direction of local anti-parliamentarian action. For political reasons its members distinguished themselves from the [[Nazi Party]] (NSDAP) as \"German [[Fascism|Fascists]]\". Among their further demands were the establishment of a Greater Germanic People's Reich, struggle against [[Social Democratic Party of Germany|Social Democracy]], the \"mercantilism of the Jews\" and the general liberal democratic worldview, and attempted without success to place candidates favorable to the politics of a renewed [[Drang nach Osten|expansion to the East]].\n\nIn 1929 ''Der Stahlhelm'' supported the \"Peoples' Initiative\" of DNVP leader [[Alfred Hugenberg]] and the Nazis to initiate a [[1929 German referendum|German referendum]] against the [[Young Plan]] on [[World War I reparations]] in order to overthrow the government of Chancellor [[Hermann M\u00fcller (politician)|Hermann M\u00fcller]]. In 1931 they proposed another [[1931 Prussian Landtag referendum|referendum for the dissolution of the Prussian Landtag]]. After both these referenda failed to reach the 50% necessary to be declared valid, the organization in October 1931 joined another attempt of DNVP, NSDAP and [[Pan-German League]] to form the [[Harzburg Front]], a united [[Right-wing politics|right-wing]] campaign against the Weimar Republic and Chancellor [[Heinrich Br\u00fcning]]. However, the front soon broke up and in the first round of the 1932 [[1932 German presidential election|German presidential election]], Theodor Duesterberg ran as ''Der Stahlhelm'' candidate against incumbent [[Paul von Hindenburg]] and [[Adolf Hitler]]. Facing a massive Nazi campaign reproaching him with a non-pure \"[[Aryan race|Aryan]]\" ancestry he only gained 6.8% of the votes cast.\n\n===Nazi Germany (1933\u20131935)===\n[[File:Naziuniformen 1934.jpg|thumb|left|''Der Stahlhelm'' in uniform, [[Circa|ca.]] 1934]]\nAfter the Nazi [[Machtergreifung|seizure of power]] on 30 January 1933, the new authorities urged for a merger into the party's ''[[Sturmabteilung]]'' (SA) paramilitary organization. Seldte joined the [[Hitler Cabinet]] as Reich Minister for Labour, prevailing against Duesterberg. ''Der Stahlhelm'' still tried to keep its distance from the Nazis, and in the run-up to the [[March 1933 German federal election|German federal election]] of 5 March 1933 formed the united conservative \"Black-White-Red Struggle Front\" (''Kampffront Schwarz-Wei\u00df-Rot'') with the DNVP and the [[Agricultural League]], reaching 8% of the votes.\n\nOn 27 March 1933, a SA raid with the intention of disarmament of ''Stahlhelm'' members in [[Braunschweig]], who under the command of [[Werner Schrader]] had forged an alliance with scattered Republican ''[[Reichsbanner Schwarz-Rot-Gold|Reichsbanner]]'' forces. The violent incident initiated by Nazi Minister [[Dietrich Klagges]] and later called ''Der Stahlhelm Putsch'' was characteristic of the pressure applied by the Nazis on ''Der Stahlhelm'' in this period, mistrusting the organization due to its fundamentally [[monarchist]] character. In April Seldte applied for membership in the NSDAP and also joined the SA, from August 1933 in the rank of an ''[[Obergruppenf\u00fchrer]]''.\n\nOn 27 April 1933, Seldte had officially declared ''Der Stahlhelm'' subordinate to Hitler's command. The attempts by the Nazis to integrate ''Der Stahlhelm'' succeeded in 1934 in the course of the \"voluntary\" ''[[Gleichschaltung]]'' ({{lang-en|Synchronization}}) process: the organization was renamed ''Nationalsozialistischer Deutscher frontk\u00e4mpfer-Bund (Stahlhelm)'' ({{lang-en|National Socialist German Combatants' Federation (Stahlhelm)}}) (NSDFBSt) while large parts were merged into the SA as ''Wehrstahlhelm'', ''Reserve I'' and ''Reserve II'' contingents.\n\nThe remaining NSDFBSt local groups were finally dissolved by decree of Adolf Hitler on 7 November 1935. Seldte's rival Duesterberg was interned at [[Dachau concentration camp]] upon the [[Night of the Long Knives]] at the beginning of July 1934, but released soon after.\n\n==Ranks and insignia==\n{{See also|Service Entry Badge of Der Stahlhelm, Bund der Frontsoldaten|label 1=Service Entry Badge}}\n[[File:Stahlhelm (N&H) obverse 1.JPG|thumb|''Der Stahlhelm'' lapel pin, 1918\u20131933]]\n* ''[[Rekrut|Wehrmann]]''\n* ''Oberwehrmann''\n* ''Stabswehrmann''\n* ''[[Gruppenf\u00fchrer]]''\n* ''Feldmeister''\n* ''Oberfeldmeister''\n* ''[[Zugf\u00fchrer (military)|Zugf\u00fchrer]]''\n* ''Oberzugf\u00fchrer''\n* ''[[Kompanief\u00fchrer]]''\n* ''[[Bataillonsf\u00fchrer]]''\n* ''[[Stabsf\u00fchrer]]''\n* ''Regimentsf\u00fchrer''\n* ''[[Brigadef\u00fchrer]]''\n* ''Divisionsf\u00fchrer''\n* ''[[Obergruppenf\u00fchrer]]''\n* ''Bundeshauptmann''\n* ''Bundesf\u00fchrer''\n\n==See also==\n* [[Weimar paramilitary groups]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{Cite book |last=Tauber |first=Kurt |year=1967 |title=[[Beyond Eagle and Swastika]]: German Nationalism Since 1945 |location=Middletown, Conn. |publisher=Wesleyan University Press}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n<!--\n  ===============================================================================\n   WIKIPEDIA IS NOT A COLLECTION OF LINKS. Only a limited number of new links \n   should be added to this article. PLEASE DO NOT ADD external links to sites with\n   information already in the article or in its sources.\n\n   See [[Wikipedia:External links]] and [[Wikipedia:Spam]] for further details\n  ===============================================================================\n-->\n* [http://www.dhm.de/lemo/html/weimar/gewalt/stahlhelm/ Der Stahlhelm, Bund der Frontsoldaten] {{in lang|de}} at the [[Deutsches Historisches Museum|German Historical Museum, Berlin]]\n* [https://www.crwflags.com/fotw/flags/de%7Dstahl.html Der Stahlhelm, Bund der Frontsoldaten] at [[Flags of the World]]\n* {{Internet Archive author|name=Der Stahlhelm, Bund der Frontsoldaten}}\n* {{worldcat id|id=lccn-n89619326}}\n<!-- EDITORS NO