     = {{end date|1935|11|07}} <small>(as Nationalsozialistischer Deutscher frontk\u00e4mpfer-Bund (Stahlhelm))</small>\n| type                = {{Nowrap|Ex-[[Serviceman|servicemen]]'s}} organization\n| purpose             = Maintain peace and order, and foster comradeship founded in the field\n| headquarters        = [[Berlin]]\n| origins             = End of [[World War I]] and the [[German Revolution of 1918\u20131919|German Revolution of 1918]]\n| area_served         = [[Germany]]\n| membership          = 1,500,000\n| membership_year     = 1933\n| language            = [[German language|German]]\n| leader_title        = Federal Leader\n| leader_name         = [[Franz Seldte]]\n| leader_title2       = Federal Deputy Leader\n| leader_name2        = [[Theodor Duesterberg]]\n| key_people          = Honorary Federal Leader<br/>''Generalfeldmarschall'' [[August von Mackensen|August von Mackensen]]\n| publication         = {{Unbulleted list|''Der Stahlhelm''|''Die Standarte''}}\n| subsidiaries        = {{Unbulleted list|''Jungstahlhelm''|''Ringstahlhelm''|''Scharnhorst''|''Stahlhelm-Landsturm''}}\n| affiliations        = ''[[German National People's Party|Deutschnationale Volkspartei]]''\n}}\n'''Der Stahlhelm, Bund der Frontsoldaten''' ({{lang-en|The Steel helmet, League of front-line Soldiers}}), commonly known as '''Der Stahlhelm''' ({{lang-en|The Steel helmet}}), was a German [[World War I|first World War]] ex-[[Serviceman|servicemen]]'s organisation existing from 1918 to 1935. It was part of the \"[[Black Reichswehr]]\" and in the late days of the [[Weimar Republic]] operated as the armed branch of the national conservative [[German National People's Party]] (DNVP), placed at party gatherings in the position of armed security guards (''Saalschutz'').\n\n==History==\n===Weimar Republic (1918\u20131933)===\n[[File:FranzSeldte1933.jpeg|thumb|left|upright=0.7|Franz Seldte in 1933]]\n''Der Stahlhelm'' was formed on December 25, 1918, in [[Magdeburg]], [[Weimar Republic|Germany]], by the factory owner and first World War-disabled [[Military reserve force|reserve]] officer [[Franz Seldte]]. After the [[armistice with Germany|November 11th armistice]], the Army had been split up and the newly established German ''[[Reichswehr]]'' according to the [[Treaty of Versailles]] was to be confined to no more than 100,000 men. Similar to the numerous ''[[Freikorps]]'', which upon the [[German Revolution of 1918\u20131919|Revolution of 1918\u20131919]] were temporarily backed by the [[Council of the People's Deputies]] under Chancellor [[Friedrich Ebert]] ([[Ebert\u2013Groener pact]]), ''Der Stahlhelm'' ex-servicemen's organization was meant to form a [[paramilitary]] organization. \n\nThe league was a rallying point for [[Revanchism|revanchist]] and [[German nationalism|nationalistic]] forces from the beginning. Within the organization a worldview oriented toward the prior [[German Empire|Imperial]] regime and the [[House of Hohenzollern|Hohenzollern]] monarchy predominated, many of its members promoting the ''Dolchstosslegende'' (\"[[Stab-in-the-back legend]]\") and the \"November Criminals\" bias against the [[Weimar Coalition]] government. Its journal, ''Der Stahlhelm'', was edited by Count [[Hans-J\u00fcrgen von Blumenthal]], later hanged for his part in the [[July 20 plot]]. Financing was provided by the ''Deutscher Herrenklub'', an association of German industrialists and [[business magnate]]s with elements of the [[East Elbia]]n landed gentry (''[[Junker (Prussia)|Junker]]''). [[History of the Jews in Germany|Jewish]] veterans were denied admission and formed a separate ''[[Reichsbund j\u00fcdischer Frontsoldaten]]''.\n\nAfter the failed [[Kapp Putsch]] of 1920, the organization gained further support from dissolved ''Freikorps'' units. In 1923 the former DNVP politician [[Theodor Duesterberg]] joined ''Der Stahlhelm'' and quickly rose to Seldte's deputy and long\u2013time rival. From 1924 on, in several subsidiary organizations, veterans with front line experience as well as new recruits would provide a standing armed force in support of the ''Reichswehr'' beyond the 100,000 men allowed. With 500,000 members in 1930, the league was the largest paramilitary organization of [[Weimar Republic]]. In the 1920s ''Der Stahlhelm'' received political support from Fascist Italy's ''[[Duce]]'' [[Benito Mussolini]].<ref>Stanley G. Payne. ''Fascism: Comparison and Definition''. University of Wisconsin Press, 1980. {{ISBN|9780299080648}}. Pp. 62.</ref>\n\n[[File:Bundesarchiv B 145 Bild-P046284, Berlin, Reichspr\u00e4sidentenwahl, Werbung \"Stahlhelm\".jpg|thumb|left|''Der Stahlhelm'' propaganda car in Berlin promoting DNVP nominee Theodor Duesterberg for president of the German Reich in the 1932 election]]\nAlthough ''Der Stahlhelm'' was officially a non-party entity and above party politics, after 1929 it took on an anti-republican and anti-democratic character. Its goals were a German dictatorship, the preparation of a revanchist program, and the direction of local anti-parliamentarian action. For political reasons its members distinguished themselves from the [[Nazi Party]] (NSDAP) as \"German [[Fascism|Fascists]]\". Among their further demands were the establishment of a Greater Germanic People's Reich, struggle against [[Social Democratic Party of Germany|Social Democracy]], the \"mercantilism of the Jews\" and the general liberal democratic worldview, and attempted without success to place candidates favorable to the politics of a renewed [[Drang nach Osten|expansion to the East]].\n\nIn 1929 ''Der Stahlhelm'' supported the \"Peoples' Initiative\" of DNVP leader [[Alfred Hugenberg]] and the Nazis to initiate a [[1929 German referendum|German referendum]] against the [[Young Plan]] on [[World War I reparations]] in order to overthrow the government of Chancellor [[Hermann M\u00fcller (politician)|Hermann M\u00fcller]]. In 1931 they proposed another [[1931 Prussian Landtag referendum|referendum for the dissolution of the Prussian Landtag]]. After both these referenda failed to reach the 50% necessary to be declared valid, the organization in October 1931 joined another attempt of DNVP, NSDAP and [[Pan-German League]] to form the [[Harzburg Front]], a united [[Right-wing politics|right-wing]] campaign against the Weimar Republic and Chancellor [[Heinrich Br\u00fcning]]. However, the front soon broke up and in the first round of the 1932 [[1932 German presidential election|German presidential election]], Theodor Duesterberg ran as ''Der Stahlhelm'' candidate against incumbent [[Paul von Hindenburg]] and [[Adolf Hitler]]. Facing a massive Nazi campaign reproaching him with a non-pure \"[[Aryan race|Aryan]]\" ancestry he only gained 6.8% of the votes cast.\n\n===Nazi Germany (1933\u20131935)===\n[[File:Naziuniformen 1934.jpg|thumb|left|''Der Stahlhelm'' in uniform, [[Circa|ca.]] 1934]]\nAfter the Nazi [[Machtergreifung|seizure of power]] on 30 January 1933, the new authorities urged for a merge into the party's ''[[Sturmabteilung]]'' (SA) paramilitary organization. Seldte joined the [[Hitler Cabinet]] as Reich Minister for Labour, prevailing against Duesterberg. ''Der Stahlhelm'' still tried to keep its distance from the Nazis, and in the run-up to the [[March 1933 German federal election|German federal election]] of 5 March 1933 formed the united conservative \"Black-White-Red Struggle Front\" (''Kampffront Schwarz-Wei\u00df-Rot'') with the DNVP and the [[Agricultural League]], reaching 8% of the votes.\n\nOn 27 March 1933, a SA raid with the intention of disarmament of ''Stahlhelm'' members in [[Braunschweig]], who under the command of [[Werner Schrader]] had forged an alliance with scattered Republican ''[[Reichsbanner Schwarz-Rot-Gold|Reichsbanner]]'' forces. The violent incident initiated by Nazi Minister [[Dietrich Klagges]] and later called ''Der Stahlhelm Putsch'' was characteristic of the pressure applied by the Nazis on ''Der Stahlhelm'' in this period, mistrusting the organization due to its fundamentally [[monarchist]] character. In April Seldte applied for membership in the NSDAP and also joined the SA, from August 1933 in the rank of an ''[[Obergruppenf\u00fchrer]]''.\n\nOn 27 April 1933, Seldte had officially declared ''Der Stahlhelm'' subordinate to Hitler's command. The attempts by the Nazis to integrate ''Der Stahlhelm'' succeeded in 1934 in the course of the \"voluntary\" ''[[Gleichschaltung]]'' ({{lang-en|Synchronization}}) process: the organization was renamed ''Nationalsozialistischer Deutscher frontk\u00e4mpfer-Bund (Stahlhelm)'' ({{lang-en|National Socialist German Combatants' Federation (Stahlhelm)}}) (NSDFBSt) while large parts were merged into the SA as ''Wehrstahlhelm'', ''Reserve I'' and ''Reserve II'' contingents.\n\nThe remaining NSDFBSt local groups were finally dissolved by decree of Adolf Hitler on 7 November 1935. Seldte's rival Duesterberg was interned at [[Dachau concentration camp]] upon the [[Night of the Long Knives]] at the beginning of July 1934, but released soon after.\n\n==Ranks and insignia==\n{{See also|Service Entry Badge of Der Stahlhelm, Bund der Frontsoldaten|label 1=Service Entry Badge}}\n[[File:Stahlhelm (N&H) obverse 1.JPG|thumb|''Der Stahlhelm'' lapel pin, 1918\u20131933]]\n* ''[[Rekrut|Wehrmann]]''\n* ''Oberwehrmann''\n* ''Stabswehrmann''\n* ''[[Gruppenf\u00fchrer]]''\n* ''Feldmeister''\n* ''Oberfeldmeister''\n* ''[[Zugf\u00fchrer (military)|Zugf\u00fchrer]]''\n* ''Oberzugf\u00fchrer''\n* ''[[Kompanief\u00fchrer]]''\n* ''[[Bataillonsf\u00fchrer]]''\n* ''[[Stabsf\u00fchrer]]''\n* ''Regimentsf\u00fchrer''\n* ''[[Brigadef\u00fchrer]]''\n* ''Divisionsf\u00fchrer''\n* ''[[Obergruppenf\u00fchrer]]''\n* ''Bundeshauptmann''\n* ''Bundesf\u00fchrer''\n\n==See also==\n* [[Weimar paramilitary groups]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{Cite book |last=Tauber |first=Kurt |year=1967 |title=[[Beyond Eagle and Swastika]]: German Nationalism Since 1945 |location=Middletown, Conn. |publisher=Wesleyan University Press}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n<!--\n  ===============================================================================\n   WIKIPEDIA IS NOT A COLLECTION OF LINKS. Only a limited number of new links \n   should be added to this article. PLEASE DO NOT ADD external links to sites with\n   information already in the article or in its sources.\n\n   See [[Wikipedia:External links]] and [[Wikipedia:Spam]] for further details\n  ===============================================================================\n-->\n* [http://www.dhm.de/lemo/html/weimar/gewalt/stahlhelm/ Der Stahlhelm, Bund der Frontsoldaten] {{in lang|de}} at the [[Deutsches Historisches Museum|German Historical Museum, Berlin]]\n* [https://www.crwflags.com/fotw/flags/de%7Dstahl.html Der Stahlhelm, Bund der Frontsoldaten] at [[Flags of the World]]\n* {{Internet Archive author|name=Der Stahlhelm, Bund der Frontsoldaten}}\n* {{worldcat id|id=lccn-n89619326}}\n<!-- EDITORS NOTE: Please follow the [[WP:EL]] guideline where possible and consider discussing on the talk page. Thank you. -->\n\n{{Portal bar|1920s|Conservatism|Germany|Society|World War I}}<!-- DO NOT CHANGE OR ADD links without prior consensus, see [[Talk:Der Stahlhelm, Bund der Frontsoldaten]]. -->\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Der Stahlhelm, Bund Der Frontsoldaten}}\n[[Category:Der Stahlhelm, Bund der Frontsoldaten| ]]<!--please leave the empty space as standard-->\n[[Category:1918 establishments in Germany]]\n[[Category:1935 disestablishments in Germany]]\n[[Category:Aftermath of World War I in Germany]]\n[[Category:Clubs and societies in Germany]]\n[[Category:Defunct paramilitary organizations]]\n[[Category:German National People's Party]]\n[[Category:German veterans' organisations]]\n[[Category:Organisations based in Berlin]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 1918]]\n[[Category:Organizations disestablished in 1935]]\n[[Category:Organizations of the German Revolution of 1918\u201319]]\n[[Category:Political advocacy groups in Germany]]\n", "name_user": "Chrism", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNazi Germany (1933\u20131935)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Der_Stahlhelm,_Bund_der_Frontsoldaten"}
{"title_page": "Eugene Siler", "text_new": "{{About||the victim of police brutality|Lester Eugene Siler|the U.S. federal judge|Eugene Edward Siler, Jr.}}\n{{More footnotes|date=January 2011}}\n{{Infobox Congressman\n| name=Eugene Siler\n| image name=Eugene Siler.jpg\n| office= Member of the<br>[[U.S. House of Representatives]]<br>from [[Kentucky]]\n| constituency = {{ushr|KY|8|8th district}} (1955\u201363)<br>{{ushr|KY|5|5th district}} (1963\u201365)\n| term_start = January 3, 1955\n| term_end   = January 3, 1965\n| preceded=[[James S. Golden]]\n| succeeded= [[Tim Lee Carter]]\n| birth_date= {{birth date|1900|6|26|mf=y}}\n| birth_place=[[Williamsburg, Kentucky]], U.S. \n| death_date={{death date and age|1987|12|5|1900|6|26|mf=y}}\n| death_place=[[Louisville, Kentucky]], U.S.\n| profession=[[Lawyer|Attorney]]\n| religion=[[Baptist]]\n| party=[[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n| nationality=American \n|}}\n'''Eugene Siler''' (June 26, 1900 \u2013 December 5, 1987) was a member of the [[United States House of Representatives]] from [[Kentucky]] between 1955 and 1965. He was the only member of the House of Representatives to oppose (by [[Pair (parliamentary convention)|pairing]] against) the [[Gulf of Tonkin Resolution]]. That resolution authorized deeper involvement of the United States in the [[Vietnam War]].\n\n==Life and career==\nSiler, a self-described \"Kentucky hillbilly\", was born in [[Williamsburg, Kentucky]]. Siler was a staunch [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] and hailed from a traditionally Republican region of Kentucky. Siler served in the [[United States Navy]] during [[World War I]] and in the [[United States Army]] as a [[Captain (U.S. Army)|captain]] during [[World War II]].<ref>http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=S000408</ref> His war-time experiences left him, according to [[David T. Beito]], \"cold to most proposals to send American troops into harm's way.\"\n\nSiler graduated from [[University of the Cumberlands|Cumberland College]] in Williamsburg in 1920 and from the [[University of Kentucky]] at Lexington in 1922.<ref>http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=S000408</ref>  He attended law school at [[Columbia University]] and returned to Williamsburg to be a small-town lawyer. Siler was a devout Baptist and became a renowned preacher. He abstained from alcohol, tobacco, and profanity; and, as a lawyer, rejected clients seeking [[divorce]]s or who were accused of alcohol-related crimes.\n\nIn 1945, Siler was elected a [[judge]] of the [[Court of Appeals]] of Kentucky. He refused his 150-dollar expense allotment, instead donating it to a special fund Siler set up for [[scholarship]]s. As a judge, Siler frequently quoted [[scriptures]] from the [[Bench (law)|bench]]. He did the same in his speeches during his 1951 run for governor. This, according to Beito, earned him \"a statewide reputation as a '[[Bible]] Crusader.{{'\"}} Siler was the Republican nominee for [[Governor of Kentucky]] in 1951. He was defeated by Democrat [[Lawrence Wetherby]], who won   346,345 votes (54.6%) to Siler's 288,014 (45.4%).\n\nDuring his tenure in the House of Representatives, which began in 1955, Siler consistently stressed [[social conservatism]]. He sponsored a bill to ban [[liquor]] and [[beer]] [[advertising]] in all interstate media. He stated that permitting these ads was akin to allowing the ''\"harsh hussy\"'' to advertise in ''\"the open door of her place of business for the allurement of our school children\"''. Additionally, he was ''\"100 percent for Bible reading and the Lord's Prayer in our [[Public school (government funded)|public school]]s\"''.\n\nLike his friend and fellow Republican, Representative [[H. R. Gross|Harold Royce Gross]], Siler considered himself a [[fiscal conservatism|fiscal watchdog]]. He opposed [[junket (trip)|junket]]s, government [[debt]], and high spending. Siler made exceptions for his home district, however, by supporting flood control and other federal measures that aided his district.\n\nLike Gross, Siler was a [[Robert A. Taft|Taft]] Republican (or [[Old Right (United States)|Old Right]] Republican) who was opposed to entangling [[military alliance]]s and foreign interventions. Siler was a consistent opponent of [[foreign aid]]; he was one of only two congressmen to vote against [[John F. Kennedy]]'s call up of reserves during the [[Berlin Crisis of 1961|Berlin crisis]]. He supported [[Barry Goldwater]] in [[1964 United States presidential election|1964]] but did not share his [[interventionism (politics)|interventionist foreign policy]] views. This [[non-interventionism]] did not seem to bother his constituents.\n\nSiler did not sign the 1956 [[Southern Manifesto]], and voted in favor of the [[Civil Rights Act of 1957|Civil Rights Acts of 1957]] and [[Civil Rights Act of 1960|1960]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/85-1957/h42|title=HR 6127. CIVIL RIGHTS ACT OF 1957.|work=GovTrack.us}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/86-1960/h102|title=HR 8601. PASSAGE.}}</ref> but cast no vote on the [[Civil Rights Act of 1964]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/88-1964/h128|title=H.R. 7152. PASSAGE.}}</ref>\n\nSiler was critical of U.S. involvement in [[Vietnam War|Vietnam]]. In 1964, after deciding not to seek reelection, he quipped, in jest, that he would run for [[President of the United States|President]] as an antiwar candidate&mdash;he pledged to resign after one day in office after ordering the troops brought home. He considered the [[Gulf of Tonkin Resolution]], which authorized President [[Lyndon B. Johnson|Johnson]] to take \"all necessary steps\" in Vietnam, as a \"buck-passing\" pretext to \"seal the lips of Congress against future criticism.\"\n\nIn 1968, the worsening situation in Vietnam prompted Siler to return to politics, unsuccessfully seeking the Republican [[United States Senate|U.S. Senate]] nomination. Siler ran on a platform calling for withdrawal of all U.S. troops by [[Christmas]]. [[Ernest Gruening]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|D.]]-[[Alaska]]) and [[Wayne Morse]] (D.-[[Oregon|Oreg.]]), the only two U.S. Senators who voted against the Gulf of Tonkin Resolution, were also defeated that year.\n\n==Legacy==\n* In 1985, [[University of the Cumberlands|Cumberland College]], in Siler's hometown of Williamsburg, built a men's residence hall named [https://web.archive.org/web/20070510095827/http://www.ucumberlands.edu/admissions/virtual_tour/siler/ '''Eugene Siler Hall'''].\n\n==See also==\n{{portal-inline|Conservatism}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* [http://hnn.us/articles/28879.html \"The Christian Conservative Who Opposed the Vietnam War\"] History News Network, August 21, 2006 by David T. Beito and Linda Royster Beito\n* [http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=S000408 U.S. Congress profile]\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-ppo}}\n{{Succession box| title=[[Republican nominee for Governor of Kentucky]] | before=[[Eldon S. Dummit]] | after=[[Edwin R. Denney]] | years=[[1951 Kentucky gubernatorial election|1951]]}}\n{{S-par|us-hs}}\n{{Succession box| title=[[U.S. Congressional Delegations from Kentucky|U.S. Representative, Kentucky 8th District]] | before=[[James S. Golden]] | after=seat lost to redistricting | years=January 3, 1955 &ndash; January 3, 1963}}\n{{Succession box| title=[[U.S. Congressional Delegations from Kentucky|U.S. Representative, Kentucky 5th District]] | before=[[Brent Spence]] | after=[[Tim Lee Carter]] | years=January 3, 1963 &ndash; January 3, 1965}}\n{{S-end}}\n{{USCongRep-start|congresses= 84th\u201388th [[United States Congress]]es |state=[[Kentucky]]}}\n{{USCongRep/KY/84}}\n{{USCongRep/KY/84/2}}\n{{USCongRep/KY/84/3}}\n{{USCongRep/KY/85}}\n{{USCongRep/KY/86}}\n{{USCongRep/KY/87}}\n{{USCongRep/KY/88}}\n{{USCongRep-end}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Siler, Eugene}}\n[[Category:1900 births]]\n[[Category:1987 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American judges]]\n[[Category:20th-century American lawyers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:American army personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:American naval personnel of World War I]]\n[[Category:American people of the Vietnam War]]\n[[Category:Baptists from Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Judges of the Kentucky Court of Appeals]]\n[[Category:Kentucky lawyers]]\n[[Category:Kentucky Republicans]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Non-interventionism]]\n[[Category:Old Right (United States)]]\n[[Category:People from Whitley County, Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Republican Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:United States Army officers]]\n[[Category:United States Navy personnel]]\n[[Category:University of Kentucky alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{About||the victim of police brutality|Lester Eugene Siler|the U.S. federal judge|Eugene Edward Siler, Jr.}}\n{{More footnotes|date=January 2011}}\n{{Infobox Congressman\n| name=Eugene Siler\n| image name=Eugene Siler.jpg\n| state=[[Kentucky]]\n| district=[[Kentucky's 8th congressional district|8th]] and [[Kentucky's 5th congressional district|5th]]\n| term=1955&ndash;1963 (8th), 1963&ndash;1965 (5th)\n| preceded=[[James S. Golden]] (8th), [[Brent Spence]] (5th)\n| succeeded= [[Tim Lee Carter]]\n| birth_date= {{birth date|1900|6|26|mf=y}}\n| birth_place=[[Williamsburg, Kentucky]], U.S. \n| death_date={{death date and age|1987|12|5|1900|6|26|mf=y}}\n| death_place=[[Louisville, Kentucky]], U.S.\n| profession=[[Lawyer|Attorney]]\n| religion=[[Baptist]]\n| party=[[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n| nationality=American \n|}}\n'''Eugene Siler''' (June 26, 1900 \u2013 December 5, 1987) was a member of the [[United States House of Representatives]] from [[Kentucky]] between 1955 and 1965. He was the only member of the House of Representatives to oppose (by [[Pair (parliamentary convention)|pairing]] against) the [[Gulf of Tonkin Resolution]]. That resolution authorized deeper involvement of the United States in the [[Vietnam War]].\n\n==Life and career==\nSiler, a self-described \"Kentucky hillbilly\", was born in [[Williamsburg, Kentucky]]. Siler was a staunch [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] and hailed from a traditionally Republican region of Kentucky. Siler served in the [[United States Navy]] during [[World War I]] and in the [[United States Army]] as a [[Captain (U.S. Army)|captain]] during [[World War II]].<ref>http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=S000408</ref> His war-time experiences left him, according to [[David T. Beito]], \"cold to most proposals to send American troops into harm's way.\"\n\nSiler graduated from [[University of the Cumberlands|Cumberland College]] in Williamsburg in 1920 and from the [[University of Kentucky]] at Lexington in 1922.<ref>http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=S000408</ref>  He attended law school at [[Columbia University]] and returned to Williamsburg to be a small-town lawyer. Siler was a devout Baptist and became a renowned preacher. He abstained from alcohol, tobacco, and profanity; and, as a lawyer, rejected clients seeking [[divorce]]s or who were accused of alcohol-related crimes.\n\nIn 1945, Siler was elected a [[judge]] of the [[Court of Appeals]] of Kentucky. He refused his 150-dollar expense allotment, instead donating it to a special fund Siler set up for [[scholarship]]s. As a judge, Siler frequently quoted [[scriptures]] from the [[Bench (law)|bench]]. He did the same in his speeches during his 1951 run for governor. This, according to Beito, earned him \"a statewide reputation as a '[[Bible]] Crusader.{{'\"}} Siler was the Republican nominee for [[Governor of Kentucky]] in 1951. He was defeated by Democrat [[Lawrence Wetherby]], who won   346,345 votes (54.6%) to Siler's 288,014 (45.4%).\n\nDuring his tenure in the House of Representatives, which began in 1955, Siler consistently stressed [[social conservatism]]. He sponsored a bill to ban [[liquor]] and [[beer]] [[advertising]] in all interstate media. He stated that permitting these ads was akin to allowing the ''\"harsh hussy\"'' to advertise in ''\"the open door of her place of business for the allurement of our school children\"''. Additionally, he was ''\"100 percent for Bible reading and the Lord's Prayer in our [[Public school (government funded)|public school]]s\"''.\n\nLike his friend and fellow Republican, Representative [[H. R. Gross|Harold Royce Gross]], Siler considered himself a [[fiscal conservatism|fiscal watchdog]]. He opposed [[junket (trip)|junket]]s, government [[debt]], and high spending. Siler made exceptions for his home district, however, by supporting flood control and other federal measures that aided his district.\n\nLike Gross, Siler was a [[Robert A. Taft|Taft]] Republican (or [[Old Right (United States)|Old Right]] Republican) who was opposed to entangling [[military alliance]]s and foreign interventions. Siler was a consistent opponent of [[foreign aid]]; he was one of only two congressmen to vote against [[John F. Kennedy]]'s call up of reserves during the [[Berlin Crisis of 1961|Berlin crisis]]. He supported [[Barry Goldwater]] in [[1964 United States presidential election|1964]] but did not share his [[interventionism (politics)|interventionist foreign policy]] views. This [[non-interventionism]] did not seem to bother his constituents.\n\nSiler did not sign the 1956 [[Southern Manifesto]], and voted in favor of the [[Civil Rights Act of 1957|Civil Rights Acts of 1957]] and [[Civil Rights Act of 1960|1960]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/85-1957/h42|title=HR 6127. CIVIL RIGHTS ACT OF 1957.|work=GovTrack.us}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/86-1960/h102|title=HR 8601. PASSAGE.}}</ref> but cast no vote on the [[Civil Rights Act of 1964]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/88-1964/h128|title=H.R. 7152. PASSAGE.}}</ref>\n\nSiler was critical of U.S. involvement in [[Vietnam War|Vietnam]]. In 1964, after deciding not to seek reelection, he quipped, in jest, that he would run for [[President of the United States|President]] as an antiwar candidate&mdash;he pledged to resign after one day in office after ordering the troops brought home. He considered the [[Gulf of Tonkin Resolution]], which authorized President [[Lyndon B. Johnson|Johnson]] to take \"all necessary steps\" in Vietnam, as a \"buck-passing\" pretext to \"seal the lips of Congress against future criticism.\"\n\nIn 1968, the worsening situation in Vietnam prompted Siler to return to politics, unsuccessfully seeking the Republican [[United States Senate|U.S. Senate]] nomination. Siler ran on a platform calling for withdrawal of all U.S. troops by [[Christmas]]. [[Ernest Gruening]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|D.]]-[[Alaska]]) and [[Wayne Morse]] (D.-[[Oregon|Oreg.]]), the only two U.S. Senators who voted against the Gulf of Tonkin Resolution, were also defeated that year.\n\n==Legacy==\n* In 1985, [[University of the Cumberlands|Cumberland College]], in Siler's hometown of Williamsburg, built a men's residence hall named [https://web.archive.org/web/20070510095827/http://www.ucumberlands.edu/admissions/virtual_tour/siler/ '''Eugene Siler Hall'''].\n\n==See also==\n{{portal-inline|Conservatism}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* [http://hnn.us/articles/28879.html \"The Christian Conservative Who Opposed the Vietnam War\"] History News Network, August 21, 2006 by David T. Beito and Linda Royster Beito\n* [http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=S000408 U.S. Congress profile]\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-ppo}}\n{{Succession box| title=[[Republican nominee for Governor of Kentucky]] | before=[[Eldon S. Dummit]] | after=[[Edwin R. Denney]] | years=[[1951 Kentucky gubernatorial election|1951]]}}\n{{S-par|us-hs}}\n